<FIRST>u a AM-SunkenTreasure     06-27 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sunken Treasure,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasure Hunters Hope Sunken Ship Will Be 17th Century Galleon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A well-preserved ship believed to be a 17th
century Spanish galleon loaded with gold has been found in 1,500
feet of water near the Florida Keys, according to a salvage company.
   Much of the wooden vessel and its cargo appears to be intact
because of the pressure and temperature of the water.
   ``It's worth a fortune in history.'' Greg Stemm, a Tampa
businessman who hopes to recover the riches, told The St. Petersburg
Times for an article published Wednesday.
   Stemm believes the wreck is the Nuestra Senora de la Merced, a
Spanish Colonial galleon believed to have vanished during the same
hurricane 350 years ago that felled another galleon, the Nuestra
Senora de Atocha.
   The Atocha, laden with gold and silver, was found by treasure
hunter Mel Fisher in 1985, about 50 miles north of Stemm's discovery.
   If Stemm's research proves correct, the wreck he discovered could
hold a treasure worth millions. Stemm, 32, is co-owner of a deep-sea
research company that discovered the sunken vessel in April.
   Seahawk Deep Ocean Technology of Tampa plans to disclose the
details of its remote-camera exploration of the ship on Wednesday.
Archaeologist and treasure hunters are hoping photos prove it's the
Merced, sunk in 1622.
   ``This is just like a time capsule because nothing's been
touched,'' said Dan S. Bagley, a Seahawk director.
   By the end of the summer, the salvors aboard Stemm's 85-foot
research vessel Seahawk will begin a full-scale operation to
retrieve the fragile artifacts and confirm the ship's identity.
   So far, they have discovered a ship's bell and a number of olive
jars that could be filled with wine, food and other commodities. The
project could take up to two years.
   Jim Miller, a state archaeologist, said he has talked to the
salvors about the importance of preserving the artifacts and other
salvageable items from the wreck.
   ``Regardless of what vessel it is, archaeologically, it's an
extremely significant site,'' Miller said. ``If you consider the
historic value, it's very great. The other side of that question is
the monetary value.''
</TEXT>
