<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Tokyo     06-27 0126</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Tokyo,0129</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Shows One-Third Favor Relocating Japan's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in three Japanese favor moving the capital out
of Tokyo because the city of 11.6 million is so crowded, a
government poll released today indicates.
   The poll, conducted by the Prime Minister's office, found 32.6
percent of respondents to favor relocation, with 17 percent opposed.
Another 34.3 percent were undecided and 16.1 percent had no answer.
   Those favoring relocation say it is necessary to correct
overconcentration of the population and solve housing and
transportation problems. Those opposed say businesses should instead
be distributed to places other than Tokyo.
   Nearly 10 percent of Japan's people live in Tokyo.
   The office said it questioned 10,000 people age 20 and older at
random in December.
</TEXT>
