<FIRST>r i PM-AfghanNomads Bjt   06-27 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan Nomads, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koochi Nomads Embody The Spirit Of Afghanistan ^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   TANGIYE POL-I-CHARKI, Afghanistan (AP) _ Bearded, turbaned men
slowly guide their camels, sheep and goats down the mountains and
carry lambs on their shoulders along the rugged path.
   Women in colorful traditional dress and small children run beside
the flock to keep the bleating animals from straying.
   They travel along the potholed road past the artillery guns and
tanks and through this military checkpoint, undisturbed by the
soldiers.
   ``We are free people,'' Habibullah said as he unloaded sacks of
goods from his kneeling camel. ``We are the true spirit of
Afghanistan. Or maybe we're what Afghanistan used to be.''
   Habibullah and the other 15 members of his clan are among the
estimated 2 million Koochi nomads who wander between winter and
summer pastures, pitching their hide tents in fields, building fires
and turning their sheep to graze.
   The Koochis, which means wanderer in the Pashto language, have
traveled the rugged hills and valleys of Afghanstian for thousands
of years. They are ethnic Pathans, like most people in eastern
Afghanistan.
   But unlike their brothers, they never settled down.
   Most still divide their time between the warm lowlands around
Peshawar, Pakistan, and the hilly fields of northern and central
Afghanistan.
   The 11-year-old civil war has made the journey more difficult for
the Koochis. But it hasn't stopped them.
   Kabul, the capital, is a common stopping point for the Koochis,
and their camel trains are as much a part of the urban landscape as
the old bazaars, the military outposts and high-rise apartment
buildings. They halt in Kabul at least once a year to sell camels,
sheep and goats at the meat market.
   ``The Koochi people are an important part of our homeland, an
important part of our tradition. We respect them,'' said Sulaiman
Laeq, the minister of clans and a Politburo member.
   The government has tried to provide them with education, health
and the benefits of progress, such as helping them purchase trucks
and organize a transport union.
   But the Koochis have made it clear they don't want to enter the
modern world, especially if it means owing alligence to the ruling
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan or any other government.
   In the early days of the 1978 Marxist revolution that touched off
the civil war, efforts were made to force the Koochis to stop
wandering and settle in the north.
   The move backfired, said the 37-year-old Habibullah. Some of the
Koochis took up guns and joined the Moslem guerrillas in the battle
against the Soviet-backed government troops.
   ``Some are still fighting, but most have returned,'' Habibullah
said through a translator.
   Laeq and other party officials speak of the mistakes the
government made while trying to bring progress to the Koochis.
   Koochi men had never been asked to serve in the Afghan armed
forces, but that tradition was reversed when the Marxists seized
power 11 years ago in a bloody coup.
   By 1985, the government had modified its policy, formally
exempting the Koochi men from government military service.
   But the war has not been easy for the Koochis.
   They often step on land mines planted by the armed forces and by
the Soviets during their nine-year intervention.
   And their travels frequently take them into battle zones near
Jalalabad, an eastern city under rebel siege since early March.
   ``This war has been very bad for our people,'' says another
Koochi leader, Azizullah. ``The bombs, and rockets and land mines
have killed so many of our people.''
   Occasionally, he says, the rebels demand money to allow them to
pass through guerrilla-controlled territory. Often the roads are
neither open nor safe, forcing the Koochis to travel through the
mountains and turning an easy one-day journey into a dangerous,
two-week affair.
   ``We are our own people. We don't want to be on either side,''
says Azizullah. ``We don't want anyone else's war.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
