<FIRST>u w AM-HUDInsurance 1stLd-Writethru   06-27 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Insurance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0716,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mortgage Company Defaults Subject of HUD Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS new information about ``Robin HUD'' turning over home
to department to cover thefts in new grafs 3-4: ``In addition,'' ADDS three
grafs to elaborate.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development
faces some $650 million in loan defaults from nine mortgage
companies whose practices now are under review, a spokesman said
Monday.
   Three of the nine companies have been suspended indefinitely from
doing business with the department, three others have been placed on
probation for six months and three more face examination of their
projects, HUD documents show.
   In addition, Frank Keating, HUD general counsel-designate, said
escrow agent Marilyn Harrell of Washington and agents in Texas and
Alabama became the first agents that HUD would bar from future
government contracts, The Washington Post said in Tuesday editions.
The cases are part of a nationwide investigation of HUD' dealings
with about 280 closing agents who handled government foreclosures.
   Ms. Harrell, whose diversion of $5.5 million from the
government's primary housing subsidy program earned her the nickname
``Robin HUD,'' turned over her house to the department to cover part
of the thefts and moved out on Monday.
   The mortgage companies have been involved in ``coinsurance
programs'' at HUD, under which they earn lucrative fees for
servicing loans for federally backed housing programs but stand to
lose little if the borrower defaults.
   The mortgage companies have to absorb the first 5 percent of the
loss on the loans, but HUD takes 85 prcent of the remaining loss.
   ``Lenders were underwriting unsound loans, overmortgaging
properties, failing to detect indications of troubled loans in a
timely manner, and were not taking adequate and timely actions to
minimize mortgage defaults and coinsurance losses,'' according to a
HUD inspector general's report issued earlier this year.
   That report estimated that loans worth some $700 million were in
default, but Bill Glavin, a HUD spokesman, said some of the
potential losses have been recovered, lowering the overall liability
to $650 million.
   That represents about 13 percent of the money loaned under the
program, he said.
   The lenders suspended indefinitely were DRG Funding Corp. of
Washington, D.C., Puller Mortgage Associates Inc. of Indianapolis
and Southwest Funding Group of Houston. The three on probation
through Nov. 1 are Benton Mortgage Co. of Knoxville, Tenn., Carnegie
Evans L.P. of Greenwich, Conn., and Citadel Mortgage Co. of San
Antonio, Texas.
   The three lenders under review are American Mortgages Inc. of
Bethesda, Md., Eagle Housing Mortgage Group of Dallas and TRI
Capital Corp. of San Francisco.
   At the beginning of May HUD placed a moratorium on the entire
coinsurance program until Sept. 1 while the agency reviews the
program.
   To preempt a federal eviction, Ms. Harrell, 46, spent the weekend
hauling six truckloads of furniture from the house she purchased
with her own money in 1986, including a white baby grand piano and a
large-screen television set. She moved in with her mother nearby.
   Ms. Harrell said she gave HUD the title to her home in December
when her contract as a closing agent for HUD ran out and agents were
asking about millions missing from her title company. She said she
also had transferred to HUD the deeds to five other houses she paid
for with HUD's money and used for various charities and homeless
families.
   Last week, Ms. Harrell said two vans and a pickup truck used by
her company were seized at her business office in Clinton, Md.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
