<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-ForeignPress Bjt   06-27 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Foreign Press, Bjt,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Uses Imaginative Tactics to Report Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Covering the news in China under the growing
obstacles created by martial law requires more in the way of
imaginative tactics by foreign journalists than derring-do.
   Reporting on China's political crisis has become increasingly
difficult as soldiers and police strictly enforce restrictions on
the press.
   Newsgathering is basically banned under martial law, except for
the infrequent government-orchestrated peasant rally or news
conference.
   But virtually all reporters in the capital and other Chinese
cities ignore the regulations, coming up with their own ways of
getting around martial law.
   ``The most effective trick these days is to act like a dumb
tourist,'' says an Asian photojournalist. ``Wear bright clothes and
shorts, and don't hide your camera.''
   If stopped by security personnel, he says, ``the best defense is
to go on the offense. Ask them some questions. It's better than
trying to run away.''
   Martial law was imposed May 20 in Beijing in a move to quell the
student-led democracy movement that was finally crushed June 4 when
soldiers killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in the capital.
   Under the vaguely worded decree, foreigners are prohibited from
entering or taking pictures at schools, factories or
``organizations''.
   Television networks face the greatest difficulties. Their
equipment makes them easy to spot.
   ``For television, we don't have a story unless we have a picture
that can convey the information,'' says a CBS News official. ``We
get chased away all the time. We're very frustrated at not being
able to shoot pictures.''
   Coverage has been reduced to relying on government-controlled TV
news.
   ``A great deal of what we're doing is recording their material
and reworking it,'' said the CBS official. ``We're very much at
their mercy.''
   Foreign television networks can no longer send segments through
state-run China Central Television to North America or Europe via
satellite.
   They must now somehow get their videotapes to Hong Kong or Tokyo.
   ``We smuggled out our tapes, did the double shuffle with the
cassettes and that sort,'' said Vernon Mann, a correspondent for
Britain's Independent Television Network whose videotape was
``confiscated'' by police after he filmed on a university campus in
Chengdu, central China.
   ``Our piece, which would have greatly upset them, was aired all
over the U.K. (United Kingdom).''
   Mann was expelled from China for the incident.
   Still photographers have an easier time. One wrapped his camera
in a jacket and put the bundle in his bicycle basket, shooting
frames as he passed soldiers guarding intersections.
   Another put aside his complex single-lens reflex camera and
instead went out with the automatic-focus variety so all he had to
do was point and push.
   Most photographers have resorted to taking pictures from cars,
some with darkened windows, as they zip past soldiers on patrol or
troops checking identification.
   One cameraman from a European photo agency took a dramatic shot
through the back window of a taxi of a man in handcuffs being led
away by soldiers. ``One guy saw me, and I just hit my driver on the
back and said, `Let's get out of here!,''' he said.
   Print journalists face more subtle difficulties.
   With most Chinese frightened into silence by widespread arrests,
including the nationally publicized arrest of a man who talked to an
American television crew, reporters' sources are drying up.
   ``I've simply stopped telephoning people,'' said one American
reporter, noting that he and most colleagues assume their phones are
tapped. ``I think of my Chinese contacts first and foremost as
friends and I've stopped making any attempt to contact them.''
   Other journalists discover that acquaintances refuse to meet
them. A German reporter was turned away when he showed up at the
doorsteps of some Chinese friends. He says now he does not even take
notes on the streets, preferring to keep his eyes open and later
write down what he saw.
   The few who do make appointments do so with great caution,
calling from public telephones, instructing friends not to say their
names in phone conversations, making appointments by prearranged
code and meeting sources furtively in discrete locations.
   ``I only move around at night,'' said a Japanese reporter. ``Even
though it's easier for me to blend into a crowd than Westerners, I
still stand out.''
   He says while many people who have helped him have gone
underground, he hasn't stopped seeing people because ``Chinese have
information you can't get otherwise.''
   He, too, says meetings are much harder to arrange. ``You can't
meet people in hotels _ they have secret cameras everywhere,''
referring to footage taken by a hidden camera of a student leader
feasting at the Beijing Hotel.
   Now he finds the only place he can interview people is in his car
_ during the day, when soldiers aren't checking vehicles for
fugitives.
   ``The greatest danger in China now is that the people have lost
their voice,'' he said. ``The reformists and intellectuals are all
gone. China have lost its good-heartedness.''
</TEXT>
