<FIRST>r w PM-EPAFines     06-27 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EPA Fines,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Companies Fined for Failure to Report Toxic Chemical Releases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of companies face nearly $4 million in
fines because they did not report toxic chemical releases under a
citizens' right-to-know law that took effect last year, says the
Environmental Protection Agency.
   The EPA announced its latest enforcement action Monday against
companies that failed to comply with the law, saying that $1.65
million in fines were placed against 42 companies in 20 states.
   The agency previously took action against 43 other companies.
   EPA Administrator William K. Reilly said the agency will continue
to pursue civil penalties against companies that do not comply with
the disclosure law.
   ``We will not allow non-reporting companies to thwart the right
of citizens to find out which toxic chemicals are being released
into their communities,'' said Reilly in a statement.
   The penalties announced Monday ranged from $5,000 to a high of
$262,000 against a California electronics firm, Diceon Electronics,
which allegedly failed to report toxic chemical releases at
facilities in Irvine and Chatsworth, Calif.
   The second highest fine was against International Extrusion
Corp., Waxalachie, Texas, which was assessed a $101,000 penalty.
   Officials from the two companies could not be reached for comment
Monday.
   Nearly 20,000 companies nationwide filed the chemical release
disclosure reports, which covered 1987, before the filing deadline
last July. The statistics recently provided the first detailed
glimpse into the volume of toxic chemicals that are being released
into the air, water and soil by industry each year.
   But the EPA has estimated that about 20 percent of the businesses
subject to the disclosure requirement may not have complied with the
law during the first reporting period.
   The second round of reports covering releases in 1988 are due to
be filed at the end of this month.
   In addition to seeking fines from the 85 companies, the agency
has filed formal notices of noncompliance against more than 1,500
other companies, although no civil penalties in those cases have yet
been sought.
   EPA spokesman Luke Hester said the amount of the fine proposed
against any single company depended on the size of the business,
total quantity of a chemical not reported and quantities
manufactured. Failure to report chemical releases can result in
civil penalties of up to $25,000 a day.
   The companies may appeal the proposed civil penalties and request
a formal hearing.
   The other companies fined in the latest enforcement action were:
   Eyelematic Manufacturing Inc., Watertown, Conn. ($59,000);
Allen's Manufacturing Inc., Providence, R.I. ($5,000); Nyman
Manufacturing Inc., East Providence, R.I. ($17,000); CPC Rexcel,
Inc., Ludlow, Mass. ($17,000); Grinnell Lithographic Co., Inc.,
Islip, N.Y. ($17,000); Harmac Industries, Buffalo, N.Y. ($17,000);
   Decora, Williamstown, N.J. ($17,000); United Wire Hanger Corp.,
Hasbrouck Heights, N.J. ($68,000); Lehigh Press, Pennsauken, N.J.
($25,000); Colonial Processing Inc., Camden, N.J. ($10,000); Reilly
Whiteman, Conshohocken, Pa. ($6,000); Damascus Steel Castings Co.,
New Brighton, Pa. ($5,000); Teledyne-Uasco, Latrobe, Pa. ($17,000);
Johnson Matthey, West Chester, Pa. ($34,000); Falls Manufacturing
Co., Fairless Hills, Pa. ($51,000);
   Chemfax Inc., Gulfport, Miss. ($51,000); LaValley Construction,
Biloxi, Miss. $34,000; BASF Cor., Lowland, Tenn. ($17,000); A &amp; S
Fiberglass Inc., Jacksonville, Fla. ($5,000); Sipi Metal Corp.,
Chicago ($92,000); Metal Lubricants, Harvey, Ill. ($51,000); Park
Rubber, Lake Zurich, Ill. ($17,000);
   Vandervoort, Fort Worth, Texas ($59,000); American Plant Foods,
Galena Park, Texas ($42,000); Southwestern Plating Co., Houston,
Texas ($15,000); St. Louis Paint Manufacturing Co., St. Louis, Mo.
($17,000); Kaw Valley Inc., Leavenworth, Kan. ($15,000); ABC Rail,
Pueblo, Colo. ($68,000); Beringer Vineyard, St. Helena, Calif.
($17,000);
   Integrated Device Technology, Santa Clara, Calif. ($67,000);
Elpower Corp., San Diego ($76,000); Sola-Opthalmics, Phoenix, Ariz.
($25,000); Dolphin Inc., Phoenix, Ariz. $(51,000); Hemet Casting,
Hemet, Calif. ($17,000); Perkin Elmer Corp., Los Angeles ($17,000);
Newport Corp., Fountain Villa, Calif. ($34,000); Matchmaster Dyeing
&amp; Finishing, Los Angeles ($42,000); Rohr Industries Inc., Auburn,
Wash. ($17,000); ESCO Corp., Portland, Ore. ($68,000);
Woodfold-Marco Manufacturing, Forest Grove, Ore. ($17,000).
</TEXT>
