<FIRST>r w PM-Bush     06-27 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Welcomes Former Democrats to the GOP</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Ceremony for Hawke begins 10 a.m. EDT; will be led</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, welcoming five dozen state and
local officials into the GOP, says the political converts are just
part of the ``droves of voters'' being shut out by a left-leaning
Democratic Party.
   Bush, who often extols the virtues of bipartisanship in dealing
with Congress, reached back for some campaign-style rhetoric Monday
at the White House event where the Republicans paraded the
party-switchers.
   ``The Democratic party is leaving droves of voters behind as it
moves over onto the more liberal side, the left side of the
political equation. And now many of those stranded voters have made
a move on their own to the Republican party, our party of family,
faith and the future,'' Bush said.
   Bush had a different sort of White House ceremony on tap today
with plans to greet Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke with full
military honors followed by a private meeting and, in the evening, a
state dinner.
   The emphasis was on politics Monday when the ex-Democrats trekked
through the Oval Office to pose for official pictures with the
president and hear their praises sung in the Rose Garden by Bush,
GOP Chairman Lee Atwater and Rep. Bill Grant of Perry, Fla., who
made his own switch to the GOP in February.
   ``You're tough,'' Grant told the state representatives, judges,
sheriffs, mayors and other officials. At home, he said, ``you're
being accused of being a traitor, turncoat, accused of betraying the
voters by leaving the Democratic Party.''
   Bush praised their political courage and promised to stand
``shoulder to shoulder'' with them as they seek re-election as
Republicans.
   ``The switch is on to the party in sync with the American
principles. The switch is on to the Republican Party,'' said the
president.
   Bush, employing the rhetoric he successfully used to hammer
Democrat Michael Dukakis in the presidential campaign, said
Republicans were moving ``in the right direction.''
   The Democrats are ``on the move, too, to the left and out of the
mainstream,'' he said.
   Atwater, embroiled in controversy recently over a GOP attack on
new House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, called the event ``absolutely the
proudest single moment I've had since taking office.''
   He said the new Republicans were just part of 118 elected
officials who have switched to the GOP ``since my chairmanship
began'' in January.
   ``And I know of no single example of a Republican party official
... who has switched the other way,'' he said.
   Charles Evers, outgoing mayor of Fayette, Miss., and brother of
slain civil rights leader Medgar Evers, said he switched parties
because ``I don't like to be with losers. The Democratic Party is a
loser.''
   Evers added that he didn't want to see an all-white Republican
Party. He said he will try to encourage black voters in Mississippi
to register Republican because blacks are better off with
representation in both parties.
   Dennis Steinberg, an Allenhurst, N.J., dentist and environmental
activist running for the state assembly, was one of only a few
politicians from north of the Mason-Dixon line identified among the
new Republicans.
   He said he changed parties because of Bush's promise to ``make
ending ocean pollution a priority in his administration.''
</TEXT>
