<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDBattlegrounds Bjt   06-27 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Battlegrounds, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Problems May be Everywhere in HUD, Investigators Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abuse and mismanagement may be everywhere in
the Department of Housing and Urban Development, say investigators
who confess they don't know where their probe will be headed next.
   ``We have made the assumption that there is a problem within
every unit within HUD, and until we learn that there isn't, we're
going to assume that there is,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., a member of the congressional panel investigating the
department.
   So far, the investigations have roamed from one unrelated program
to the next and have been shotgunned from one part of the nation to
another.
   A sampling from around the country:
   _In Denver, U.S. Attorney Mike Norton says his office is
investigating allegations that a suspended HUD accountant embezzled
some $1 million in housing funds.
   _In Indianapolis, auditors are trying to account for $176,965
arising from 11 property sales.
   _In Philadelphia, a pair of real estate brokers are awaiting
trial on charges of defrauding HUD of more than $900,000.
   _In Atlanta, U.S. Attorney Robert Barr's office has filed a civil
suit against two Atlanta men the Justice Department says kept
proceeds from HUD real estate closings. The lawsuit, which contends
HUD lost $840,000 in payments and $860,000 in interest, seeks $7.5
million in damages.
   _In the Maryland suburbs of Washington D.C., a private escrow
agent has confessed to stealing more than $5 million from HUD. Her
role was to help the department close on sales of repossessed homes
by signing papers and accepting the buyers' money for the property.
Marilyn Harrell, nicknamed ``Robin HUD'' because she gave some of
the stolen money to the poor, told investigators her operation was
simple: She just didn't give the government its money.
   On Monday, Ms. Harrell turned over her house to the department to
cover part of the thefts. Ms. Harrell and unidentified agents in
Texas and Alabama became the first agents that HUD will bar from
future government contracts, the Washington Post reported today,
quoting Frank Keating, HUD general counsel-designate.
   Investigations involve 11 other private escrow agents around the
country, and as much as $20 million of HUD funds may have been taken
this way, according to Paul Adams, the department's inspector
general.
   On another front, revealed just this week, HUD has moved to halt
losses from a loan program where some $650 million in mortgages are
in default. The department moved swiftly to suspend three mortgage
companies indefinitely, put three others on six-month probations and
review the operations of still three more.
   HUD officials say a certain amount of fraud is to be expected in
a $20 billion government agency involved chiefly in making loans and
giving away money to help people get shelter and aid the nation's
cities.
   But what began quietly as an in-house investigation more than a
year ago has since exploded into charges of influence-peddling,
betrayal and mismanagement by the people who once held the highest
offices in the department.
   Former Secretary Samuel Pierce Jr. has been criticized for his
hands-off style of management. His onetime top aide, Deborah Gore
Dean, invoked the Fifth Amendment when asked about her role in
handing out HUD grants to developers who sometimes paid six-figure
sums to big-name Republicans to get favorable consideration for
their projects.
   Geography made little difference. Money went to projects in New
Jersey as well as those in New Mexico.
   ``The problem was at the top,'' said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
another member of the House committee investigating HUD. ``Deborah
Dean was in charge of America.''
   Shays agreed.
   ``People who were not fit to hold office were in charge of that
agency,'' he said Monday. ``Mr. Pierce had a good resume. He
inherited an agency in disarray and left it worse than he found it.''
   ``There is always a problem in a democratic society of a
push-pull,'' said Frank. ``The people who are trying to politicize a
program are pulling against the people who are trying to run it
non-politically.
   ``The difference with HUD was there were no people with real
authority to run it non-politically, that you had people in charge
at the top who just didn't care about the program.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
