<DOCNO> AP890627-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett-Complaints     06-27 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett-Complaints,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Czar Defends Staff's Experience, Pace of Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar William J. Bennett rejects criticism
that he has hired people inexperienced with drug issues, saying his
assistants understand the problem and what they don't know, he finds
out from his ``kitchen cabinet.''
   ``There's plenty of experience,'' Bennett said in an interview.
``There isn't anybody who knows all of it. All the people here know
various pieces. We call on our colleagues in the government all the
time, certainly on the Hill too.''
   He can call on other experts to fill in some of the gaps, said
Bennett, director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
   ``Calling in the experts is fine,'' he said. ``You don't have to
have everybody on staff. I've been given a fairly small staff and I
have to make it travel a long way.''
   Rep. Lawrence J. Smith, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee's Task Force on International Narcotics, and New
York City's chief narcotics officer said in interviews that Bennett
will have difficulty drawing up a national drug strategy, due in
September, with his current staff.
   The comments echoed criticisms against Bennett by some federal
officials, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   ``He's not going to be able to draw up a comprehensive strategy
... and prevent turf wars and figure out how to minimize duplication
without having people who have worked in the agencies and know how
to do that,'' Smith said.
   ``Bennett himself, without any real drug experience, has
surrounded himself with people who don't have any real drug
experience, and, without that, they're going to be operating in a
vacuum,'' he said.
   Sterling Johnson Jr., New York City's special narcotics
prosecutor, said, ``There is no one that I know of with any real law
enforcement experience on his team.''
   Johnson said Bennett has asked him to join his ``kitchen
cabinet'' of unofficial advisers and he'll probably do so.
   ``I told him that I want him to succeed. If he fails, we all
fail,'' said Johnson.
   John Walters, Bennett's chief of staff, defended the office's
experience, saying more than half of its 60 workers have been sent
there from ``every major federal agency involved in anti-drug
efforts.''
   Some three dozen federal agencies, including the Drug Enforcement
Administration, the Coast Guard and the departments of Education and
Health and Human Services, are part of the war against illegal drugs.
   Some of the officials criticizing Bennett come from agencies that
opposed Congress' creation of his office, which is charged with
scrutinizing their budgets and priorities as it develops a national
strategy.
   That oversight role, as well as traditional rivalry between
agencies, may be responsible for some of the complaints, Walters
said in an interview.
   ``Frankly, I am suspicious of some of the offers for help,
because those take the form of a desire to write the strategy for us
from people in particular agencies, on the Hill and elsewhere,''
Walters said. ``We want competent staff help, but we do not want
someone to do our job for us.''
   Bennett also has generated criticism by deciding not to fill many
permanent positions until his top two deputies are in place,
depending for now on temporary staffers detailed from other agencies.
   His candidates for the deputy slots _ U.S. Marshals Service
Director Stanley Morris for the supply reduction job and Dr. Herbert
Kleber of Yale University for the demand reduction job _ have not
yet been nominated by the White House. Kleber is already on the
payroll as a consultant.
   Bennett said he has urged the White House to act on the
nominations and he presumed the need for thorough background checks
was causing the delay.
   But he added that he consults with both men regularly and the
empty posts will not hinder preparation of an anti-drug strategy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
