<FIRST>r w PM-GermanChemicals     06-27 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-German Chemicals,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Moving Against Firm in Iran Chemical Weapons Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government is taking action
against a German firm that arranged the sale to Iran of chemicals
used in the production of poison gas, according to U.S. officials.
   ``We've been very happy'' with the West German response, one
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told The Associated
Press Monday.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III discussed the sale with
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher during Genscher's visit to
the United States last week, the officials said.
   The officials said they did not have precise details of exactly
what West Germany was doing in the case, which they said involved a
Dusseldorf firm they did not identify.
   The New York Times reported today that the firm had arranged the
sale to Iran of hundreds of tons of thionyl chloride, a chemical
used in the manufacture of mustard gas, by an Indian manufacturer.
   The bulk of the chemicals was not delivered, according to the
Times.
   During the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, Iran complained that its
people and troops were the targets of several gas attacks by Iraq.
   Last winter, U.S. officials accused German firms of helping Libya
built a plant that could be used to produce chemical weapons, though
Libya insisted the plant would be used for pharmaceuticals.
   In response, the Bonn government has proposed legislation to
stiffen export controls and penalties.
</TEXT>
