<FIRST>r a PM-Scotus-DeathList     06-27 1086</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Death List,1116</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Of the some 2,200 convicted killers on death row in the United
States, at least 32 committed their crimes under age 18.
   Texas _ with nine _ has the most death-row inmates who could feel
the effect of Monday's U.S. Supreme Court ruling that the
Constitution's ban on ``cruel and unusual punishment'' does not
cover execution of people who were under 18 when they committed
their crimes.
   According to state officials, here are the people on death row
who were under 18 when they committed their crimes:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ALABAMA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Frederick Lynn, 24, sentenced May 1983 for February 1981 killing
of Marie Driggers Smith during residential burglary. He was 16.
   _Timothy Charles Davis, 28, sentenced July 1980 in the 1978
killing of Avis Alford, slain during holdup at store in which $12
taken. Davis was 17.
   _Pernell Ford, 24, sentenced August 1984 in the December 1983
fatal stabbing of Willie Griffith and her daughter, Linda Griffith
in Jacksonville. He was 17.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ARIZONA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Jesus Jimenez, 19, was sententenced to death Jan. 22, 1988, for
the Nov. 30, 1986, slaying of a 5-year-old Phoenix girl. Jiminez
claimed that voices told him to kill the girl, who was strangled and
stabbed in the breasts, vagina, rectum, mouth and throat. He was 17
when the crime was committed and 18 when he was sentenced.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FLORIDA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Cleo Douglas Lecroy, 26, convicted in shooting deaths of a
couple on a camping trip in Palm Beach County, Jan. 4, 1981. He was
17.
   Sentence was affirmed Oct. 20, 1988, by Florida Supreme Court,
and he is now up for clemency before the governor and six-member
Cabinet.
   _Bernell Hegwood, 19, convicted of killing three Wendy's
restaurant employees during a Broward County robbery May 23, 1987.
He was 17.
   Appeal is pending before state Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GEORGIA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Janice Buttram, 26, convicted in the stabbing death of a young
girl in Whitfield County on Sept. 3, 1980.
   _Jose High, 30, convicted of the kidnapping and murder of a child
April 26, 1976, in Taliaferro County.
   _Alexander Williams, 21, convicted in the kidnapping, rape and
shooting death of a woman in Richmond County on March 4, 1986.
   _Christopher Burger, 29, convicted of murder and kidnapping of
man Aug. 5, 1977, in Wayne County.
   All were 17 at the time of crime, the minimum age in Georgia for
the death sentence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>INDIANA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Paula Cooper, 19, pleaded guilty in April 1986 to the stabbing
murder of Ruth E. Pelke, a bible teacher from Gary, Ind. She was 15.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>KENTUCKY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Kevin Stanford, 25, was sentenced to death for the 1981
abduction and murder of Louisville gas station attendant Baerbel
Poore, 20, who was sexually abused in the gas station's bathroom,
then driven to a wooded area and allowed once last cigarette before
she was shot twice in the head. He was 17.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LOUISIANA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Two juvenile killers on death row:
   _Dalton Prejean, 29, convicted of shooting Louisiana State
Trooper Donald Cleveland during routine traffic stop for a broken
tail light. Prejean was 17 when murder was committed, seven months
after he had been released from reform school for the murder of a
cab driver when he was 13 years old.
   Seventh execution date stayed by 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals pending outcome of cases decided Monday by the U.S. Supreme
Court.
   _Troy Dugar, 18, robbed and murdered Donald L. Williams in 1986
after robbing him of $3 then putting him in trunk of his own car and
starting on a trip. Dugar pulled over to the side of the road,
emptied his revolver into Williams, reloaded and shot him again.
Dugar was convicted on his 16th birthday.
   No execution date set.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MARYLAND:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   James Russell Trimble, sentenced to death for his role in the
1981 gang rape and murder of a teen-age girl in Baltimore County.
Trimble, who was 17 at the time, is mentally retarded.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MISSOURI:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Frederick Lashley, 25, sentenced to death for the 1981 killing
of Janie Tracy, his physically handicapped, 55-year-old foster
mother. He was 17.
   _Heath Wilkins, 20, sentenced to death for the 1985 stabbing
death of Nancy Allen, 26, a Kansas City area liquor store clerk. He
was 16.
   Wilkins was the subject of Monday's U.S. Supreme Court ruling and
has an appeal that challenges his competency pending in Clay County
Circuit Court.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NORTH CAROLINA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Richard Wayne Joyner, 17, sentenced to death for killing a man
with a shotgun during a robbery attempt this year. He was 17 at the
time of the crime.
   _Thomas Mark Adams, 18, sentenced to death for stabbing a
70-year-old woman to death last year. He was 17.
   Both have appeals pending in state court.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PENNSYLVANIA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Kevin Hughes, 27, convicted of luring a nine-year-old girl into
an abandoned house in Philadelphia, raping and strangling her, and
setting her body on fire. Murder was March 1, 1979. Hughes was 16.
   _Percy Lee, 20, stabbed to death a 33-year-old woman and her
17-year-old daughter in a North Philadelphia housing project on Feb.
26, 1986. He was 17.
   An execution warrant has not been signed in either case.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OKLAHOMA:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Scott Allen Hain, 19, convicted of killing two Tulsa restaurant
employees, who were locked in the trunk of a car that was then set
on fire. He was 17.
   _Sean R. Sellers, 20, was convicted of killing his parents and a
convenience store clerk. He was 16.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TEXAS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Joseph Cannon, 29, convicted of the 1977 Bexar County shooting
death of the sister of an attorney appointed to defend him on a
burglary charge.
   _Curtis Harris, 27, convicted of the 1978 Brazos County beating
death of a man who had stopped to help Harris with his stalled car.
   _Efren Ibanez, 26, convicted of strangling a 38-year-old man to
death in El Paso County in 1980 and stealing the victim's car.
   _Gary Graham, 28, convicted of the 1981 robbery-slaying of an
Arizona man in a Houston supermarket parking lot.
   _Robert Carter, 28, convicted of the 1981 robbery-slaying of a
Harris County convenience store clerk.
   _Johnny Garrett, 25, convicted of the 1981 strangulation and rape
of a nun in an Amarillo convent.
   _John Matson, 21, convicted of the abduction-rape-slaying of a
woman in Houston in 1985.
   _Gerald Mitchell, 21, convicted of a 1985 shooting death in
Harris County.
   _Bobby Joe Wills, 22, convicted of the 1985 slaying of a
convenience store clerk in Orange County, Judy Bracewell, 31.
   At the time of the crime, all were 17, the minimum age for which
a death sentence can be given.
</TEXT>
