<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Fence     06-27 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Fence,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Romania Pulling Down Fence on Hungarian Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania is tearing down a barbed wire
fence it had constructed along the Hungarian border in an apparent
bid to stop people from fleeing, the state-run MTI news agency
reported.
   At a human rights conference in Paris last week, even the Soviet
Union criticized its Warsaw Pact ally for putting up the fence.
   ``The `wire curtain' and the concrete pillars were almost
completely removed from Saturday to Monday,'' MTI said Monday.
   Hungarian Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, on a visit to Austria,
said Monday, ``I haven't heard it yet, but the news delights me.''
   Horn called for Romania to re-establish an autonomous region to
safeguard ethnic and cultural rights of its 1.7 million-member
Hungarian minority. Many ethnic Hungarians have fled Romania,
complaining of persecution.
   MTI said the dismantling of the fence was announced by Col. Janos
Pal, commander of Hungarian frontier guards in the Oroshaza
district..
   During the first five months of this year, 3,231 Romanians
crossed illegally into Hungary, Hungarian officials said.
   About 30,000 Romanians have fled to Hungary in recent years
seeking refuge from chronic hardships and discrimination under
President Nicolae Ceausescu.
   Relations between Hungary and Romania have been deterioratating.
   As Communist authorities in Budapest prepare to embrace
multiparty democracy and free elections next year, Ceausescu's
hard-line government is going ahead with plans to raze thousands of
villages to force assimilation.
   MTI reported June 20 that Romania had completed a barbed wire
fence 6{ feet to 8\ feet high along 90 percent of the countries'
common border.
   A subsequent MTI report said Romanian authorities had piled sand
on roads leading to the border, apparently to block traffic, and
border guards had noticed a kind of steel ``car trap.''
   MTI said Romania started building the fence 1{ years ago, but the
pace of construction was speeded up in March.
</TEXT>
