<HEAD>12 Killed in Crash of Commuter Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter plane caught fire just after
takeoff today in the southern city of Kaohsiung, clipped an
apartment building and crashed, killing 12 of the 13 people on
board, officials said.
   The Formosa Airlines twin-prop Cessna 404 had just taken off from
Kaohsiung Airport, about 210 miles south of Taipei, said airline
president Chen Chung-chen. Officials said 10 passengers and two crew
members were killed.
   A 19-year-old student, Chen Chung-ming, was hospitalized in
satisfactory condition as the only survivor, the airline president
said.
   No one in the two-story apartment building was injured, the
official Broadcasting Corporation of China reported.
   It quoted witnesses as saying they heard an explosion before the
airplane crashed into an empty lot near the apartment, crushing a
small truck that did not have anyone inside.
   The aircraft was on a 30-minute flight from the port city to
Pescadores island, officials said.
   There was no immediate word on the cause of the crash.
