<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-27 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Says Federal Mining Agency Violated Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government cleared the way for
strip mining in a national forest in Ohio after a skimpy review and
without independent documentation, congressional investigators say.
   ``No record exists which suggests that the Office of Surface
Mining conducted a thorough analysis'' before deciding a coal
company had a legal right to strip mine in Wayne National Forest,
said a report by the House Interior Committee's mining subcommittee.
   The agency violated its own policy when it determined Belville
Coal Co. could strip mine for coal on 5,440 acres of the
government-protected land in southern Ohio, the report said.
   ``It is improper for the Office of Surface Mining to have based
this decision on considerations other than its stated policy,'' it
concluded. ``It is inappropriate for a decision of this magnitude
... to have been based on a dearth of written independent agency
analysis and supporting agency documentation.''
   Interior Department spokesman John Wright on Monday said a deputy
assistant secretary was reviewing the Wayne Forest determination
``to see what prompted the decision, how it was based.'' The Office
of Surface Mining is part of the Interior Department.
</TEXT>
