<HEAD>Columnist Reprimanded in Gun Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columnist Jack Anderson has rejected a
reprimand he was issued for his ``role in bringing a gun into the
Capitol'' for a television show on terrorism.
   Anderson has said he engineered the plan to smuggle the gun into
the Capitol last month to show a need for better security. He did
not carry in the gun himself.
   The reprimand was issued Monday by a five-member committee of
journalists which provides credentials to reporters who cover
Congress. Anderson, in a response, said, ``With no disrepect
intended, I must reject the reprimand of the standing committee.''
   During a May 24 interview with Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., in Dole's
private office, Anderson pulled from his pocket a gun that had been
concealed in his televison crew's equipment. The incident occurred
during taping for a segment of his TV program and Anderson claimed
it was to demonstrate security breaches in the building.
   It is a felony to bring a firearm onto the Capitol grounds or
into any of the congressional office buildings, and Capitol police
and the U.S. attorney are investigating whether to press charges
against Anderson, said officer Dan Nichols.
