<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-27 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Way Up; Shares Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended sharply higher against the Japanese
yen Tuesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 95.11 points the
previous day, shed 156.61 points, or 0.47 percent, ending the day at
33,469.21 points.
   The dollar closed at 141.23 yen, up 1.05 yen from Monday's
140.18-yen finish. Opening at 141.15 yen, the dollar fluctuated
between 140.90 yen and 141.30 yen.
   Trading was extremely light in the absence of market-affecting
news, said Toru Kanai, foreign exchange analyst with New Japan
Securities Co. ``Trading was almost dead,'' he said.
   ``Japanese investors lost incentives to buy the yen following the
Liberal Democratic Party's election loss on Sunday,'' Kanai said.
   Socialist Party candidate Kinuko Ofuchi defeated the candidate of
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party in a by-election Sunday in
Niigata, northern Japan, winning a seat in Parliament's upper house.
   Japanese investors are gradually unloading yens due to their
pessimism over the Liberal Democrats' prospects in an upper house
election scheduled for July 23, Kanai said.
   On the stock exchange, dealers attributed weaker prices to the
yen's slip against the dollar.
   A dealer with Nikko Securities said Japanese participants
remained on the sidelines and avoided major moves ``mainly because
of the lower yen.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   An overnight loss in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York
also discouraged Japanese investors, he said.
   ``External factors were not favorable enough to prompt buying
incentives,'' the dealer added.
</TEXT>
