<HEAD>Goodwill Tour for Henry Hudson's Half Moon Replica Canceled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first voyage of the replica of Henry
Hudson's 17th century ship has been delayed for about a year because
of the death of the ship's architect in an accident.
   The $1 million Half Moon had been scheduled to set sail July 5 on
a goodwill tour of 10 ports in the Northeast. The trip has been
rescheduled tentatively for next spring, organizers said Monday.
   The Half Moon's architect, Nicholas Benton, 35, of Middletown,
R.I., was killed last Monday when the mast of another ship he was
working on snapped and threw him 75 feet to the ground.
   ``To ensure that Mr. Benton's project is completed in the manner
he intended, we are seeking outside experts to complete the ship,''
said Andrew Hendricks, a New Jersey resident who initiated the
project.
