<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     06-27 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinian Prisoners Reported Killed as Collaborators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian inmate at Israel's desert prison
camp killed two fellow Arabs, and Israel radio said the attacker was
retaliating for the prisoners' alleged collaboration with Israel.
   The killings, discovered today during the morning prisoner count,
raised to four the number of prisoners slain in the last two weeks
at the Ketziot prison in the Negev Desert.
   In Jersualem, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said
the Israeli leader planned to hold the first meeting on his peace
plan in July with Palestinian leaders from the occupied territories.
   Shamir spokesman Avi Pazner denied reports in the Israeli media
that Shamir will meet with supporters of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which has rejected the plan.
   In its report on the overnight prison slayings, Israel radio said
the killer attacked the two victims because he suspected them of
collaborating with Israeli authorities.
   The army confirmed the deaths, but said police were still
investigating the reason for the murders. An army spokesman
identified the victims as Mahmoud Abdul Abedgalla and Ali Hijazi
Taaf, both of the occupied Gaza Strip.
   The spokesman, who may not be identified under military
regulations, said a fellow inmate was arrested and confessed to the
murders. He gave no details on how or exactly why the men were
murdered.
   Last week at the prison, a 23-year-old Palestinian carried the
body of Mohammed Faraj Abu Jadalla out of a tent, threw it in front
of a guard and said he strangled Jadalla because the man
collaborated with Israeli authorities, the news agency Itim said.
   Earlier in the week, another Palestinian, 19-year-old Samir
Mohammed Antiz was found dead in his tent.
   Israel radio said Antiz apparently was killed by fellow prisoners
who accused him of collaborating with the Israeli authorities.
   Also today, a 17-year-old Palestinian died of wounds sustained in
a clash with troops on Saturday, Arab hospital officials and the
army said. The victim, identified as Tarek Salih Awad, was wounded
during a confrontation in the West Bank village of Idna.
   The three deaths today raised to 539 the Palestinian death toll
in the 1{-year-old uprising against Israeli rule. Seventy of the
victims have been killed by fellow Arabs as collaborators.
Twenty-three Israelis also have been slain.
   In the Gaza Strip, troops opened fire on a group of Palestinian
stone-throwers today and wounded 13 people, including four
11-year-olds, Arab hospital officials said.
   An army spokesman said the military was investigating the
incident.
   Also today, Israel radio quoted police as saying that ballistics
tests showed a 20-year-old Bedouin shepherd fatally wounded Friday
was shot by one of seven Jewish settlers held in connection with a
settler raid on a West Bank village.
   Police did not release the name of the accused, the radio said.
   The Haaretz newspaper published a poll showing Israelis are
almost evenly divided on whether settler vigilante raids in reaction
to Arab stone-throwing attacks are justified.
   The poll, conducted by the Tel Aviv-based PORI Institute, said
44.3 percent of the 1,200 Israelis questioned found the attacks
justified and 44.6 percent did not.
   Seven percent said raids should depend on the circumstances, and
4 percent gave no answer. No margin of error for the poll was given.
   In his comments, Pazner said Shamir would begin meetings with
Palestinian leaders from both the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
in July. Israel captured the territories in the 1967 Middle East War
from neighboring Arab states.
   Shamir's plan calls for elections and limited autonomy in the
occupied territories. The PLO and most Palestinian leaders instead
support an independent Palestinian state.
   ``There will be no PLO supporters,'' Pazner said when asked about
news reports that such people would be included. He said Palestinian
leaders have agreed to attend, but he would not reveal their names.
</TEXT>
