<DOCNO> AP890627-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SplittingVenice     06-27 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Splitting Venice,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote to Split Venice In Two Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venetians have decided to stay together,
defeating a referendum that called for divorcing the romantic lagoon
city from a dependent, blue-collar suburb on the mainland.
   The referendum, with balloting on Sunday and Monday, was pressed
for by officials in Mestre, a community that is administratively
part of the city across the causeway but has little in common with
the fabled place of singing gondoliers and smelly canals.
   Mestre politicians say the growing community's needs are
different from those of aging, tourist-choked Venice and that
Mestre's identity is overwhelmed by Venice's fame.
   While citizens of Mestre outnumber the citizens of historic
Venice, 3-1, the measure nevertheless went down to defeat, 58
percent against separation, 42 percent in favor.
   Lacking affordable housing, young Venetians have been steadily
moving out of the lagoon city to Mestre.
   In 1951, historic Venice had 175,000 people while Mestre had
about 50,000.
   In 1987, Venice's population stood at 83,000 while Mestre has
250,000.
   With souvenir stores far outnumbering butcher and grocery shops,
remaining Venetians depend greatly on Mestre for shopping.
   Ten years ago, a group of influential Venetians lobbied for a
similar referendum. That proposal was defeated with more than 72
percent of the voters opposed to separation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
