<FIRST>r a PM-TreatyOak     06-27 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treaty Oak,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Fly In to Help Historic Tree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dallas billionaire H. Ross Perot is offering
advice as well as money, and others have contributed gifts ranging
from flowers to chicken soup to help the historic Treaty Oak recover
from a poisoning attack.
   Concerned people have lent moral support by leaving the tree
get-well messages, bunches of flowers and rock crystals, which some
believe have healing powers. Monday, a votive candle and a can of
cream of chicken soup were among the offerings.
   Meanwhile, an officer on the case said police are taking a
``long, hard look'' at a suspect in the poisoning.
   ``We're getting there,'' said Austin Police Sgt. John Jones. He
said officers are concentrating on someone identified in telephone
tips to make sure the person is a ``legitimate suspect.''
   ``The publicity and the reward tend to bring out everyone,'' said
Jones, who is investigating the case as second-degree felony
criminal mischief.
   Velpar, a powerful herbicide, was poured around the oak's base.
   According to legend, Stephen F. Austin, the father of Texas,
signed a treaty with the Indians under the tree's branches. The
Handbook of Texas, however, gives little credence to that story.
   The tree was admitted to the American Forestry Association's Hall
of Fame in 1927. The live oak is about 50 feet tall, has a 127-foot
limb spread and is 52.5 inches in diameter at chest height.
   The centuries-old live oak has been losing leaves and expending
its reserve energy to replace them.
   City forester John Giedraitis said Monday that Perot, who has
pledged funds to help the tree, told him, ``Don't worry about the
bureaucracy, let's just do it.''
   Perot has recommended using dechlorinated water to mist the
tree's foliage, Giedraitis said.
   ``What we're trying to do is lower the stress on the tree ...
When they (twigs) are cool, they're not under as much stress,'' he
said.
   James Houser, head of a task force that gathered at the oak
Monday and chairman of the Austin Urban Forestry Board, said the
experts would work to come up with a coherent plan of action.
   Task force members are from the U.S. Forest Service, North
Carolina State University, Texas A&amp;M University, University of
Texas, Texas Department of Agriculture, Texas Forest Service, St.
Edwards University, American Society of Consulting Arborists, the
city and Du Pont, maker of Velpar.
   A $10,000 reward for information leading to the conviction of the
poisoner has been offered by Du Pont, and $1,000 has been offered by
the Texas Forestry Association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
