<FIRST>r a PM-Gray-Accountant     06-27 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gray-Accountant,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Reportedly Asked Gray About Philadelphia Accountant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents who met with Rep. William H. Gray
III in recent weeks questioned him about a financially troubled
accountant who had worked for the Democratic congressman, according
to a report.
   In today's editions, The Philadelphia Inquirer quoted an
unidentified source as saying that most of the specific questions
that the agents asked Gray concerned Neil B. Godick, president of
Godick &amp; Co., a Philadelphia accounting firm that filed for
bankruptcy in 1987.
   Godick has been accused of embezzlement by one of the creditors
in the bankruptcy proceedings.
   Gray's attorney, Abbe Lowell, said that Godick worked for Gray at
various times between the late 1970s and 1986 as a personal
accountant, an aide in his congressional office, and a campaign
consultant who helped prepare Federal Election Commission reports.
   Lowell would not talk about what the FBI and Gray discussed, nor
would he confirm that Godick had been mentioned in the interview.
   Gray met first with FBI agents on Memorial Day, triggering
reports that he was under investigation. The reports came while Gray
was making an eventually successful bid to become House majority
whip.
   The Justice Department has said that Gray is not the subject of
an investigation.
   Gray declined to discuss his meeting with the FBI.
   ``I have consistently attacked the leaks that have plagued this
investigation,'' Gray said in a statement released by his office.
``Indeed, I have called for the appointment of an independent
counsel to determine the source of these leaks. Therefore, it would
also be hypocritical of me to comment on the substance of The
Inquirer's story.''
   Godick refused requests for an interview by the newspaper.
</TEXT>
