<FIRST>r a PM-UrbanDolphins     06-27 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Urban Dolphins,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine Biologists Fail To Move Dolphins To Ocean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine biologists and the Coast Guard suspended
efforts to herd two wayward dolphins out of the East River toward
open water because the dolphins showed signs of stress.
   ``The dolphins were getting very excited,'' said Coast Guard
spokesman Jeff Crawley, and the attempts to steer them down river
were not working when they were halted Monday evening.
   Biologists and government officials were to meet today to discuss
other methods to move the white-sided dolphins.
   A lone dolphin was first spotted last Tuesday by staff at
Metropolitan Hospital and students and teachers at an Upper East
Side school. On Monday, the marine biologists trying to move that
dolphin out to sea spotted a second dolphin swimming with the first.
   The Coast Guard, the Okeanos Ocean Research Foundation Inc., the
National Marine Fisheries Service and the state Department of
Environmental Conservation worked to try to herd the white-sided
dolphins to open waters.
   The marine biologists tried to lure the dolphins by placing an
electronic device in the water with a high-frequency sound to
attract them. They had hoped the dolphins would follow their boat
down the East River, through New York Harbor, past the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge to the Atlantic Ocean.
   Sam Sadove, research director at Okeanos, said Sunday the first
dolphin appeared to be in relatively good health, although it was
making sudden changes in its swimming direction, possibly because of
impaired sonar.
   A humpback whale that strayed up the Hudson River on New York's
west side last June turned and swam back out to sea a couple of days
later when several Coast Guard boats gunned their engines, banged
pipes and sounded horns.
</TEXT>
