<FIRST>u i PM-China-Train 1stLd-Writethru a0472 06-27 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Train, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>24 Killed In Shanghai Train Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 24 dead, more details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dynamite exploded in a passenger compartment of a
train outside Shanghai, killing at least 24 people and seriously
injuring 11, official reports said today.
   An official of the city's Foreign Affairs Office described
Monday's blast as an accident. Western diplomats in Shanghai said
there was no indication it was linked to this month's military
suppression of the pro-democracy movement.
   The national television news showed tape of a gaping hole in the
side of the train from the explosion, which it said occurred in a
toilet at the front of a third-class compartment.
   The inside of the train was severely damaged but there was no
fire, reported the Japan's Kyodo News Service
   China's official Xinhua News Agency and government-run television
said the blast was caused by dynamite but gave no details.
   The Foreign Affairs Office official said the blast occurred on a
train bound for Shanghai from Hangzhou, about 110 miles to the
southwest.
   The official, who did not give his name, said an unknown number
of passengers suffered minor injuries and 11 were seriously hurt. He
said 24 people were killed in the blast.
   A local railroad official who identified himself only as Qi said
he was uncertain how many people were on the train. But he said the
capacity of the compartment where the blast occurred was 100 people.
   The television news showed Mayor Zhu Rongji at the crash site
investigating the damage and talking to the injured.
   Explosions on Chinese trains are not uncommon. Sometimes they are
the result of peasants carrying dynamite for their farms or
fireworks for New Year celebrations.
   Shanghai was the scene of major protests before soldiers killed
hundreds of unarmed civilians in Beijing in crushing the
pro-democracy movement.
   On June 6, six people were killed in Shanghai when a train
smashed through a barricade set up by demonstrators.
   Three men convicted of setting fire to the train after the crash
were subsequently executed.
</TEXT>
