<FIRST>u a PM-ToplessCoffee     06-27 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Topless Coffee,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Topless Coffee Shop Owner Vows to Keep Business as Usual</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DICKSON CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dad's Coffee Shop, where java in a
plastic cup will cost you $2, has been fined $16,000 for using
topless waitresses.
   Magistrate John E.V. Pieski on Monday cited Dad's prices as
evidence the adults-only business offers entertainment, for which it
is not zoned.
   ``These are not waitresses who as a necessary and customary
incident to the service of food are friendly. Their primary purpose
and objective is to entertain by their nakedness and by their
fraternization,'' Pieski said.
   The judge also cited Wasley's newspaper ads: ``Noon to 6 p.m. _
Topless Colleen from L.A. (38-24-34),'' read one.
   Thomas Wasley said his business, which opened Feb. 15, will
continue to use topless help while he appeals. The borough said it
probably will seek additional fines.
   ``How can you really say when a girl serves you coffee that it's
entertainment?'' Wasley asked. ``The question here is uniform. ...
Where are they going to draw the line as to what's entertainment and
what's dress?''
   Frank Siderowicz, who led a petition drive against Dad's, said he
will not be happy until the business closes.
   ``We don't want this type of business in Dickson City,'' he said.
``This is small-town America. It's bringing a bad type of people to
Dickson City.''
   About 1,100 of the borough's 6,700 residents signed a petition
circulated outside churches opposing Dad's ``or any other enterprise
of obscene nature.''
   ``It's disgusting,'' Dad's regular Joe Olszewski said of the
ruling. ``A woman giggling is not entertaining. God made them that
way.''
</TEXT>
