<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion     06-27 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Says He's Ready to Release Fusion Grant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Norm Bangerter says the University of
Utah's fusion experiments have gotten enough independent
confirmation for the state to release $5 million for more research.
   However, the Legislature gave control of the $5 million to a
fusion advisory committee, not the governor. Members of the
committee, who are scheduled to meet with university officials on
Thursday, have complained the university has not shared enough
details.
   Experiments at other universities have only partly duplicated the
process by which Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons and British colleague
Martin Fleischmann claimed to have achieved nuclear fusion at room
temperature. Their table-top experiment, announced March 23, raised
prospects of a cheap, safe energy source but was derided by many
physicists.
   ``There's nothing in the legislation that requires it to even be
fusion or to have commercial applications,'' Bud Scruggs,
Bangerter's chief of staff, said Monday. ``The governor won't put
pressure on the committee, but he will say he thinks the legislation
is designed to kick in now.''
   Hugo Rossi, director of the university's fusion research, said he
is eager to go before the committee with a proposal for the $5
million.
   James Brophy, the university's vice president for research, said
a collaboration agreement with General Electric Co. is expected this
week.
   Pons and Fleischmann are in England working on a scientific paper
and will not be at Thursday's meeting, but Pons is expected to
attend a July 11 meeting of the panel.
</TEXT>
