<FIRST>r a PM-StreetShrink     06-27 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Street Shrink,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Down-and-Out Get Their Own Roving Psychologist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merchants weary of panhandlers are
sending a psychotherapist into the streets to talk to the homeless
and ``find out what they want.''
   The 244-member Downtown Merchants Association voted last week to
hire Sarah Howard to strike up conversations with street dwellers
and direct them to the appropriate agency for help.
   Gregory Borrelli, president of the association, said he started
the program to give panhandlers ``hope and dignity.''
   Hope and dignity aside, merchants have been irked by panhandlers,
fearing they are driving away business. The organization had planned
to hire a security guard to police the area but abandoned the idea
for the psychological approach.
   ``What I'm getting from the homeless people is that they don't
feel respected by the mental health community,'' said Howard. She
said she will try to ``find out what they want.''
   Howard, who has a master's degree in psychology, will supervise a
staff of volunteers who will keep tabs on the progress of homeless
people seeking help.
</TEXT>
