<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Palme     06-27 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Seen Following Palme Just Before Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a hot dog stand today
testified that he saw the accused killer of Prime Minister Olof
Palme behind the Swedish leader moments before the shooting.
   The testimony was one of the most damaging to the defendant,
Christer Pettersson, since the trial began June 5. Pettersson has
denied the killing.
   Kiosk owner Ljuvica Nadik said he noticed someone walking 10 to
15 feet behind Palme and his wife, Lisbeth, down a street after they
left a movie theater on Feb. 28, 1986.
   ``I'm certain this is the man who followed them,'' said Nadik, a
Yugoslav immigrant who occasionally was helped by a translator.
   He remembered noticing that Palme had no security guards and
feeling disappointed that the couple were simply dressed.
   Asked how he could identify Pettersson with certainty, Nadik said
``the image is very vivid with me. I've been reminded so many times.
Every time I watch television or look through a newspaper and there
has been something about the Palme murder, I have seen the image of
the man who followed them,'' he said.
   A second witness, Anders Bjorkman, testified that he saw the
shooting from a distance of about 15 yards, but he could not
identify the gunman.
</TEXT>
