<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Khashoggi     06-27 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khashoggi,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khashoggi Refuses Extradition to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi arms dealer Adnan Khashoggi has
refused extradition to face U.S. charges that he helped Ferdinand
and Imelda Marcos plunder the Philippines, a Swiss Justice Ministry
official said today.
   Spokeswoman Ursula Riedel said Khashoggi was asked whether he
would accept immediate extradition, but refused.
   Swiss police arrested Khashoggi in April at the request of the
U.S. Embassy and authorities are considering a U.S. extradition
request.
   They will decide only after Khashoggi's lawyers give formal
reasons for his refusal, expected in about a week, Ms. Riedel said.
   Since Switzerland seems likely to approve extradition and
Khashoggi's lawyers would fight the decision in court, the
international financier probably will spend his 54th birthday, July
25, in a Bern jail cell.
   A U.S. District Court in New York in October indicted Khashoggi,
the Marcoses, five other people and a California bank.
   The ousted Philippines president and his wife are accused of
stealing art and more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury
to buy real estate and art objects.
   Khashoggi allegedly posed as owner of some assets.
   He is charged with racketeering, conspiracy, obstruction of
justice and mail fraud. Racketeering alone carries a penalty of up
to 20 years in jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
