<FIRST>r a PM-RescuedGrad     06-27 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rescued Grad,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Fireman Sees Girl He Saved in 1975</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former fireman traveled from a retirement home
in Las Vegas for the high school graduation of a girl he hadn't seen
since he pulled her from a burning building 14 years ago.
   At Lisa Greene's invitation, Marvin Bunch, 60, watched the
17-year-old receive her diploma Monday at Thomas Jefferson High
School.
   ``I've always wanted to thank him personally and I wanted to show
him that it was really worthwhile saving my life,'' Miss Greene said.
   Bunch said he wept when he got the invitation.
   ``The recognition that Lisa gave me and the efforts of the men in
Engine Company 332 was better than any medal or award that I could
have gotten,'' he said.
   Miss Greene was pulled from a fire that destroyed her Brooklyn
home when she was 3. ``I thought about how I am here today and did
not even know who rescued me. So I decided to find out,'' she said.
   Her family contacted the Fire Department six months ago to trace
records that led to Bunch, who retired in 1979.
   Bunch on Monday recalled rushing into the burning house and
groping through smoke on the second floor.
   ``I stepped and my leg hit something soft. I reached down and I
felt someone's arm,'' he said. He brought the unconscious child out
and she was taken to a hospital, where she underwent skin grafts and
took four months to recover.
   Other firefighters brought out her sisters, Rebecca, 1, and
Trina, 2.
</TEXT>
