<FIRST>u w PM-US-China 1stLd-Writethru a0504 06-27 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Affirms Need For Contacts With Chinese</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 17 grafs new with Bush news kfc, picking up 2nd graf pvs,
``In Asia, etc.; edits pvs to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he would keep trying
to get in touch with the leaders of China but acknowledged he had
not been able to make contact in the last few weeks.
   Bush, at a White House news conference, said he had still not
received a telephone call from Beijing despite his efforts to
discuss the recent turmoil in the world's most populous nation.
   But Bush said there have been ``some exchange of views'' at a
lower level, And he stressed that the Chinese ambassador here, Han
Xu, has had easy access to senior U.S. officials.
   Bush first disclosed his inability to make contact at a news
conference last week. He appealed publicly for a show of clemency,
but executions proceeded.
   In his remarks, Bush was mildly critical of moves by the Chinese
to suspend Peace Corps visits to the country.
   ``That's too bad,'' he said, ``One of the things that moved
reform is contacts with Americans. I don't want to see those
contacts cut off.''
   Bush again avoided any heavy denunciation of the arrests and
executions in China. ``I reiterate my desire not to do damage to the
people themselves.''
   He said U.S. contacts with China had promoted economic reform in
the country. ``Someday we will move the process of political reform
forward,'' he said.
   In the meantime, he said 30,000 Chinese now studying here will be
``going back there with a sense of what democracy and freedom is all
about.''
   He said U.S. ties had helped China move out of a period of
cultural isolation and that ``this relationship is important.''
   Repeatedly, Bush said good relations with Beijing are in the U.S.
interest. But he did not respond to two questions asking him to give
specific examples.
   ``At this moment,'' Bush said, ``it's impossible to have normal
relations for very obvious reasons. But I am going to do my level
best to find a way to see improvement there.''
   And yet, the president said he could not ``dictate'' to the
Chinese who should be leading the country.
   Since Army troops fired on students June 3-4 in Tiananmen Square
the leadership of the government and the Communist party has been
revised to remove leaders who showed some sympathy for democratic
reform movements.
   Bush, who headed the U.S. liaison office in Beijing and claims
expertise in Chinese affairs, said he could not have predicted the
recent turn of events.
   But, he said, ``I guess the lesson is to go forward as best you
can'' and ``to hold high the banner of values you believe in.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, in a speech Monday night
in New York, was optimistic about long-term prospects for democracy.
   ``In Asia, as in Europe, a new order is taking shape,'' Baker
said in a speech summarizing Bush Administration policy on Asia.
``While the rites of passage will be painful _ China proves that _
it is an order full of promise and hope.''
   ``We and some other nations have suspended business as usual,''
Baker said. ``But we and the rest of the world must not let our
revulsion at this repression blind us to pressure for reform.''
   Baker spoke for 25 minutes before 1,000 guests at a black-tie
dinner of the Asia Society, a private group dedicated to improving
American understanding of Asia.
   He outlined a proposal for a new association of Asian countries
to increase trade and investment and handle other regional issues
ranging from cultural affairs to the environment.
   Baker said he plans to seek input on the form such an
organization might take during a trip to Asia that starts July 3.
   Baker will stop in Tokyo to help plan multinational economic aid
for the Philippines. In Brunei, he will attend the annual meeting of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, an economic organization
of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and
Thailand.
   Japan's new foreign minister, Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, who met with
Bush earlier Monday, spoke at the dinner before Baker.
   He stressed the need for America ``to maintain a strong
political, economic and military presence and commitment to the
region.''
   Mitsuzuka also called China's ``path toward isolation''
regrettable and appealed to China's leaders to ``govern in a spirit
of reconciliation and restraint.''
   Meanwhile, 11 Americans were detained Monday by Chinese officials
in Kunming and charged with distributing religious tracts, said Adam
Shub, a State Department spokesman.
   The Americans were believed to be members of an evangelical
Christian group, the Latter Rain Ministry of Litchfield, Ill.
   A U.S. diplomat from the American consulate in Chengdu was
investigating.
   In the past, Americans who distributed religious tracts have been
fined and asked to leave.
</TEXT>
