<FIRST>u w PM-US-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0455 06-27 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hails Progress in US-Soviet Ties; Experts Urge Push For START
Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 11 grafs new with Bush comments today; picking up 4th graf
pvs, bgng, ``But it....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JON KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today said the Soviet Union
knows ``we want to move forward'' on a nuclear weapons reduction
treaty and applauded Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev for visiting
Western Europe.
   The president spoke to reporters a day after five former
secretaries of state and defense urged the administration to push
for the treaty but warned that the United States does not know
enough about Kremlin intentions ``to justify extraordinary political
or economic concessions.''
   Bush said he had no timetable for a first summit meeting with
Gorbachev but said such a meeting did not need to wait for a major
treaty agreement between the superpowers.
   ``I don't think it should be something to sign, but I'd like to
think that the governing criterion would be that the world would see
the meeting as successful, something good coming out of it,'' Bush
said.
   Bush, speaking in general terms about arms negotiations with the
Soviets, said ``they know we want to move forward with START,'' an
acronym for Strategic Arms Reduction Talks.
   ``I feel comfortable,'' about the pace of improvements in
U.S-Soviet ties, Bush said, adding that a number of medical and
cultural exchanges had helped improve the relationship.
   ``We're coming closer on some of these broad, broad-scale
objectives,'' Bush said. ``All I want to say is I think the
relationship is going in the right general direction albeit we have
tremendous differences with the Soviet Union still.''
   Bush applauded Gorbachev's recent visits to West Germany and
England and said he did not expect the Kremlin ``to be uptight''
about his upcoming visit to Poland, a Warsaw Pact ally of the
Soviets.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev goes to Western Europe and he is well received; I
will go to Eastern Europe and I will be well received,'' Bush said.
   The report released Monday and signed by the five secretaries and
six other ex-officials also counseled Bush to show restraint on
developing space-based defenses.
   It concluded that Gorbachev is more inclined than any of his
predecessors to reach accords with the United States that further
Western interests.
   But it added that U.S. knowledge of current and future Kremlin
policy was ``too problematical to justify extraordinary political or
economic concessions which we would otherwise not consider.''
   James Schlesinger, secretary of defense in the Nixon
administration, criticized the Soviet leader for agreeing last week
to resume arms aid to Iran. He said it showed Gorbachev is still
seeking ``marginal advantage'' over the West and in that respect
``failing the test.''
   Still, the report urged the administration to push hard to
complete the treaty to reduce long-range bombers, missiles and
submarines by 30 to 50 percent. After a seven-month recess, the Bush
administration resumed negotiations last week in Geneva.
   At the same time, the United States and its NATO allies are
negotiating with the Warsaw Pact in Vienna to reduce troops, tanks,
artillery and other non-nuclear armories in Europe.
   The report said completion of a strategic arms reduction treaty
``will make it easier for the United States and its allies to obtain
large and asymmetrical reductions in conventional arms, and should
not wait on success in the latter.''
   Gorbachev already has made ``especially significant'' commitments
to cut more men and arms than the West and to shift the role of
Soviet troops toward defense, the report said.
   ``I do worry,'' said Harold Brown, who was secretary of defense
in the Carter administration, ``if START is pushed to the back
burner it will not get done at all. That would be a big mistake.''
   Schlesinger and Brown, who held a joint news conference, were
joined in the report by former Defense Secretary Melvin R. Laird and
former Secretaries of State Cyrus R. Vance and Edmund S. Muskie.
   The other ex-officials who issued the report were David Abshire,
Michael Blumenthal, Arthur H. Hartman, Richard Helms, Peter Peterson
and Thomas Watson.
   On space-based defenses, they said the United States should be
willing to recommit itself for 10 years to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty and discuss with the Soviets what kind of tests for a
space-based defense are permitted.
   This could have the effect of constraining the program undertaken
by former President Reagan to develop a shield against Soviet
ballistic missiles combining sophisticated technology and nuclear
weapons in space.
   However, the report also suggested the 1972 treaty could be
amended or a new one concluded with the Soviets through negotiations.
</TEXT>
