<FIRST>u i PM-WGermany-Iran     06-27 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WGermany-Iran,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Checking Allegations of U.S. Company's Deal With Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are checking U.S.
allegations that a West German company was involved in the sale of
chemicals aimed at producing poison gas for Iran, the Foreign
Ministry confirmed today.
   West German officials also had asked Iran to recall a Bonn-based
diplomat allegedly linked to the suspected chemicals deal but he had
already left the country, the ministry said.
   A ministry spokesman, Hans Schumacher, said the request to have
the diplomat recalled was based on U.S. information about his
suspected links to the chemicals purchase.
   ``The person in question has not worked at the (Iranian) Embassy
for some time and will not resume his duties there,'' Schumacher
said.
   Schumacher did not say when the Iranian diplomat was asked to
leave or identify him by name.
   Informed sources in Bonn, who requested anonymity, identified him
as Seyed Karim Ali Sobhani.
   Another Foreign Ministry spokesman confirmed that federal
officials are taking steps to investigate the U.S. allegations. ``We
were informed by the Americans about this last week,'' said Rainer
Mueller, a ministry spokesman for Middle East affairs.
   Mueller was replying to a query about a report in The New York
Times today that a Duesseldorf company had acted as a broker to sell
of tons of thionyl chloride to a manufacturer in India.
   The chemical can be used to make mustard gas, and was intended
for use by Iran, the report said. It said the bulk of the chemicals
was not delivered.
   ``We have notified the appropriate departments to take the
necessary steps'' for an investigation, Mueller said in a telephone
interview.
   Mueller declined to name the company being investigated.
   The Iranian diplomat, Sobhani, was allegedly involved in the case
of a West German national who was arrested in July 1988 in the
United States for attempting to ship thiodiglycol, a precursor for
mustard gas, to Iran via Singapore and Karachi, Pakistan.
   The West German, Peter Walaschek, later pleaded guilty to
violating U.S. export laws and said he purchased the chemicals at
the request of Sobhani.
   Walaschek fled a halfway house where he was confined, and U.S.
officials said in May that they believe he returned to West Germany.
   Late last year, U.S. officials accused West German firms of
helping Libya to build a chemical weapons plant south of Tripoli.
Libya said the plant was to make pharmaceuticals, not weapons.
   Following a lengthy investigation, officials arrested Juergen
Hippenstiel-Imhausen, the former head of Imhausen-Chemie company, in
connection with the Libyan deal. His case is still pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
