<FIRST>u i PM-SovietSub     06-27 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Sub,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recator Accident May Have Contaminated Soviet Submarine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leak in the nuclear power system of a
Soviet submarine probably contaminated the vessel but not the
environment, a Norwegian expert said today.
   The submarine, built in the 1960s, billowed smoke and steam when
its reactor's cooling system broke down Monday, 70 miles from the
coast of northern Norway.
   Soviet officials say there was no radiation leak. They say the
reactor was shut down and no one was injured.
   But Knut Gussgard, acting chairman of Norway's Committee on
Peacetime Nuclear Accidents, said pieced-together details of the
accident aboard the Echo-II Class submarine show a reactor cooling
circuit most likely leaked radioactive water and steam into the
vessel.
   Gussgard, from the Norwegian Nuclear Energy Safety Authority,
said by telephone that too little information is available to judge
the effect of such radiation on the crew.
   Just before Monday's accident, submarine Capt. V. Ovisjinnkov was
quoted as telling the Soviet publication Smena that Soviet nuclear
submarine crews are poorly trained, know little about procedures and
can handle fewer than half the situations they should master.
   It was the second Soviet submarine accident in three months. On
April 7, an advanced Mike Class nuclear submarine sank 207 miles
away in the Norwegian Sea. Forty-two Soviet sailors died. No
radiation was reported.
   Last week, the Soviet cruise liner Maxim Gorky rammed the ice
pack off Norway. None of the 950 passengers were hurt.
   Johan Baarli, of Norway's Institude for Radiation Hygiene, said
preliminary water and air tests show no radiation from the Echo II
accident.
   ``But the tests would not measure radiation aboard ship,'' Baarli
said in an interview.
   Reports said that with its reactor being kept cool with fresh
water pumped from a Soviet escort vessel, the damaged submarine was
sailing toward its home port in the northern Soviet Union.
   ``We don't like the idea of them having to cool the reactor with
water from another ship. Even with the reactor shut down, if it
loses all cooling the afterheat of the reactor could be enough to
cause problems,'' said Gussgard.
   Officials of this NATO member nation have criticized Moscow's
slowness in warning them of potential danger and express concern
about general safety of Soviet submarines.
   Oslo's Defense Minister Johan Joergen Holst called Monday for a
special agreement requiring the Soviets to inform Norway of
dangerous situations near its coast.
   A Soviet Embassy spokesman told the newspaper Dagbladet today
that the Soviets regretted the delay but had not considered the
accident threatening enough to warrant a warning.
   Norway is concerned that 100 nuclear submarines operating out of
the Soviet North Fleet base on the Kola Peninsula, just over
Norway's northern border, may be dangerous even in peacetime.
   The submarines, including about 30 of the older Echo II design,
regularly pass through and patrol a narrow, strategically important
corridor to the North Atlantic that follows Norway's coast, a
Norwegian defense spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0079 </DOCNO>
