<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TropicalStorm 3rdLd-Writethru a0478 06-27 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Storm, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0478,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remnants of Tropical Storm Dump Torrential Rains on Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with morning traffic conditions,
Louisiana tornado; PICKS UP 12th graf pvs, `The storm ...' DELETES outdated
20th graf pvs, `Houston traffic ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remnants of Tropical Storm Allison battered
the Gulf Coast today with torrential rain, sending streams and
bayous over their banks, turning roads into canals and killing at
least one person.
   Before it was downgraded to a tropical depression early today,
the first named storm of the Atlantic hurricane season also was
blamed for the partial collapse of the roof at Northline Mall in
Houston and for the capsizing of a tugboat in Galveston Bay. No
serious injuries were reported in those incidents.
   The slow-moving storm swept ashore Monday about 60 miles
southwest of Houston. Forecasters said rainfall eventually might be
measured in feet.
   ``We hope it won't become a reality but it is a possibility,''
Ron Stagno of the National Weather Service in Houston.
   No relief was expected until late today because the system was
moving so slowly _ only 6 mph to the north.
   During the morning rush hour, high water closed both major
highways into Houston from the north, and freeway underpasses and
service roads were littered with abandoned vehicles.
   ``It's a helpless feeling,'' said stranded motorist Miles Nye.
``There's nothing you can do. You just watch the water moving up.''
   Some underpasses had as much as 15 or 20 feet of water. An empty
city bus stuck in an underpass near downtown was barely visible in
the water.
   At 5 a.m., the poorly defined center of the depression was about
50 miles north of Houston.
   Maximum sustained winds dropped to 35 mph with 45 mph gusts along
the eastern Texas-western Louisiana coast, the National Hurricane
Center in Coral Gables, Fla., said. Maximum sustained winds must be
at least 39 mph for a depression to be a named tropical storm.
   More than 10 inches of rain fell in the Houston area during the
24 hours that ended early today, the weather service said. ``The
main thing is the rain,'' said meteorologist Larry Vannozzi. ``It's
a heavy rainmaker.''
   The heavy rain and flooding extended into southwestern Louisiana,
where a tornado overturned trailers in rural Hackberry today. In
Texas, authorities reported a tornado Monday evening at Smithpoint
and Double Bayou.
   The storm was blamed for the fatal traffic accident of a
46-year-old Port Neches man Monday evening, police said.
   Rain fell at an inch per hour in some areas and deluges were
expected to continue today into east Texas and southwest Louisiana.
   Hardest hit areas were along the Texas coast although damage
appeared to be minor, confined to downed power lines and some roof
shingles blown away. Damage from high water also was reported.
   Flash-flood warnings were in effect for the coastal counties
south of Houston while the rest of southeast Texas was under a
flash-flood watch.
   ``It's starting to come up pretty fast,'' Don Best, of Danbury in
Brazoria County, said as his family tried to save household
belongings from rising waters. ``We're trying to put our furniture
up as fast as we can.''
   In east Houston, fire department airboats were used to evacuate
dozens of residents of two apartment complexes bordering a bayou.
   ``It doesn't look like there's going to be any relief,'' fireman
Lester Tyra said. ``The only way out is with an airboat.''
   Allison was upgraded to a tropical storm Monday morning. The
storm had its origins in Hurricane Cosme, which moved from the
Pacific Ocean across Mexico last week. The Atlantic hurricane season
runs from June to November.
   In Galveston Bay, the capsized tugboat sent a barge loaded with
benzene aground in the Houston Ship Channel. Three people escaped
serious injury and the barge was not believed to be damaged, Coast
Guard spokesman Mark Kennedy said.
   ``It may be able to ride out the storm aground,'' Kennedy said.
``These are fairly soft and sandy bars and reefs so maybe it won't
be a problem.''
   Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co. at one point reported 30,000
customers without electricity.
   The University of Houston, Rice University and Texas Southern
University were among schools to cancel classes.
