<FIRST>u i PM-India-USPilots 2ndLd-Writethru   06-27 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-US Pilots, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0542,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Releases American, West German Pilots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with West German comment, freed
pilots leaving India; picks up 7th pvs, ``Indian officials ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today released two American
and two West German pilots 10 days after they were detained and
questioned for flying over restricted airspace, U.S. and West German
diplomats said.
   ``I can confirm that the four pilots ... were unconditionally
released on Tuesday,'' said a U.S. Embassy official who cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   The State Department has identified the Americans as Frank Haile
Jr. of Dallas and Carson Gilmore of Rocksprings, Texas.
   A West German Embassy official said two Germans, whom he
identified only by their last names as Kuhlmann and Kuffner, also
were released today.
   ``I can confirm that the two Germans left this morning at 11.26
a.m. for Bahrain in their Beechcraft plane,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   U.S. diplomats in New Delhi refused to disclose more information
about the Americans or their whereabouts, citing the U.S. Privacy
Act.
   The Americans also were flying a Beechcraft Bonanza, in formation
with the West Germans, when Indian air force fighters forced them
down June 16 for intruding into restricted airspace in western
Gujarat state, Defense Ministry officials said.
   Indian officials said the planes had deviated 310 miles from
their prescribed course and had come close to a defense airfield in
Bhuj, 500 miles southwest of New Delhi.
   The airspace over Bhuj, near the Pakistan border, is closed to
commercial air traffic.
   Civil aviation authorities cleared the planes to fly from New
Delhi to Bahrain via Bombay.
   Haile, 57, the owner and president of a Dallas-based engineering
firm, had departed with Gilmore from Addison airport more than four
weeks ago on an around-the-world trip.
</TEXT>
