<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-27 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Fight Police; Threaten to March to North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national student group said today it
will defy a government ban and march to communist North Korea to
attend a youth festival.
   Other students hurled rocks and firebombs at riot police on two
campuses Monday. Official Yonhap news agency said 15 students were
arrested.
   The chairman of the radical National Council of Student
Representatives told a news conference he expects 15,000 students to
congregate at Seoul's Hanyang University for a march Friday, the eve
of the festival.
   ``We've not given up hope to go to North Korea,'' said Im
Chong-suk.
   The World Youth Festival will be held in North Korea's capital,
Pyongyang, July 1-8.
   Prosecutors confirmed they issued warrants Monday for the arrest
of Im and two other leaders of the radical student group, charging
them with violating the National Security Law by talking on the
telephone with North Korean students. The law forbids communication
with people in an ``anti-state'' body. Im was undeterred. He said
South Korean students plan to draft a joint communique with North
Korean students and, if they cannot get to Pyongyang, details will
be arranged through third countries using telephones and facsimile
machines.
   Students holding valid passports and those studying overseas are
being encouraged to try to get to Pyongyang through third countries,
he said. The Seoul government says any who attend without notifying
the government or a South Korean Embassy can be prosecuted.
   Seoul accuses Pyongyang of using the festival to stir up
dissident movements in South Korea _ a charge the Noth Korean
government denies. The festival is a political and sports event
attended mostly by youths from the Third World and communist bloc.
   At Hanyang University Monday, fighting erupted when 200 students
screaming anti-government slogans and hurling rocks and firebombs
attacked riot police blocking campus gates.
   About 500 visored police ringed the campus and stopped outsiders
from entering. Student leaders said some students from the provinces
already were inside.
   In provincial Taegu city, police fired tear gas to disperse 500
students from three schools who attacked them with firebombs and
rocks outside Yongnam University, according to Yonhap.
   The South Korean agency said 15 students were arrested.
   South and North Korea have been bitter rivals since their land
was divided at the end of World War II. North Korea invaded the
south in 1950 and the three-year Korean War left more than l million
dead on both sides. A truce was never signed and enmity deepened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
