<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Khomeini     06-27 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Khomeini,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Urge Khomeini's Son to Run in Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 Iranian legislators are
urging the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's son, Ahmad, to run for
parliament, Tehran Radio reported today.
   Iranian opposition groups claim the move is to head off an open
power struggle between radicals led by Ahmad Khomeini and so-called
pragmatists headed by Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of the Majlis, or
parliament. Rafsanjani is the only announced candidate in the July
28 presidential election.
   ``We call upon your excellency to be in the Majlis ... to become
a cause of strength, encouragement and guidance for this important
pillar of legislation in the arena of the country's decisions,''
said a letter signed by 205 deputies, the radio said.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the daily Tehran
Times as saying the deputies suggested Ahmad Khomeini become speaker
of the 270-seat legislature if he wins an election in Rafsanjani's
Tehran constituency. The radio and agency were monitored in Nicosia.
   Rafsanjani will have to relinquish his seat to run for the
presidency. But no date has been set for the by-election.
   There has been growing speculation that the politically ambitious
Ahmad, 43, would declare himself a candidate to run against the
powerful Rafsanjani.
</TEXT>
