<FIRST>u a PM-OilSpill-RI     06-27 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill-RI,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harbor Pilot Says He Radioed Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A harbor pilot today said he radioed
three warnings to the World Prodigy to change course before the
tanker ran aground and spilled 420,000 gallons of oil.
   But the pilot, David G. Leonard, told a Coast Guard-National
Transportation Safety Board hearing he could not be certain the
message was received because there was a lot of radio interference
at the time.
   The 533-foot Greek tanker hit a reef at the mouth of Narragansett
Bay on Friday after failing to wait for the pilot to board and guide
the vessel into port.
   Rhode Island authorities are investigating whether the ship was
past the point at which a pilot is required by state law.
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete testified that hours after the spill, the
captain admitted he was at fault. The governor said he asked Iakovos
Georgoudis, ``Why were you in that location which requires a pilot
to be on board?''
   ``He said, `That was my mistake,''' DiPrete said. ``He made no
bones about it.''
   Leonard said he first talked with the ship about 4:30 p.m. Friday
and that the tanker reported it was about 2{ miles from the point
where Leonard was supposed to meet it and guide it into the bay.
   ``My first words were, `Aim the vessel more toward the (Brenton
Light) tower,''' Leonard testified. ``That was not correct, so I
said `Head the vessel more toward the tower.' Then I said, `Keep the
red buoy on your starboard bow.'''
   The pilot said he repeated the warning twice but could not be
sure it got through.
   ``That transmission, there was interference with a lot of
small-boat traffic,'' Leonard said. He said that interference is
common during the summer and called on the Coast Guard to do
something to free up vital radio channels.
   Most of the spilled oil had dispersed or evaporated by today and
no longer posed much of a threat to the shore, officials said.
   ``It's going to flush out by itself,'' said Coast Guard Petty
Officer Mike Gilmore, overseeing the cleanup at Hull Cove in
Jamestown.
   There had been reports of lobsters killed and several small birds
found dead, but officials said those did not appear to be widespread.
   State Attorney General James O'Neil seized the ship's records and
has begun criminal investigation. He planned to convene a grand jury
on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0087 </DOCNO>
