raise a good point, and it isn't _ my affection for our oldest
grandson is _ it's just that he's there and he's ready. And he plays
ball and he does stuff, and we're going to the Orioles game
tomorrow, I think it is. And so _ but it is not discriminatory, it
is not discriminatory.
   Yeah.
   Q. Mr. President, if I could ask one last question...
   A. Or wasn't I not supposed to say that _ What, about the ball
game? Come on.
   Q. Some things that you just can't ...
   Q. If I could ask one last question on the HUD scandal?
   A. Yeah?
   Q. I think that many people would think it's unfair to hold you
responsible when you were vice president for the things that were
going on at HUD. But some of the people who have been implicated in
this scandal are very close to you. I'm thinking of both Frederick
Bush, who was your key fundraiser in the campaign, and Paul
Manafort, who was an adviser to your campaign and a partner of Lee
Atwater, your campaign manager. Have you made any effort to find out
exactly what these people who are close to you were doing with HUD,
or to express your views of it to them? Have you made any efforts in
those regards?
   A. I'm not singling out any, you know, _ going, say, look for
people that I know that may have done business with HUD in the past.
What I am trying to do is do it generically. Say to the degree there
was any breaking of the law, obviously the people should pay the,
whatever the price is. To the degree we can guard against any abuse
for the future, I want to go the extra mile to do that. And one of
the first things I did as president, unnoted though it was, was to
meet with the inspectors general in here and encourage them towards
independence and thorough investigation. And so, that's the way I am
trying to handle that matter.
   Q. As a follow-up, does this affect your relationship with these
people, to know that they were involved apparently in influence
peddling?
   A. Well, it doesn't improve things, but on the other hand I want
to be fair. I want to be sure that I don't jump at conclusions as to
what guilt is and what it isn't, whether law was broken or were
people just out there, you know, doing what was permitted. I want to
have the standard higher, though, even if it's permitted. I want to
have the highest possible standard, but I haven't put it on that
kind of a personal basis yet.
   Q. Mr. President, the Senate has just passed a child care bill
that would spend almost $9 billion in federal funds on child care.
Your spokesman says that bill is a candidate for a veto. Do you
intend to veto that bill, and what are your objections?
   A. I want to see what comes down here. But if there was one thing
that was clear _ I've got to be careful of these gestures, the way
these, Rich Little and these guys _ but if there was one thing that
was clear, one thing that was clear, it was my position on child
care: maximum choice through credits. And the ABC bill does not fit
what I think is the proper description for child care. And to then _
for me to take the back seat and say, ``I'm less concerned about
child care because I'm unenthusiastic about the ABC bill,'' I don't
accept that at all. So I remain convinced that what I have proposed
is the right way to go about it. I would like to see what comes down
here before I make further statements about what action I will take
or won't take. I want to know the final, you know, piece of
legislation that hits this desk.
   Q. But you would veto the bill as it stands now.
   A.I've made my position clear on the ABC bill.
   Yeah.
   Q. Sir, you say you don't want to prejudge Secretary Pierce, but
doesn't the evidence of mismanagement and influence-peddling make it
evident to you that there were major problems there at the very top?
   A. Yes, yes.
   Q. And what can be done about that?
   A. Well, that's what the process, that's what the secretary is
trying to do right now, is to make guarantees and put out
regulations to see that these kinds of abuses _ a woman sitting in
Maryland ripping off $5 million from the American taxpayers, that's
wrong. And that _ and I expect that's in the courts. I don't know,
that's where it should be, in my view.
   Yeah, Frank?
</TEXT>
