<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-Rights     06-27 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-Rights,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Bulgarian Dissidents Arrested, Emigre Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five dissidents have been arrested in
Bulgaria, but it is unclear when or if they will go on trial, an
emigre source reported Tuesday.
   The source confirmed the arrest in Sofia last month of the Rev.
Hristofor Sabev, an Orthodox priest from Veliko Turnovo who founded
the Independent Committee for Religious Freedom.
   It was believed that Sabev, 43, was taken into custody because of
his support for religious and human rights in Bulgaria, including
the Turkish minority's ethnic rights.
   In early June, authorities also arrested Todor Gagalov, an
economist and vice president of Podkrepa, an independent
intellectuals' union, one of about eight dissident groups that have
arisen in Bulgaria recently.
   Three other leading members of Podkrepa, including Konstantin
Trenchev, its president, were arrested last month.
   Bulgarian government officials said Friday about 50 people were
under investigation for their role in ethnic Turkish disturbances
last month that Western diplomats say killed 30 people.
   The clashes with Bulgarian security forces occurred as
authorities sought to disperse demonstrators calling for restoration
of religious and civil rights of the 1 million-member Turkish
minority.
   More than 70,000 of the ethnic Turks have already left Bulgaria
for Turkey after the Sofia government opened its borders early this
month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
