<FIRST>r i PM-JetsCollide 1stLd-Writethru   06-27 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jets Collide, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0535,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Jets Collide on Ground at Heathrow, No Injuries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with aviation official's comment;
no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wing of a taxiing jetliner clipped the tail
section of another today at Heathrow Airport as the aircraft were
preparing to take off, but none of the 480 people on the planes was
injured, airline officials said.
   The incident involved a British Airways Boeing 757 carrying 111
passengers and seven crew members to Brussels and a Thai Airways
International Boeing 747 en route to Bangkok.
   Both jets suffered minor damage when the wing of the Thai jet
struck the tail section of the stationary British Airways jet as the
Bangkok flight was taxiing toward the runway, said Linda Jones, a
spokeswoman for British Airways.
   ``It was actually a very minor accident,'' Ms. Jones said.
``People on board probably were not aware of it.''
   British Airways passengers were transferred to another plane.
Thai Airways was making alternative arrangements for its 348
passengers, said airline spokesman Jeff Bacall. The Thai flight had
a 21-member crew.
   A Civil Aviation Authority spokeswoman, speaking on condition of
anonymity in keeping with British practice, said: ``It is a
reportable incident and will be investigated by the Air
Investigations Branch.''
</TEXT>
