<FIRST>r a PM-KraftContest     06-27 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kraft Contest,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>$250 Checks Go to Would-Be Van Winners in Kraft Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft today said it is mailing $250 checks to
hundreds of people who claim they won a $17,000 van that was
supposed to be the grand prize in a botched contest.
   Letters accompanying the checks say that the payment ``represents
our appreciation for your understanding and good will'' and that the
company is ``sorry for any confusion or disappointment the flawed
game may have caused.''
   Because of a printing error, the ``Ready to Roll'' game pieces
Kraft offered last month in newspapers in the Chicago and Houston
areas matched virtually all game pieces in packages of Kraft cheese,
making hundreds, possibly thousands, of people apparent winners of a
1990 Dodge Caravan.
   The company nullified the contest June 12 after the error was
discovered, prompting at least two class-action lawsuits by would-be
winners.
   Kraft USA spokeswoman Kathy Knuth said from company headquarters
in suburban Glenview that the number of people who mailed in
matching game pieces for the van and other prizes is not available.
Kraft is owned by Philip Morris Cos.
   The company announced the $250 consolation-prize checks along
with a modified contest in which Kraft gave claimants until June 16
to qualify for a July 14 drawing for four vans and other prizes.
</TEXT>
