<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     06-27 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire in Test Engine Could Delay Space Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers examined a space shuttle
main engine Tuesday to determine if damage it suffered in a
test-firing could delay this summer's launch of the shuttle Columbia.
   ``Engineers have to inspect the engine and look at the data
before they can make a decision about Columbia's launch,'' said Dave
Drachlis, a space agency spokesman at the Marshall Space Flight
Center in Huntsville, Ala.
   The failure happened Friday on a test stand at the Stennis Space
Center in Bay St. Louis, Miss., during firing of a development
engine that has been ignited 23 times over several years to test new
parts for future shuttle flights.
   Columbia's three main engines already are in place as technicians
here prepare it for a launch in late July or early August on a
classified Defense Department mission.
   Jerry Smelser, head of the engine program at the Marshall center,
said NASA needs to determine if the problem involves parts similar
to those in Columbia's engines.
   Drachlis said the test engine operated normally until about 21
minutes into a planned firing of 22 minutes 17 seconds, when there
was a sudden shutdown and a fire. During a shuttle launch, the main
engines normally fire for about 8 minutes 30 seconds.
   There was significant damage to several internal parts, Drachlis
said.
   ``The engine did not blow up; it's still fundamentally intact,''
he said.
   The engine was flown to its manufacturer, the Rocketdyne Division
of Rockwell International in Canoga Park, Calif. Drachlis said
engineers would take the engine apart for detailed inspection.
</TEXT>
