<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-China     06-27 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-China,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese TV Factory OK'd for Venture in South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese TV factory has signed an
agreement with a South Korean company, the first time the Seoul
government has given approval for direct investment by a business
from a communist nation, the Finance Ministry said Tuesday.
   The Hanzhou TV Factory has signed an agreement to invest $2.8
million in a joint venture with Orion Electric Co. of South Korea
and Zhejiang Fuchen Co. of Hong Kong, a ministry spokesman said.
   Foreign investment in Korea is subject to approval by the Finance
Ministry.
   The spokesman said the joint venture with the factory was
expected to produce 580,000 20-inch tubes for color TV sets in 1989,
1.1 million tubes in 1990 and 1.2 million in 1992.
   The joint venture was expected to export 20 percent of the
production to China and Hong Kong through Zhejiang Fuchen, which has
invested $1.2 million in the venture, the ministry said.
   South Korea, which has no diplomatic relations with neighboring
China, is trying to expand trade with communist nations to enlarge
its markets and ease tension with communist North Korea.
</TEXT>
