<FIRST>u i PM-China 3rdLd-Writethru   06-27 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0586,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Puts Off U.S. Peace Corps Volunteers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 4th, `In Tokyo...' to UPDATE with EEC
calling for sanctions; pikcs up 5th pvs: Official Chinese...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has asked the United States to delay the
start of the Peace Corps program that was to begin sending American
volunteers to China this fall to teach English, a U.S. official said
today.
   Authorities also ordered two Americans _ a teacher and a student
_ to leave the country, apparently for participating in the
student-led pro-democracy movement, the U.S. Embassy said.
   Eleven other Americans, detained Monday in Kunming and charged
with distributing religious tracts, were released and told to leave
China by Friday, the embassy said. It said the Americans, members of
the Latter Rain Ministry of Litchfield, Ill., would leave in the
next day or so.
   In Tokyo, group tours to China involving 43,000 Japanese have
been canceled since martial law was declared in Beijing in May and
troops crushed the pro-democracy movement, Japanese officials said.
Transport Ministry official Tokuji Nakamura said the cancellations
cost the agencies $60 million in sales.
   In Madrid, Spain, European leaders today called for an embargo on
arms sales to China and urged the World Bank to postpone new loans
to China to protest the government's crackdown.
   The leaders of the 12-nation European Economic Community, at
their two-day summit, condemned in a statement ``the brutal
repression taking place in China.''
   Official Chinese media reported today that the steering committee
of China's legislature would meet in special session Thursday to
endorse the Communist Party's tough stance on dissent.
   Also to be discussed are a draft law on tightening controls over
rallies and demonstrations. Plans to discuss a long-pending bill
defining the rights and responsibilities of the press have been
shelved.
   The student demonstrations of April and May _ now called the
period of turmoil _ called for greater press freedom, and for
several weeks the press enjoyed unprecedented leeway in objectively
reporting events.
   But, since political hard-liners gained the upper hand, the press
has reverted to its former role as mouthpiece of the party line.
   The Chinese gave no reason for their request last week for the
Peace Corps postponement, the U.S. official said, saying they just
wanted to put the program off ``until a more appropriate time.''
   The decision was apparently triggered by continuing tension
following the June 4 military crackdown in which soldiers killed
hundreds of unarmed protesters in clearing central Beijing of
student protesters.
   Martial law remains in effect in most of the capital.
   Twenty Americans had been scheduled to go to Sichuan province in
central China to teach English from this fall, said the U.S.
official, who would not be further identified.
   China has criticized Washington for cutting off military aid
because of the bloody crackdown and for harboring leading dissident
Fang Lizhi in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing.
   But ``we're not reading anything retaliatory into'' the Peace
Corps postponement, the official said. ``It's not by any means
canceled.''
   The volunteers began a training program in May to prepare for
their assignments in China, which would be the 65th nation and first
communist country with a Peace Corps program.
   The two Americans ordered to leave China by Friday are a teacher
and a student at Nankai University in the northeastern port of
Tianjin, a U.S. Embassy official said on condition of anonymity.
   Contacted by telephone, a foreign affairs official at the
university identified the two as Mark Radicia, 25, of Omaha, Neb.;
and Helen Qubain, 21, of Buena Vista, Va.
   The official quoted the pair as saying police had ordered them
out of the country for violating unspecified regulations on the
behavior of foreigners. The official said Radicia taught business
management.
   Six journalists _ three Britons and three Americans _ have been
ordered out of the country since June 4 for ther reporting on the
situation.
   The official media said the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress would hear a report at its session Thursday on
``quelling the counterrevolutionary rebellion.''
   The Standing Committee, consisting of about 160 members, meets
every few months, usually for about a week, to discuss legislation
to be put before the annual full session of the Congress.
   Decision-making power in China rests with the party, and the
Congress' role has generally been limited to formal approval of laws
and government appointments.
   In recent years, however, it has been given more freedom to delay
or revise legislation and to debate national issues.
</TEXT>
