<FIRST>u a PM-NukeTest     06-27 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuke Test,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Nuclear Weapons Test in A Week Finally Detonated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear blast up to 12 times more
powerful than the bomb dropped on Hiroshima rocked the desert this
morning in the second major U.S. weapons test in a week.
   The blast registered 4.6 on the Richter scale at the National
Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo., said spokesman John
Minsch.
   The test, code-named Amarillo, was deemed a success by the Energy
Department. Spokesman Jim Boyer said monitors indicated no leak of
radiation.
   The device was detonated 2,100 feet beneath the test range at
8:30 a.m. and had an explosive force of up to 150,000 tons of TNT.
The blast that destroyed Hiroshima had an explosive force of 13,000
tons of TNT.
   Ground zero was three miles from where a test code-named Contact
was conducted June 22. That blast measured 5.2 on the Richter scale.
   The test was scheduled for Saturday but was repeatedly delayed by
unfavorable wind. Tests are not conducted if winds are blowing
toward a populated area such as Las Vegas in case radiiation escapes
the underground cavity.
   Both devices were classified as having a range of between 20 and
150 kilotons, the upper limit allowed under treaties with the Soviet
Union.
   Today's test was believed to be near the upper limit. When a test
is conducted near the upper limits, the Energy Department announces
the blast in advance and warns managers of highrise buildings in Las
Vegas not to have workers in precarious positions.
   Today's test was the seventh announced blast of the year at the
Nevada Test Site and the 694th since testing began in Nevada in 1951.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
