<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Spying     06-27 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Spying,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgian Air Force Colonel Convicted of Spying For Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Spy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Belgian air force colonel accused of
giving top secret Belgian and NATO documents to the Soviet Union was
convicted of treason Tuesday and sentenced to 20 years at hard labor.
   Col. Guy Binet was sentenced by the military court to 20 years at
hard labor and discharged from the armed forces. He could have
received life imprisonment, but the prosecutor had asked for a
15-year sentence.
   Binet, 54, had given secret Belgian and NATO military documents
for which he received the equivalent of $105,000, according to
testimony at the trial, which began earlier this month.
   Belgian Defense Minister Guy Coeme said at the time of Binet's
arrest in September 1980 that the colonel was driven by profit
motives rather than ideological reasons.
   Binet's lawyers argued that he did not act for money, that the
sum he received had been placed in a bank in Luxembourg and turned
over to Belgian authorities.
   Binet began spying for the Soviet Union in 1986, Coeme said, but
an investigation revealed the first contact with Soviet agents took
place three years earlier.
</TEXT>
