<DOCNO> AP890627-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Rights     06-27 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rights,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Pushed 1991 Human Rights Plans at Paris Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union used an East-West human rights
conference last week to sell itself as host for a follow-up session
in 1991.
   Laboring under U.S. and British threats to boycott the Moscow
conference if sufficient progress in human rights is not made, the
Soviet delegation tried to dispel doubts about its sincerity.
   The month-long Conference on the Human Dimension, which ended
Friday, was the first of three on human rights held in the framework
of the 1975 Helsinki accords.
   Ambassador Yuri B. Kashlev said his delegation held more than 100
meetings with journalists and human rights groups, assuring a high
profile and an ``open and straightforward position'' that ``drew
positive response.''
   Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze set the tone in a speech May
30 at the 35-nation forum, saying the affirmation of individual
rights should be the objective of all countries.
   A Soviet official later paid his nation's first clear homage to
Raoul Wallenberg, the Swedish diplomat who saved thousands of Jews
in Hungary in World War II, then disappeared after being arrested by
occupying Soviet forces.
   ``We profoundly regret the death of this noble person,'' said
Vladimir Andreyev of the Soviet prosecutor's office. Wallenberg's
fate, he said, ``is a somber page in our history.''
   Over the following month, the affable Soviet delegation laid on
news conferences and opened its doors to special interest groups
with grievances about human rights abuses in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviets deny they fear a U.S. boycott of the Moscow meeting
and say their attitude reflects the fruits of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policies of social and economic reforms.
   ``It's not an artificial thing,'' said Kashlev. ``Even before the
decision on the Moscow conference, we were the same open people ...
It's not just a trick to persuade somebody.''
   The United States agreed to attend the Moscow conference ``in the
expectation that progress in human rights would continue'' and that
free access by protest groups be guaranteed, said a ranking member
of the U.S. delegation, who asked not to be identified.
   ``We have agreed ... and we're planning to go,'' he said. ``But
we would have a very hard time sending a delegation if things moved
backward.''
   ``The decision has been taken,'' said the Soviet ambassador.
``There is no force in the world that will stop it (the Moscow
conference) from being held.''
   With or without the Americans, ``the process of democratization
will continue,'' Kashlev said.
   ``It's not because of their pressure. It's our own internal
development. It's Gorbachev who does this, not Mr. Abram,'' he said
of Morris B. Abram, head of the U.S. delegation in Paris.
   The stakes for Moscow are high. Holding the third conference
there amounts to an affirmation of Soviet compliance with the
principles of the Helsinki Final Act subscribed to by the nations of
the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe. The conference
includes all European nations except Albania, as well as the United
States and Canada.
   The three human rights conferences were decided on at the close
of a January meeting in Vienna. The second conference will be held
next year in Copenhagen, and a final meeting is scheduled for
Helsinki in 1992.
   The United States and West European nations have acknowledged
broad Soviet progress in human rights under Gorbachev.
   While East bloc allies Romania and Bulgaria were criticized for
human rights abuses, the Soviet Union was praised for progress and a
new spirit of cooperation.
   ``The Soviets have taken some comfort that they are not the
worst,'' said the U.S. delegate. They have used a
``non-confrontational, more tolerant approach than we've seen
before,'' he said.
   ``For quite a long time, our position was `hands off _ it's our
internal affair,''' Kashlev said. ``We have changed completely, much
more than the West.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
