<DOCNO> AP890627-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HousingBias     06-27 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Bias,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Remedial Action to Open Suburban Housing to
Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered local, state and federal
agencies to expand efforts to open suburban Boston housing to black
families.
   Ruling in a lawsuit filed 11 years ago, U.S. District Judge
Walter J. Skinner ordered the state to give the Boston Fair Housing
Commission authority to issue subpoenas, levy fines and start civil
actions to attack discrimination.
   Skinner agreed with the charge in the lawsuit by the Boston NAACP
that the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development failed to
use its grant programs to produce an adequate supply of affordable
integrated family housing in the metropolitan area.
   Skinner's findings dealt with HUD practices between 1977 to 1982.
But he wrote, ``The conditions, exacerbated by HUD's pattern of
inaction, apparently continue to exist and are currently
remediable.''
   The ruling, made public Monday, is a ``blockbuster _ a whole new
world,'' said Dianne Wilkerson of the Boston chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``This ruling
changes life for minorities in Boston in some very major ways. This
is just amazing.''
   HUD spokeswoman Jacqueline Roundtree said the department had not
decided whether to appeal.
   The ruling orders HUD and the state to require owners of all
government-assisted housing in metropolitan Boston to participate
fully in anti-discrimination programs. It also orders Boston to
create a clearinghouse with a list of federally assisted housing
units.
   In 1985, Skinner dismissed the lawsuit, saying he lacked
authority to review and correct HUD practices. In 1987, an appeals
court said Skinner did have authority and ordered him to reopen the
case.
</TEXT>
