<FIRST>r a PM-MormonRestoration 1stLd-Writethru a0531 06-27 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mormon Restoration, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mormons Finish Restoring Jail Where Church Founder Died</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with jail shrine dedicated. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARTHAGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormons today dedicated a $1 million shrine
in the old jail where a mob 145 years ago killed church founder
Joseph Smith and his brother.
   Mormon Church President Ezra Taft Benson, Gov. James R. Thompson
and more than 3,000 others attended ceremonies marking the end of a
restoration project at the site considered sacred by the world's 6.5
million Mormons.
   Gordon Hinckley, first counselor to Benson, recalled the shooting
of Smith and his brother, Hyrum, on June 27, 1844 as part of an
``epic story of martyrdom.''
   ``Few could foresee the future stature of the man whose blood
stained the floor of this jail,'' Hinckley said. ``We are grateful
for the reconciliation that has come with the passage of time.''
   The jail has been restored to its 1844 appearance. A statue of
the Smiths and six slate monuments inscribed with quotations from
Joseph Smith also were unveiled.
   The former jail's renovation was completed to coincide with the
150th anniversary of the Mormons' settlement in the Mississippi
River town of Nauvoo, 200 miles north of St. Louis.
   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints envisioned the
town as its home. But non-believers persecuted the Mormons over
Smith's claims that he had spoken with God.
   ``Joseph and Hyrum were summoned to Carthage to stand trial and
were being held at the jail when they were murdered by the mob. It
is a sacred place to us,'' said Loren C. Dunn, president of the
restoration project.
   Two years later, Brigham Young led church followers to their
eventual home in Salt Lake City. The church is spending $20 million
to uncover church roots in Illinois and restore the settlement at
Nauvoo, now a town of 1,100 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
