<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-US     06-27 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Photographer Says He Was Chained by Afghan Authorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American free-lance photographer
said Tuesday he was chained and handcuffed after his arrest by
Afghan security forces 19 days ago.
   Tony O'Brien, accompanied by police and agents of the Afghan
secret police, told a news conference that authorities have treated
him well since then.
   His comments came as a U.S. official arrived from India to
negotiate his release.
   O'Brien, 43, of Santa Fe, N.M., said Afghan officials told him he
would be tried for entering the country without a valid travel
document. The charge carries a prison term of five to 10 years.
   Looking relaxed and smiling at the Kabul Press Club, O'Brien
apologized to the government for entering Afghanistan without a visa.
   ``I really want to thank the Afghan government,'' he said at the
news conference, which was videotaped by Afghan television. ``I know
I have broken the laws of the country ... I apologize for that.''
   O'Brien said he was not pressured to make statements. ``I was
told that journalists wanted to meet me,'' he said. ``I was asked if
I was willing.''
   O'Brien said he was handcuffed and chained when arrested June 8
in Kabul, but since then, ``They have really treated me well, I did
not expect this.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said O'Brien had
entered Afghanistan six times in the company of the U.S.-backed
Moslem guerrillas fighting the pro-Soviet Kabul government. O'Brien
nodded.
   Journalists enter Afghanistan with the Pakistan-based guerrillas
because the government in the past had refused visas to many Western
journalists. But the government opened up its doors in June 1988,
and 1,200 foreign journalists have entered the country with valid
visas since then.
   At least three Western journalists and two foreign aid workers
have been captured while traveling with guerrillas during the
decade-long civil war. All were released unharmed. O'Brien is the
first American captured.
   O'Brien is a free-lance photographer with the Picture Group photo
agency and was on assignment for Life magazine when arrested.
O'Brien's photos from previous visits to Afghanistan have appeared
in major U.S. publications.
   Renny Smith, a consular officer from the U.S. Embassy in New
Delhi, arrived in Kabul on Tuesday to negotiate O'Brien's release.
</TEXT>
