<FIRST>r i AM-Khashoggi     06-27 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khashoggi,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Jailed Financier Will Fight Extradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi financier Adnan Khashoggi says he
will fight extradition to the United States, where he is accused of
helping Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos hide stolen wealth, a Swiss
official reported Tuesday.
   Marcos and his wife are accused in New York of stealing more than
$100 million in Philippine government money to buy real estate and
art objects before he was ousted as president in February 1986.
Khashoggi allegedly posed as the owner of some assets.
   Justice Ministry spokeswoman Ursula Riedel said Khashoggi was
asked, after a U.S. request arrived May 31, whether he would agree
to extradition.
   He refused and his attorneys are expected to provide an formal
explanation by next week, after which Swiss authorities will rule on
the extradition request, she told The Associated Press.
   No decision is expected until mid-July and Khashoggi's lawyers
have said they will appeal any ruling against him to the Federal
Tribunal, Switzerland's Supreme Court.
   Khashoggi, known for his middleman role in the Iran-Contra
affair, was arrested by Swiss police in April at the request of the
U.S. Embassy. It appears almost certain he will spend his 54th
birthday, July 25, in a Bern jail.
   A U.S. district court in New York indicted Khashoggi, the
Marcoses, five other people and a California bank last October.
   The financier is charged with racketeering, conspiracy,
obstruction of justice and mail fraud. Racketeering alone carries a
prison term of up to 20 years.
   Marcos was president of the Philippines for 20 years. The
government of President Corazon Aquino, swept to power by a
civilian-military uprising that drove Marcos into exile, accuses him
of stealing billions of dollars in public funds.
</TEXT>
