<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Czech-AIDS     06-27 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Czech-AIDS,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Step Up Pro-Condom Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are stepping up their
campaign against AIDS before the peak tourist summer months, the
official CTK news agency said Tuesday.
   Five people have died of the disease in Czechoslovakia and
another 145 have tested positive for it, the report said.
   The report, quoting data submitted to the recent World Conference
on AIDS in Montreal, said the main task of the campaign is health
education.
   ``That is why the windows of most of Prague's drugstores will
remind their customers of the advatages of condom use before
vacation time,'' according to the newspaper Mlada Fronta.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   The scientific name for the virus is human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV.
