<HEAD>Futrell Will Stay Out of NEA Race _ Maybe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the nation's largest union
said Tuesday that she won't endorse either candidate vying to
succeed her _ unless it looks like the vote isn't going the way she
wants.
   About 8,500 delegates will vote Monday on Mary Futrell's
successor during the National Education Association's annual
convention.
   The race between union vice president Keith Geiger and executive
committee member John Wilson is the hottest NEA leadership battle in
memory.
   Geiger is a long-time official who has worked closely with
Futrell. Wilson describes himself as the candidate for teachers who
prefer passion to pragmatism.
   Futrell said she reserved the right to make an endorsement ``if
it becomes necessary to get involved.''
   Asked what would make that necessary, she replied with a grin:
``If I think it's not going the way I would like for it to go.''
   But, Futrell said, ``so far it's going the way I would like it to
go.'' She didn't say which way that was.
