<HEAD>Two Historically Black Atlanta Colleges Formally Tie The Knot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to restore time element.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scarlet ribbon stretched across James P. Brawley
Drive symbolized the union of two of the country's oldest
historically black institutions, Clark College and Atlanta
University.
   The cutting of the ribbon across the street between the schools
Monday signaled the formation of a new institution _ Clark Atlanta
University.
   ``The significant history in this consolidation is what (the
institutions) bring to the table at this critical point in the life
and times of black America,'' said Dr. Thomas W. Cole Jr., president
of Clark Atlanta.
   The boards of trustees of the two institutions voted to
consolidate more than a year ago.
   The consolidation alleviates severe financial problems suffered
in recent years by Atlanta University, a graduate school chartered
in 1867, and a shortage of classroom and research space at Clark
College, founded in 1869.
