<FIRST>u a PM-ChurchResignation 1stLd-Writethru a0460 06-27 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Resignation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0460,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Turmoil-Ridden Church Council Resigning</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with resignation announced; PICKS
UP 8th graf pvs, `Brouwer riled ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the National Council of Churches
announced his resignation today in a dispute over the future of the
country's biggest ecumenical organization.
   The Rev. Arie R. Brouwer, general secretary of the council since
1985, said the organization is not ready to pursue the unifying
goals he set for it.
   ``The time is not ripe for it,'' he said in announcing he will
step down on Friday.
   The council, which includes most major Protestant and Eastern
Orthodox churches in the country, has been enmeshed in controversy
for three years over departmental accountability and authority, as
well as financial difficulties.
   Brouwer, who came close to being dismissed a month ago, had
pressed for closer integration of various council units against
stiff resistance by some officials.
   Their ``dream was different than mine,'' he said.
   Brouwer, 53, a Reformed Church in America clergyman, said the
rupture was clarified for him by a 57-57 vote over a move to dismiss
him at the council's governing board meeting in Lexington, Ky., last
month.
   Since the vote, pressure for Brouwer to step down continued.
   ``I will be in prayer and fasting over the days and weeks to
come,'' Brouwer had said after the vote.
   Brouwer riled some board members with a scathing report in
Lexington, saying recent months had been ``a crucifixion, a journey
through hell.''
   He said the ecumenical atmosphere has been fouled with ``rumors,
innuendo and false charges ... poured forth from the bureaucratic
rumor mill,'' public media and religious press. Defending his own
leadership style, he said:
   ``The problem is that I have dared to speak the truth to the will
to power. ... The powerful are not accustomed to such behavior and
they are outraged. They will not have it.''
   The main conflict had come over moves to make the council a more
united body functioning as a ``communion of communions,'' with each
department sharing proportionately in central administrative costs.
   That system was strongly resisted by Church World Service, the
council's relief arm and financially biggest operation. The service
had operated somewhat independently and with its own revenues.
   A furor developed in mid-1988 when the service's executive, the
Rev. J. Richard Butler, resigned because of conflict with Brouwer
over integrating the service more closely with other council units.
   As a result of the internal stress, general recommedations of a
reorganizational committee were approved at the Lexington meeting,
consolidating the council's 11 units into four.
   Measures that would give member denominations more direct
oversight of the council units were part of the plan, specifics of
which were to be worked out in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
