<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Thornburgh-CivilRights 2ndLd-Writethru a0423 06-27 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh-Civil Rights, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0423,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Pursue Legislation to Overturn Court Rulings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; Inserts grafs 6, President Bush, and 10-13, During a discussion,
with reaction.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh told a black
audience today that the Bush administration won't pursue legislation
to overturn recent Supreme Court decisions on civil rights.
   However, Thornburgh said he would monitor implementation of the
rulings and take ``any legislative or executive action that might be
required to resolve inequities.''
   ``The pursuit and promotion of civil rights in America is more
than a legal obligation, it is a moral imperative embodied in our
national sense of fairness and justice,'' Thornburgh told the annual
convention of Operation PUSH, the civil rights group founded by the
Rev. Jesse Jackson.
   The high court, adopting some positions advocated by the Justice
Department under the Reagan administration, has restricted
affirmative action programs and made it more difficult for
plaintiffs to prove discrimination in the workplace.
   The decisions have prompted calls from some lawmakers to consider
legislation to overturn the rulings.
   President Bush told a news conference today his advisers
concluded that none of the rulings has jeopardized the principles of
equal opportunity for all Americans. He said if the court's
decisions turn out to hamper civil rightrs enforcement, he would
consider legislation.
   Thornburgh, in his first public pronouncement on the
controversial cases, said some viewed the decisions ``as a retreat
in the battle for civil rights.''
   But, Thornburgh asked, do ``these decisions ... stand in conflict
with this nation's fundamental commitment to ensure the provision of
civil rights of all Americans? Or do these decisions represent
attempts by the court to fine-tune the complexities of enforcement
of civil rights law in America?''
   Thornburgh said the effect of the rulings would not be felt until
they are applied in new cases, but that President Bush had asked him
to monitor their implementation.
   ``This responsibility is one I take very seriously and one that
the Department of Justice will approach consistent with our
commitment to the goals of fairness and equality in our quest for
equal opportunity,'' Thornburgh said.
   During a discussion following the speech, several panelists
expressed disappointment that Thornburgh didn't favor immediate
legislation to overturn the high court rulings.
   ``In the past six days, the Supreme Court has basically repealed
Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,'' said Julius Chambers,
director of the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, Inc.
   ``It disappoints us, to put it mildly, to suggest that we must
now wait to see how these decisions work in practice.''
   ``We ask the administration to express the same reverence for
equal opportunity'' as for the American flag, said employment rights
lawyer Nancy Creiter, referring to President Bush's proposal for a
constitutional amendment to overturn the high court's legalization
of flag burning.
   Ralph G. Neas, executive director of the Leadership Conference on
Civil Rights, an umbrella group of civil rights organizations
nationwide, had said the administration's response would be an
important test.
   ``President Bush has repeatedly stated his commitment to civil
rights and to minority outreach efforts. However, a decision to
oppose legislation to overturn the recent Supreme Court decisions
would be completely incompatible with such a commitment,'' Neas said
before Thornburgh's speech.
   ``Indeed, remedial legislation has become the No. 1 priority for
everyone committed to equal employment opportunity for all
Americans,'' Neas said.
   Thornburgh spoke at the invitation of Jackson, who hailed the
attorney general's commitment to civil rights after the two met at
the Justice Departent last winter.
   ``The lights have been turned back on in the Justice Department
and hopefully the dust will be cleared from the books,'' Jackson
told reporters that day. He was referring to the Reagan
administration's civil rights record, which was roundly criticized
by black leaders.
   As he did after the meeting with Jackson, Thornburgh has
repeatedly expressed commitment to ``the full enforcement of civl
rights laws ... and the full enjoyment of equal opportunity by all
of its citizens.''
   But the attorney general has conceded he may have differences
with civil rights leaders about achieving those goals.
   William Lucas, whose nomination to head the Justice Department's
civil rights division has split the civil rights lobby, was
accompanying Thornburgh to the convention.
   A black Republican from Michigan, Lucas' nomination is opposed by
several organizations who contend he lacks the necessary legal
experience to be the Justice Department's civil rights chief.
   But Jackson and other black leaders have expressed support,
albeit muted in some cases, for the Lucas nomination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
