<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     06-27 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Session Opens in Bucharest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Romanian Communist Party's
policy-making Central Committee convened Tuesday in Bucharest to
discuss the upcoming 14th Party Congress in November, the official
Agerpres news agency said.
   The two-day meeting, chaired by party leader Nicolae Ceausescu,
will discuss ``directives regarding Romania's socio-economic
development in the 1991-95 five-year period, as well as long-term
guidelines until 2000-2010,'' the news agency said.
   The meeting also will approvie programs on the ``development of
revolutionaty worker's democracy, the growing role of the Romanian
Communist Party in ideological and political activity ... and the
fundamental characteristics of the present international
situation,'' Agerpres said.
   The meeting is the first since Romania in April made a surprise
announcement that it managed to pay off a foreign debt which in 1981
stood at $11 billion.
   The price, however, was steep. For nearly a decade, communist
authorities sharply rationed food, gasoline, electricity and other
essentials. Dissent over government policy was suppressed by one of
the world's most efficient police forces.
   Now that the debt is paid off, there is no word yet whether this
will translate into better lives for Romanians.
   Western commercial officials said in addition to the traditional
problems encountered in trading with a centralized economy, Romanian
industry has been starved of investments and is plagued with
breakdowns and supply problems.
   Romanian economists said Bucharest would like to expand its trade
with developing countries by offering better financing.
   The session would also discuss Romania's stand on foreign policy
developments prior to next week's Warsaw Pact summit in Bucharest,
which will draw the East bloc's party general secretaries, including
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
