<SECOND>AM-Bare Breasts,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Topfree 10 Plead Innocent in Rochester</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight women arrested for baring their
breasts on a city beach pleaded innocent Tuesday, saying a state law
that permits men to go shirtless discriminates against women.
   Ten women were charged on Saturday with exposure of person, a
violation under state law. Two defendants did not enter pleas and
were rescheduled to appear Wednesday.
   The women, dubbed the Topfree 10, said the state law that permits
men to go shirtless in public is unconstitutional because it
discriminates against women.
   ``Because the law is unjust, I plead not guilty,'' Kathie Reilly
told Judge John Manning Regan in Rochester City Court. He scheduled
a pre-trial conference for Aug. 1.
   The women are repeating a 1986 protest, in which seven women were
arrested in a city park for going topless and spent a week in court
trying to convince a judge that the state nudity law is unfair.
   In 1986, Judge Herman Walz dismissed the charges against the
women, saying they were expressing their right to free speech by
exposing their breasts as a form of protest.
   The women have been having ``Topfree Equality Picnics'' for the
past four years. In 1987 and 1988 they were not arrested.
