</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Bonnie Koloc says her versatility
has hurt her career.
   ``I can sing almost anything,'' she said in a recent interview.
``Country, jazz, gospel and `legitimate' all influenced me. I think
my stuff is not very classifiable; and that has hurt me my whole
career.''
   Her base of popularity is folk music, but she resists the label
folk singer.
   ``It labels you as not salable,'' she said. ``If I'd have played
piano instead of guitar, nobody would have ever called me a folk
singer.''
   Koloc, who lives in Nashville, has released eight albums,
including the current ``With You on My Side.'' She also has done
theater work in New York, including Thornton Wilder's ``The Human
Comedy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denver Broncos running back Sammy Winder has
responded to a $600,000 alienation of affection lawsuit by saying
the woman in question left her husband because of mistreatment, not
because of Winder's actions.
   Winder asked for a hearing Friday to determine whether he must
answer allegations that he had an affair with Cecelia Evans Spell,
bought her clothes and flowers, gave her money, and wined and dined
her.
   Winder said allegations by the woman's husband, Stanley Spell,
about an affair are vague and can't be countered without more
details.
   The athlete also claims Spell threatened to file criminal charges
unless Winder gave him $60,000.
   Spell encouraged his wife to lead a separate life, told her not
to use her married name and to keep their marriage a secret,
according to court documents filed by Winder.
   Spell seeks $60,000 for physical and mental distress, and
$540,000 in punitive damages from Winder, who owns a Jackson
construction company.
