<FIRST>u a PM-OwlCompromise     06-27 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Owl Compromise,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ranks Split On Timber Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists today rejected a
compromise plan but held the door open for further negotiations with
the timber industry over protecting the spotted owl in Oregon and
Washington.
   Andy Kerr, conservation director for the Oregon Natural Resources
Council, said there was not enough time to consider the plan.
   Spokesmen for logging companies said the industry was willing to
accept the compromise proposed Saturday by Gov. Neil Goldschmidt and
the state's congressional delegation at a so-called ``spotted owl
summit'' in Salem.
   The proposal called for a short-term increase in the number of
trees that could be cut on federal land in the two states while
protecting some of the older forests where the rare Northern spotted
owl nests.
   A statement issued by environmental groups said they could not
accept the timber harvest figures in the compromise without more
information.
   The congressional delegation had given both sides until this
morning to accept the plan. The deadline was set to allow Northwest
congressmen to attach a rider to an appropriations bill that comes
up in a House committee Wednesday.
   Robert L. Spence, chairman of the Northwest Forest Resources
Council, said the timber industry reluctantly accepted the plan. The
alternative was ``economic chaos,'' Spence said in a statement.
   ``The simple truth is that less timber means fewer jobs,'' Spence
said.
</TEXT>
