<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-RecallVote 1stLd-Writethru a0527 06-27 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Recall Vote, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0527,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Councilor Faces Recall Election Prompted by Smoking Ordinance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf to CORRECT number of votes needed to
1,943 sted 3,885.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city councilman faced a recall
election today for getting a tough new anti-smoking ordinance passed.
   The ordinance sponsored by Councilman Richard Chapman banned most
indoor smoking in public places as of April 19.
   It led a smokers'-rights group to gather enough signatures to
force today's recall election, the first involving an Albuquerque
city councilor.
   Critics have also charged that Chapman votes his personal views
and ignores the wishes of the people he represents.
   ``He's got an insatiable ego and is arrogant, and his usefulness
has long since expired,'' said Frank Bowden, an organizer of recall
campaign.
   Chapman, 41, said he sponsored the bill because polls showed most
people in Albuquerque favored smoking restrictions. He said he has a
politics-for-the-people attitude but can't please everyone all the
time.
   Chapman will lose his seat if a majority of the voters in his
district choose to remove him. In addition, at least 1,943 would
have to vote against him, half the number of votes cast in the 1987
election in which he won his seat.
   The American Smokers Alliance, a national smokers' rights group,
said Chapman's defeat could deter local governments from getting on
the anti-smoking bandwagon.
</TEXT>
