<DOCNO> AP890627-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-JunkBonds     06-27 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Junk Bonds,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showdown Brewing in Congress Over Junk Bonds and S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The junk bond market, already troubled by the
prospect of an economic slowdown, could suffer a heavy blow if
Congress adopts legislation forcing savings and loans to sell the
high-risk, high-yield securities, economists say.
   Nevertheless, members of Congress upset about the wave of
corporate takeovers and leveraged buyouts are determined to push
thrifts out of the lucrative, but speculative, investment.
   ``The question ... is simple,'' said Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa.
``Should the U.S. taxpayer subsidize leveraged buyouts, takeover
artists and large corporate mergers?''
   Leach is one of the chief backers of a provision, sponsored by
Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., in House-passed S&amp;L legislation. It would
forbid thrifts from buying junk bonds and force those that already
own them to sell within two years.
   The Senate version is more lenient. It maintains the current rule
restricting the junk bond holdings of federally chartered S&amp;Ls to 11
percent of assets. It extends the limit to state-chartered
institutions, but allows them to exceed it if they can come up with
extra capital.
   A House-Senate conference begins work in two weeks to resolve the
many differences, including the provisions affecting junk bonds, in
comprehensive legislation to bail out out and reform the S&amp;L
industry.
   High-yield, high-risk bonds, which are often used to finance
hostile corporate raids and management buyouts, are nicknamed junk
bonds because they have no or a low credit rating. Commercial banks
already are forbidden to invest in the bonds, but thrifts have been
allowed to buy them since the early 1980s.
   Relatively few thrifts own junk bonds _ only 161 S&amp;Ls in 36
states, a little more than 5 percent of all S&amp;Ls, according to a
report this spring by the General Accounting Office, Congress'
auditing agency.
   Most of those have relatively small investments. Ten thrifts
account for three-quarters of the industry's investment, and only
seven have junk bond portfolios exceeding the Senate's proposed
limit.
   But those numbers, according to economists, understate the extent
of thrift involvement in junk bonds and the potential ripple effects
of Dorgan's amendment.
   Between 1985 and 1988, S&amp;L junk bond holdings increased by 136
percent to $13.2 billion _ representing about 8 percent of the
entire junk bond market, according to the GAO.
   Economists warn that if the Dorgan amendment becomes law, junk
bond prices likely will fall and investors, including the S&amp;Ls
themselves, will get stuck for the losses.
   ``I think it's going to be very painful for a lot of these
thrifts,'' said economist Elliott Platt of Donaldson, Lufkin and
Jenrette. ``Investors who hold junk bonds are going to have to
monitor this legislation very, very carefully.''
   Those who defend allowing thrifts to own junk bonds say such
investments have been unfairly criticized. For all practical
purposes, a thrift buying a junk bond is taking no more risk than a
thrift making a commercial loan, they say.
   Secondly, they say, junk bonds offer high returns and they allow
S&amp;Ls in economically troubled regions to diversify by purchasing
bonds from companies in healthy regions and industries.
   Economist Paul Getman of the WEFA Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa.,
consulting firm, said junk bonds have been among the most profitable
activities for thrifts. WEFA studied thrifts and junk bonds for the
Alliance for Capital Access, a group representing junk bond issuers
and investors.
   Junk bond critics say the bonds have never been tested by a
recession, when losses from defaults are likely to rise, offsetting
profits from high-interest earnings.
   They also say extensive junk bond investment by thrifts diverts
money from home mortgages and could allow collusion between S&amp;Ls and
securities firms selling the bonds.
   The largest S&amp;L investor in junk bonds is Columbia Savings and
Loan Association of Beverly Hills, Calif., which owns about $4
billion, representing 35 percent of its portfolio.
   According to published reports, the Securities and Exchange
Commission has been investigating allegedly unlawful trading
arrangements between Columbia and Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., the
nation's largest underwriter of high yield securities.
   ``Junk bond holdings are one of the areas of most abuse,'' said
economist David Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., a government
securities dealer in New York. ``I as taxpayer don't want to be the
ultimate guarantor of a sweetheart deal between an S&amp;L and an
investment firm.''
</TEXT>
