<SECOND>AM-Brites,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYWHOPPITY BOTTOMS, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trash has proved to be a
13-year-old girl's ticket to Washington, D.C.
   Amy Carlton, a Hancock County Middle School student, won first
place in the state and regional competitions of the Invent America
contest. The latest victory means a $500 bond and a trip to the
nation's capital with her ``trash stash'' invention for another
round of competition.
   The device, inserted in the rear deck of a car below the back
windshield, is a slot with a swinging door that allows trash to be
dropped into a bag in the trunk. The bag is easily changed when full.
   ``Our car is always a mess,'' Amy said. It was the car's littered
floorboard which provided her with the inspiration to build the
device.
   Invent America is sponsored by the non-profit U.S. Patent Model
Foundation based in Washington, to encourage schoolchildren to be
inventive.
   After state competitions, five regional winners are chosen for
each grade kindergarten through eighth. So Amy will compete against
four other 7th graders in the national finals July 22-27.
   This week, Amy must send her invention to Patent Model
Foundation. Her working model of the invention includes the actual
rear deck of a car surrounded by plastic foam to resemble a cutaway
section of a car.
   She said she plans to seek a patent on her invention in hopes of
getting rich.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sick of slow service? Incensed by
indifference? Does bad food leave you bummed, pal? Well, for a
paltry $2.25, you don't have to take it anymore. Just use a
Consum-Alert sticker.
   The stickers can be applied on the window _ or the employee if
you're that angry _ of the offending business. They aren't permanent
_ they use static cling and can easily be removed and leave no
sticky residue.
   The black and gold flourescent stickers are the idea of radio
announcer Bill Flynn and ad agency owner Greg Fischer.
   ``I can only say there have been ample opportunities in my life
in the last six months where I could have used one of these things
and felt justified in doing so,'' Flynn said Tuesday. ``We live in a
time where it's so easy to be treated like a number.''
   ``The ultimate goal is to just be able to vent ourselves,''
Fischer said.
   Purchasers get six decals to an order. Black letters say:
``Consum-Alert Warning! This Business Has Been Targeted By Your
Fellow Consumer For'' one of four offenses.
   White letters on a black background indicate the offense: ``Slow
Service,'' ``Poor Service,'' ``Bad Attitude'' or ``Poor Hygiene.''
There are two Poor Service stickers and two for Bad Attitude.
   Instructions with the stickers claim ``the feeling of
self-respect and vindication you get is exhilarating.''
   The stickers should be placed, according to the instructions, in
a ``high-visibility, eye-level location for your Consum-Alert. Put
that sucker where everyone can see it!''
   The instructions don't encourage confrontation. The pleasure of
relieving frustration should be sufficient. ``You've joined the
ranks of Robin Hood and The Lone Ranger. Be proud.''
   Some of the proceeds from the sale of the stickers will go to the
Better Business Bureau, although Flynn admits ``We hope to make
money on this.''
</TEXT>
