<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     06-27 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Fails in Effort to Form Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts by Premier Andreas Papandreou to
form a coalition government from his hospital bed ended Tuesday with
a rebuff from the communist alliance.
   A medical bulletin issued by his doctors said the health of the
70-year-old Socialist was ``continually improving.'' He was
hospitalized Thursday for pneumonia, eight months after undergoing
heart surgery, and developed kidney and heart complications.
   Harilaos Florakis, leader of the Coalition of the Left and
Progress, said proposals from Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement were ``just as interesting'' as those made last week by
Constantine Mitsotakis, leader of the conservative New Democracy
party.
   Florakis said he favored a ``widely accepted'' government ``not
be headed either by Papandreou or Mitsotakis.'' His coalition is an
alliance of the Greek Communist Party and the Greek Left, a
Eurocommunist group.
   Negotiations began after inconclusive elections June 18.
   Officials of Papandreou's party did not disclose their proposals,
but said one condition was that he lead the government. New
Democracy had offered the alliance the Interior and Justice
ministries, but the communists rejected Mitsotakias as head of the
government.
   Doctors said Papandreou's heart condition was under control and
he was being treated successfully with a kidney dialysis machine.
The premier sent a representative to meet with the communists.
   New elections may be held soon if a government cannot be formed.
The communist alliance said it would support an effort to create a
national unity coalition.
   New Democracy won 145 seats in the 300-seat unicameral
parliament, six short of a majority. Papandreou's Socialists, hurt
by scandals in recent months, got 125 seats and the communist
alliance 28.
   Mitsotakis could not obtain communist support in the time allowed
and the Socialists were given their turn Friday, but negotiations
were delayed until Monday because of Papandreou's condition.
   Florakis said he would meet with leaders of both major parties
about the possibility of a broad coalition.
</TEXT>
