<HEAD>Palestinian Prisoner Kills Two Inmates Suspected of Collaborating</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT that police suggesting collaboration,
UPDATE casualties to 29. Pickup 5th, ``Israel radio ...'' SUBS grafs 9-11
``The three ... '' to conform. Pickup 12th graf, ``An army ....''; DELETES
last 3 grafs to TRIM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian prisoner in a desert detention
center killed two inmates, the army said Tuesday, and police
suggested the victims may have been accused of collaborating with
Israeli authoritiies.
   In the occupied territories, Israeli troops wounded at least 29
Palestinians when they opened fire on stone-throwers, hospital
officials said. Four victims were 11 years old, they said.
   Aides to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he will meet
Palestinian leaders from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip next
month to discuss his election plan.
   The killings in Ketziot, a Negev desert jail for Palestinian
security prisoners, were discovered when the men failed to report
for morning roll call, said an army official, who cannot be
identified under military rules.
   Police said the men may have been killed as suspected
collaborators. But the army spokesman said the killer may have been
avenging the 1985 killing of a friend.
   Israel radio said a prisoner confessed to the slayings, which
raise to four the number of inmates killed by fellow prisoners in
the past two weeks.
   Itim news agency said the victims were strangled, and police are
investigating whether the killer had accomplices.
   Those killed were identified as Mahmoud Abdul Abedgalla, 24, and
Ali Hijazi Taaf, 30. Both are from the Gaza Strip.
   Also Tuesday, Tarek Salih Awad, 17, died of bullet wounds from a
Saturday clash with Israeli troops, said officials at Mukassed
Hospital in Arab east Jerusalem. The army confirmed the death.
   His death increased the toll to 537 Palestinians killed since
Arabs started revolting against Israeli occupation in December 1987.
Sixy-eight have been killed as collaborators by fellow Arabs.
Twenty-three Israelis also have died.
   In Gaza Strip, Israeli troops opened fire on stone-throwing
demonstrators in Rafah town, wounding 21 Palestinians, doctors said.
Victims include a 17-year-old with a bad head wound, they said.
   Three other Palestinians were wounded in Khan Yunis refugee camp,
three in Shati refugee camp and one each in Nuseirat and Bureij
camps, hospital officials said.
   An army spokeswoman confirmed three injuries in Rafah, all from
plastic bullets, and said troops were forced to open fire when a
large crowd began hurling stones.
   Shamir spokesman Avi Pazner said the Israeli leader will meet
Palestinian leaders in July, but declined to reveal their names.
   Pazner denied Israeli media reports that some Palestinians at the
talks will be supporters of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
Israel considers the PLO a terrorist organization.
   Shamir's plan calls for elections to select Palestinian
representatives from the occupied lands to open peace talks with
Israel. The proposal has been rejected by the PLO and prominent
Palestinians in the territories who say it does not recognize their
aspiration for an independent state. Hard-liners in Shamir's Likud
bloc want the proposal amended because they say it could lead to
creation of a Palestinian state.
