<HEAD>Palestinian Peacemaker Banned From Meeting PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school principal who drafted his
own 11-point peace plan said Tuesday he canceled a trip to Egypt to
promote the proposal because Israel barred him from meeting PLO
officials.
   Assad Saftawi attracted attention with his plan calling for local
Palestinians to negotiate an interim autonomy for the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The plan brought positive reactions from Israeli officials who
said it indicated Palestinians from the occupied territories are
willing to start negotiations without the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which Israel designates a terrorist group.
   The officials considered it a favorable response to Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's proposal for elections in the occupied
lands to choose Palestinians to negotiate with Israel about
self-rule. Talks on the final status would be left until later.
   But Saftawi, headmaster of a school in the Gaza Strip's Bureij
refugee camp, told Israeli officials he needed PLO approval.
   ``There is no way that my peace plan will be valid unless the PLO
looks at it and agrees on it,'' he said.
   ``But the Israelis think that if they let me go and talk to the
PLO they will recognize the PLO in a roundabout way.''
   Saftawi, 54, said he is canceling his trip to Egypt since the
main purpose was to meet PLO officials.
   He met Monday with Shmuel Goren, Israel's coordinator for the
occupied territories, and conferred last month with Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin.
   The Rabin meeting was considered significant because of Saftawi's
history as a pro-PLO activist convicted in 1973 for belonging to
Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction.
   Fatah official Salah Khalaf was quoted Tuesday as criticizing
Saftawi's plan. The Kuwait daily Al-Watan quoted Khalaf as saying:
``I think we differ with this blueprint because we consider any
separation between the elections and comprehensive solution to be
designed to serve Israel's interests.''
   An Israeli military official said Goren warned Saftawi he faced
prosecution if he violated Israeli laws barring contacts with the
PLO.
   ``We told him that if he wants to go abroad, he can do it. ... If
he disobeys the law, however, he will have to take the
consequences,'' the official said on condition of anonymity.
   ``Every Palestinian who asks for permission to meet with PLO
officials gets the same answer,'' he added.
   Violators from the occupied territories can be sentenced to up to
10 years in jail, said an army spokesman. Israeli violators can get
up to three years in prison.
   The attorney general's office said Tuesday it is investigating
three Israeli legislators for meeting with Arafat. Those under
investigation are Communist Party Members Meir Wilner and Tawfik
Ziad and Abdel Wahab Darousha, an Israeli-Arab from the Democratic
Arab Party.
