<FIRST>r i AM-Synagogue     06-27 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Synagogue,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Berlin's Bombed-Out Synagogue to be Rebuilt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Berlin's largest synagogue, nearly destroyed by
World War II bombs, will be rebuilt as the center of Jewish worship
and culture in the city's communist eastern sector, organizers said
Tuesday.
   The announcement was made at a news conference in East Berlin
attended by Heinz Galinski, the leader of West Germany's Jewish
communities, along with members of East Berlin's Jewish community.
They make up a group called the Association for Rebuilding, which is
coordinating restoration of the synagogue.
   East German leader Erich Honecker laid the cornerstone for
rebuilding the synagogue last year, but workers soon discovered that
nearly the entire building will have to be torn down and reassembled.
   West Germany has pledged about $500,000 toward restoration of the
building, but more is needed, said Hermann Simon, secretary of the
rebuilding association. He said there were no final estimates of the
cost.
   East German officials are counting on most of the cost to be
covered by donations.
   About 173,000 Jews lived in Berlin before the Nazi Holocaust.
Today, about 6,000 Jews live in West Berlin, and about 300 Jews live
in East Berlin.
   The Berlin synagogue was burned during the Nazis' ``Crystal
Night'' attacks of Nov. 9-10, 1938, but a policeman saved the
building by calling the fire department. Allied bombers virtually
destroyed the complex during the war.
</TEXT>
