<HEAD>Legal Advice Hotline Besieged by Worried Chinese</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers working on a new legal hotline for foreign
students received dozens of queries Tuesday from Chinese worried
about possible danger when they return home after joining in
anti-government protests.
   Some of the callers asked how to get foreign passports or how to
defect, said Kohei Sugino, a spokesman for the free telephone
service sponsored by the Tokyo Bar Association Committee for the
Protection of Human Rights.
   The hotline had 74 calls Tuesday _ its first day _ and will
operate for two more days, Sugino said.
   Most of the callers were Chinese, worried that their
participation in anti-government demonstrations might endanger them
when they go home.
   ``They are extremely uneasy because Japan grants visa extensions
on a case-by-case basis,'' Sugino said.
   The Japanese Ministry of Justice has announced it will consider
granting individual six-month visa extensions for students who have
finished their studies and whose visas have expired. As of June 21,
43 such students had applied, but no one had yet been granted the
special extension, said a Justice Ministry official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Since Japan does not give blanket visa extensions, China will be
able to find out which students are seeking to avoid going home,
Sugino said.
   He also said some students were concerned about returning home
even temporarily. There are rumors going around that students
visiting home must report on their political activities to obtain a
Chinese exit visa to return to Japan.
   Sugino said the lawyers advised callers on Japanese visa
procedures.
   Government officials say more than 7,700 Chinese students are in
Japanese universities or colleges, and another 120,000 Chinese are
in Japan for business or other purposes.
