<FIRST>r w AM-US-EasternEurope     06-27 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Eastern Europe,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Changes Sweeping Eastern Europe, US Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic change is so far advanced in Hungary
that it is conceivable a majority of the Hungarian parliament will
become noncommunist in the next two to five years, a State
Department official told Congress Tuesday.
   The official, Curtis W. Kamman, deputy assistant secretary of
state for European affairs, told a House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee the Bush administration does not believe House
legislation to reward Hungary with a five-year exemption from
economic and trade restrictions is needed.
   He explained that Hungary has removed practically all
restrictions on the ability of its citizens to travel abroad or to
emigrate at will, the objective of the restrictions.
   Kamman said that while both Hungary and Poland are building
democratic institutions, Hungary has drafted a new constitution and
has scheduled multiparty local elections for the fall and multiparty
national elections next year.
   ``It is conceivable that within the next two to five years, you
could have a majority in the Hungarian parliament that will be
noncommunist,'' Kamman said.
   He said both Hungary and Poland have permitted more freedom of
speech and the press than ever before in modern times.
   President Bush will visit Hungary and Poland during his trip to
Europe next month and Kamman said: ``By his presence, we will
encourage and signify our commitment to their struggle for freedom
and democracy.''
   Kamman said the administration is working on economic initiatives
for Hungary similar to those Bush announced for Poland during a
speech last month.
   He was asked whether or not that progress could or might be
reversed.
   ``The potential for reversal is very, very low,'' he replied. ``I
really don't foresee it in either Poland or Hungary if the present
leaders remain in power.
   But he noted that the climate for democratic change could be
altered if ``dramatic changes occurred in the Soviet Union,''
altering its apparent present tolerance toward independent political
development in Eastern Europe.
   Kamman said Eastern Europe can no longer be seen as a
Moscow-dominated, communist monolith.
   He said democratic reforms are most advanced in Hungary and
Poland and that there have been modest changes in Czechoslovakia,
East Germany, and Bulgaria. The exception is Romania, where he said
the political and economic situation appears to be rapidly
deteriorating.
   ``What we see now is that if the promise of reform is kept,
Eastern Europe will be a very different place: more true to its own
historical traditions, more independent and ultimately more
prosperous and stable,'' Kamman said.
   ``It is no longer a bloc but an increasingly interesting and
important grouping of individual countries _ each moving forward or
sideways or, as in Romania's case, backwards.''
</TEXT>
