<FIRST>r w AM-Wheat-Soviets     06-27 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wheat-Soviets,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy Additional 400,000 Metric Tons of U.S. Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat for delivery this year under the
long-term grain agreement between the two countries, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday.
   Officials said the sale, by unidentified private exporters, was a
straight commercial transaction and did not involve subsidies under
the department's Export Enhancement Program.
   The Soviet Union has bought more than 4.2 million tons of wheat
under EEP arrangements for 1988-89 delivery, the most recent being
96,000 tons announced on June 23.
   Although the Soviets had virtually used up the previous EEP
allocation, a new deal for an additional 1.5 million tons of wheat
was announced May 2. Officials said Moscow still has 814,200 tons
available under the program.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. According to the latest USDA five-day average, the price
of wheat has been $3.85 per bushel, meaning the latest sale of
approximately 14.7 million bushels could have a farm value of around
$56 million.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition
in selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   The sale announced Tuesday boosted to more than 21.2 million tons
the amount of grain Moscow has bought for delivery in the sixth year
of the agreement, which began last Oct. 1. Of that, corn makes up
nearly 16.2 million tons, and wheat, more than 5 million tons.
   In addition, the Soviets have bought 442,500 tons of soybeans;
1.35 million tons of soybean meal; and more than 1 million tons of
grain sorghum.
</TEXT>
