<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HousingBias     06-27 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Bias,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Judge Orders HUD, Boston, State To Combat Housing Bias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development, the state and the city to work harder
to eliminate racial discrimination in housing in metropolitan Boston.
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge Walter Jay Skinner stems from a
lawsuit filed 11 years ago by the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People against HUD.
   Dianne Wilkerson of the NAACP in Boston called the ruling ``a
blockbuster _ a whole new world.''
   ``This really is a challenge,'' Ms. Wilkerson said Tuesday. ``In
the end it's a challenge to (HUD Secretary) Jack Kemp. Jack Kemp has
said fair housing is a challenge for his administration. If that's
true, they won't appeal.''
   Jacqueline Roundtree, a HUD spokeswoman in Boston, said agency
attorneys were reviewing the ruling and had not decided whether to
appeal.
   The Boston Fair Housing Commission has found that eight of 10
blacks who look for a home to rent or buy encounter discrimination,
Ms. Wilkerson said. Friday's ruling gives them more means to fight
back, she said.
   From 1977 to 1982, Skinner said in his ruling, HUD broke federal
law by failing to use its grant programs to produce an adequate
supply of affordable integrated housing and failing to require
effective fair housing enforcement by the city.
   ``The conditions, exacerbated by HUD's pattern of inaction,
apparently continue to exist and are currently remediable,'' the
ruling said.
   Skinner's ruling orders:
   _ HUD to require that all landlords who get federal aid
participate in programs that market suburban housing to low-income
minorities.
   _ Boston to create a Housing Opportunity Clearinghouse that lists
available public housing.
   _ The state to give the Boston Fair Housing Commission legal
authority to issue subpoenas, levy fines and initiate civil actions
against discrimination.
   In 1985, Skinner said he agreed with the NAACP suit, finding that
HUD was aware that Boston had a history of racial bias in housing
and that its acute shortage of low-income family housing affected
blacks more than whites.
   However, he dismissed the lawsuit then, saying he lacked
authority to review and correct the agency's practices. In 1987, an
appeals court said Skinner did have authority, and ordered him to
reopen the case.
   Mayor Raymond Flynn said Tuesday he welcomed the decision and has
supported many similar remedies since becoming mayor in 1984.
   Marcia Hertz, a spokeswoman for the Executive Office of
Communities and Development, the state housing agency, praised the
ruling.
   ``It actually mirrors the state policies already in place. Our
programs and policies all have strong affirmative action
components.''
   Ms. Roundtree said, ``If you ask whether there's been some
improvement in Boston since 1978, from a public housing standpoint,
our survey and monitoring report in 1987 showed there are still some
problems.
   ``We're not 100 percent where everybody has equal housing but
we're moving in that direction, it's probably not as much as the
judge wanted.''
   Metropolitan Boston refers to an area of 2.8 million people in
about 110 municipalities. While 13 percent of Boston's 573,000
people are black, there are no current figures available on the
percentage in the metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
