<SECOND>AM-US-Germany-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Diplomat Will Be Expelled in Poison Gas Sale</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, inserts graf 4, bgng ``German authorities,'' with
German embassy comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government has agreed to a U.S.
request to expel an Iranian diplomat involved in a German company's
sale of poison-gas chemicals to Iran, the Bush administration said
Tuesday.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III told visiting West German
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher about the sales during a
luncheon last week, said State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler.
   Genscher said he knew nothing about the incident, Ms. Tutwiler
said.
   German authorities undertook an investigation into the activities
of the company, a small firm in Dusseldorf, said a West German
Embassy official.
   The company, to circumvent stricter West German export controls,
bought the chemicals from a business in India, another
administration official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, declined to
name the West German company.
   The diplomat in charge of the chemical acquisition was identified
as Said Karim Ali Sobhani, an official of Iran's trade mission.
   Ms. Tutwiler said it was understandable that West German
officials don't know about every sale by every West German company.
She also said the United States was satisfied with the West German
response, but doesn't view the case as closed.
   News of the incident comes as Congress considers several
proposals to enact sanctions against nations and companies that sell
chemical and biological weapons.
   The proposed legislation was prompted by revelations last year
that West German companies sold Libya equipment for production of
chemical weapons. West Germany tightened its export control laws as
a result of the ensuing furor.
   Iran and Iraq used chemical weapons during their nine-year war
that ended last year.
   Use of the chemical weapons prompted the United States to join
with its allies in seeking to halt sales of any chemicals that can
be used by Third World countries as weapons.
</TEXT>
