<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     06-27 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khamenei Wants Says Peace Talks Impossible With Land Occupied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ali Khamenei of Iran said
Tuesday his country is committed to peace talks with Iraq, but he
insisted the Persian Gulf rival give up occupied Iranian territory.
   ``We will support the talks if they lead to peace, but we cannot
find the necessary faith as long as the enemy is on our soil,''
Khamenei said in comments carried by the official Islamic Republic
News Agency, monitored in Nicosia.
   ``How can they have pretensions to peace when they have kept
their forces on our soil?'' he said. ``Iraq must withdraw its forces
...''
   The eight years of fighting ended in August under a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire agreement. But talks on a permanent peace
remain deadlocked over several issues, including possession the
Shatt al-Arab waterway, prisoner exchanges and the withdrawal of
troops to pre-war borders.
   Iraqi troops still occupy about 380 square miles of Iranian
territory.
   The Iranian news agency said Khamenei's remarks came in a speech
to volunteer forces from throughout the nation. Khamenei was chosen
as Iran's senior leader after the June 3 death of revolutionary
patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The remarks follow a Saturday speech by Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein, who urged Iran to work for peace in the gulf region instead
of rebuilding its armed forces.
   Hussein also suggested the two sides exchange prisoners of war in
a goodwill gesture, but Khamenei did not address that point. An
estimated 100,000 soldiers remain to be repatriated.
</TEXT>
