<FIRST>u a AM-OilSpill-Delaware Bjt   06-27 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Delaware, Bjt,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warming Trend Worries Cleanup Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLAYMONT, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Climbing temperatures on Tuesday melted
blobs of heavy oil scattered over 21 miles of the Delaware River and
slowed down cleanup efforts already being challenged in court as too
slow.
   Coast Guard officials revised downward the number of gallons
spilled from 800,000 gallons to 306,684 gallons, based on new
assessments.
   A Uruguayan tanker went aground early Saturday, spilling No. 6
industrial heating oil. The oil coagulated in the cool water into
chunks, averaging about the size of a basketball but with some up to
2 and 3 feet across.
   Cleanup workers had been using pitchforks and even their hands to
snare the blobs of oil from the water while skimmers, jammed up by
the larger chucks, were deployed in areas of the river where there
were smaller lumps. The crews also have tried out fishing nets.
   ``When we've got it in chunks, we can pick it up,'' said Coast
Guard Capt. Larry Murdoch.
   But on Tuesday, the temperature headed into the 90s, the melting
range for the No. 6 industrial heating oil.
   During an inspection tour, officials pointed to patches where the
rainbow hue of petroleum on water showed up and said it was coming
from oil blobs close enough to the surface to heat and melt.
   The melting oil poses a much greater haal Guard, federal
government and private contract employees walking along the
shoreline and working out of 22 boats snaring the oil blobs.
   Coast Guard officials said they hoped to have more than 500
people involved in the cleanup Tuesday. But Roger A. Lucio of the
Delaware Department of Natural Resources and Environmental Control
said 207 National Guard and private contractor employees were
working along with 100 federal government workers.
   The heat was reaching the point where officials also began to
worry about the cleanup workers.
   ``We ... have to recognize if we work them unreasonably in this
kind of weather, we can also do bad things to their health,''
Murdock said.
</TEXT>
