<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-HUD 1stLd-Writethru a0712 06-27 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-HUD, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush on HUD: OK, Blame Me, I Was Vice President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Frederick Bush being called for more questioning,
subbing 2 grafs for 9th graf, Frederick Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday he accepts some
responsibility for recently unearthed Reagan-era problems at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development since he was vice
president at the time.
   He also said that while he doesn't want to jump to conclusions,
congressional questioning of people close to him about influence
peddling on housing projects ``doesn't improve things'' in his
relationships with the men.
   ``If you want to assign blame to the vice president for what
happened over the past ... eight years, OK, that's fine, I accept
it,'' said the president during a news conference at the White House.
   Bush said he wants to make sure there is no recurrence of
``cronyism'' and ``special favors'' in awarding government contracts.
   ``That matter is being looked into by our very able, dedicated
Secretary of HUD and we are going to do everything we can to clean
up any cronyism or see that matters of that nature not recur,'' said
Bush.
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development has been rocked
in recent months by allegations that several Republican insiders and
former government officials were paid as consultants and developers
in the agency's moderate rehabilitation program.
   Bush said he would not single out anyone when asked specifically
about two men who were key aides in his presidential campaign last
year.
   Paul Manafort, an adviser to Bush's 1988 presidential campaign
manager, Republican National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater, told a
congressional panel last week that the more than $300,000 he earned
as a consultant on one project could indeed be characterized as
being for ``influence-peddling.''
   Frederick Bush, who was deputy chief of staff for then-Vice
President Bush, no relation, earlier testified before the same panel
about his role in another project.
   He has been asked to make a second appearance this week before
the House subcommittee on employment and housing to further clarify
his company's $260,000 consultant's fee on the Los Jazmines project
in Puerto Rico.
   The president was asked, ``Does this affect your relationship
with these people, to know that they were involved apparently in
influence peddling?''
   ``Well, it doesn't improve things, but on the other hand I want
to be fair,'' he answered. ``I want to be sure that I don't jump at
conclusions as to what guilt is and what it isn't, whether law was
broken or were people just out there, you know, doing what was
permitted.
   ``I want to have the standard higher, though, even if it's
permitted. I want to have the highest possible standard, but I
haven't put it on that kind of a personal basis yet,'' Bush said.
   The president praised HUD Secretary Jack Kemp for his work but
sidestepped placing blame on former Secretary Samuel Pierce for
problems at the agency.
   ``I am not about to prejudge the secretary himself. I assume that
he would accept responsibility for what happened _ past tense _ in
his department, just as I would have to assume responsibility for
something that goes on in my administration whether I know about it
or not,'' said Bush.
   ``The message has gone out loud and clear to every Cabinet
officer that we want the highest possible ethical standards,'' Bush
added.
   HUD Inspector General Paul Adams has said at least a dozen
private escrow agents nationwide are under investigation for
possible embezzlement of millions of dollars of HUD funds.
   Bush said he has met with investigators and encouraged
independence and thoroughness in their work.
   His statement came as reports revealed the U.S. attorney in
Atlanta is seeking $7.5 million in damages from two agents accused
of keeping more than $1 million in proceeds from real estate
closings there.
   In Maryland, Marilyn Harrell, an escrow agent dubbed ``Robin
HUD'' by investigators, has admitted she stole $5.5 million from HUD
closings she conducted.
   Harrell has turned over her Temple Hills, Md., home to the agency
to compensate for part of her theft.
   Mike Norton, the U.S. attorney in Denver also is investigating
allegations that a suspended HUD accountant embezzled $1 million in
housing funds.
   Meanwhile HUD announced $89.2 million in new grants Tuesday to
private, non-profit and government sponsors to develop 131 projects
nationwide in a demonstration transitional housing program for the
homeless.
</TEXT>
