<FIRST>r a AM-SovietSpy-Reax     06-27 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Spy-Reax,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Souther Called Unlikely Spy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Spy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glenn Michael Souther may have been a Soviet
spy, but it's unlikely he was a Russian mole who infiltrated this
country, his former associates said Tuesday after Souther's death
was reported in the Soviet Union.
   Rather, he was a rambuctious young American who satisfied his
craving for attention by defecting to the Soviet Union three years
ago, a decision that may have cost him his life, they said.
   ``They used him like a spider playing with a moth and when they
were going to finish with him, they finished with him,'' said
Barbara Fahey, a professor's wife who knew Souther when he was an
Old Dominion University student.
   Souther, 32, was a former Navy intelligence specialist who
disappeared shortly after he graduated from ODU in May 1986 with a
degree in Russian. He appeared on Soviet television last July and
said he had defected. The Soviet military newspaper Red Star
reported Tuesday that Souther was a KGB agent named Mikhail Orlov
and that he died unexpectedly June 22.
   ``There's some attempt to imply that he was really a Soviet-born
citizen and became a mole, but that was never really stated and I
don't believe it's true,'' said Ronald Kessler, a Maryland author
who is writing a book on Souther.
   ``He was in fact a very successful spy,'' Kessler said in a
telephone interview from his home in Potomac. ``He was an American
mole. It's possible that he took this Russian name after he
defected.''
   ODU professors who taught Souther said he was an outgoing,
well-liked student who started out poorly in his Russian major.
   ``There was, throughout the years, not a single indication that
he could have been not an American,'' said Leonid I. Mihalap, a
Soviet-born professor who taught Souther Russian. ``He did not look
Slavic and besides he didn't drink vodka.''
   But Mihalap said he reread one of Souther's final papers in
Russian and was surprised that it was grammatically flawless except
for one misspelling.
   ``His Russian was better than what I taught him,'' he said.
   Fran Hassencahl, Souther's speech professor at ODU, said he
talked often about his childhood in the Midwest and she met several
members of his family. She said she understood that he had married a
Russian woman and his mother had visited him in the Soviet Union.
   Kessler, who said he has obtained evidence of Souther's spying,
said he received a letter from Souther this month in response to the
writer's request for an interview.
   ``He said, `According to your letter you have already convicted
me of espionage: guilty until proven innocent' and then he said that
due to that he didn't want to be interviewed but would respond in
writing to questions,'' Kessler said.
   John Fahey, a retired Navy commander who taught Souther Russian
at ODU, said Souther loved to clown and play pranks.
   One of Souther's pranks may have led to his decision to defect,
Fahey said. Because he was suspended from ODU in 1984 for biting a
female student on the neck, Souther was turned down for officer
candidate school in the Navy.
   ``He was very bitter about what happened to him as far as the
problem on campus,'' Fahey said. ``He really wanted to become a
naval officer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EECSummit     06-27 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC Summit,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Leaders Plan for Monetary Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European leaders made a deal Tuesday to take
the first steps toward economic and monetary union, but Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain fended off moves for a single
currency and one central bank.
   Leaders of the 12-nation European Economic Community fell far
short of embracing sweeping proposals that would lead to tight
economic integration of the trading bloc.
   ``We've made as much progress as we can at this stage while
leaving longer term issues for further discussion,'' Mrs. Thatcher
said at the end of a two-day summit.
   Mrs. Thatcher was pitted against French President Francois
Mitterrand and West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who wanted a
quick monetary marriage.
   Despite their differences, the leaders praised the agreement to
coordinate more closely their economic and monetary policies.
   Kohl described the summit outcome as ``superb.''
   ``The foundation has been laid for a development that brings the
EEC further together and brings political union one step nearer,''
he said.
   Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez said, ``A week ago, I
would have said this would have been impossible.''
   Jacques Delors, a top Common Market official who championed
radical plans for monetary unity, said, ``I can say the (community)
is moving forward.''
   The leaders expanded the Common Market's drive to fashion a
single market by the end of 1992. By that date, the nations hope to
remove the many trade barriers that block the free movement of
people, goods, services and money.
   In their final statement, the leaders said they decided ``the
first stage of the realization of economic and monetary union would
begin on July 1, 1990.''
   They asked Common Market officials to complete measures required
for the initial phase, which generally stresses greater cooperation
on economic and monetary issues.
   In agreeing only on greater economic coordination, the leaders
failed to back wholeheartedly a report, pushed by Delors, setting
out three stages for a monetary union.
   They did, however, agree to start work on a special conference to
alter their founding treaty. Such changes would be necessary to set
up a European-wide central bank system and joint currency.
   Delors said the unity movement ``has been started, and I'm
tempted to say it's irreversible and will lead to economic and
monetary union.''
   Mrs. Thatcher said, however, ``There is absolutely nothing
automatic about going beyond stage one. All that is for future
decisions.''
   The leaders also sidestepped the touchy question of a proposed
``Social Charter'' to set out minimum rights for workers in the new
European-wide market.
   Mrs. Thatcher, a conservative, had criticized the proposal as a
socialist move.
   ``We have agreed at this (summit) that it can't be done now and
we have said it is all for further discussion,'' she said.
   But Gonzalez said the plan had not been shelved.
   The agreement for further discussion, he said, ``constitutes a
clearing of the way to continue working for social rights.''
   Also Tuesday, the EEC leaders called for an embargo on arms sales
to China and urged the World Bank to postpone new loans to that
country to protest the government's crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators.
   They also froze visits by high-level EEC members to Beijing,
extended visas of Chinese students in Europe and placed limits on
cultural and scientific exchange programs.
   The leaders also called for the participation of the Palestine
Liberation Organization in any U.N.-sponsored peace conference on
the Middle East.
   The declaration spoke of the ``continuing deterioration of the
situation'' in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and
called on Israeli authorities ``to end repressive measures'' in the
territories.
   The 18-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation of
the territories has claimed 539 Palestinian and 23 Israeli lives.
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry issued a statement expressing
disappointment with the EEC's Middle East declaration.
   EEC members are Britain, Belgium, France, Germany, Denmark,
Luxembourg, Spain, Greece, Italy, Portugal, the Netherlands and
Ireland.
</TEXT>
