<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalStorm-Surfers     06-27 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Storm-Surfers,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Galveston Surfers Get Rare Treat From Allison: Surf's Up!</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tropical Storm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While residents of southeastern Texas
remember Tropical Storm Allison for flooded homes and cars, serious
water-lovers will talk about the gnarly waves the radical storm
brought.
   ``This is a dream, right here!'' surfer Scott Cannary, 22, said
gleefully Monday when he rushed to the city's seawall to take
advantage of the rare fast, high waves. ``This is the best time.''
   A few blocks away, Ron Smith, 21, said he and a group of friends
rushed from League City for the same reason that Cannary braved the
storm.
   ``Big waves! Big, big ones!'' he said.
   Smith said Monday's waves were 4 feet high, a vast improvement
over the 1- to 2-foot waves that prevail on the upper Texas coast.
   Lt. Vic Maceo, director of the Galveston County Sheriff's
Department beach patrol, said his staff allowed no swimming on
Galveston Island beaches but would allow experienced surfers in the
water.
   ``You can tell immediately who they are,'' Maceo said.
