<FIRST>r w AM-HotSwitch     06-27 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hot Switch,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Big Wheel' Riding Toys Have Problem Switch, CPSC Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of ``Big Wheel'' riding toys will
replace the ``on'' switch for 39,000 of the battery-powered vehicles
because of possible burns from overheated switches or loss of
control due to stuck switches, the Consumer Product Safey Commission
said Tuesday.
   The CPSC said the free replacement offer by Empire of Carolina
Inc. of Tarboro, N.C., covers toys sold nationwide from 1986 to
1988. The models covered by the replacement offer are Kawasaki KLT
250 ``Prairie Big Wheel,'' Nos. 1215, 1220 and 1223, and
``Sweet-Tee-Nuff Big Wheel,'' No. 1221.
   To get a replacement, owners should call Empire toll-free at
1-800-334-5666, or if in North Carolina, collect at 1-919-823-4111.
Or they can write: Empire Campaign, c@o Empire of Carolina Inc.,
P.O. Box 427, Daniel Street Extension, Tarboro, N.C. 27886.
   The ``on switch'' is on the handlebar and is pushed down to drive
the toy, which can travel up to 5 mph. The toy should stop when the
button is released.
   Empire and the CPSC said they know of five instances in which the
switch overheated or burned out, and one in which the switch stuck
and the operator could not stop the toy. Minor burns were reported
in two of the incidents.
</TEXT>
