<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0677 06-27 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Withdraws Seven Cabinet Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to include with one nomination still active,
scientists turning down environmental job, other info; picks up 11th `_The
environmental'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov bowed to pressure from
the new legislature Tuesday and withdrew seven Cabinet nominations.
It was the first time elected Soviet representatives had kept such
officials from taking office.
   Six of the nominees were rejected in first-ever confirmation
hearings last week by committees of the 542-member Supreme Soviet,
which replaced the old rubber-stamp body this year.
   Ryzhkov also withdrew his nominee, not identified, to head the
Ministry of Instrument-Making, Automation Equipment and Control
Systems, and said he had no nominee to lead the government
environmental agency.
   He could have taken the fight for his first choices to the full
Supreme Soviet this week, but said in a speech to the lawmakers that
he would submit new candidates.
   Tass, the official news agency, said the Supreme Soviet later
confirmed 60 nominees for posts in government ministries and
committees.
   The new Supreme Soviet is the country's first full-time
representative legislature, a branch of the larger Congress of
People's Deputies chosen this spring in the first national
multiple-candidate elections.
   The six nominees rejected after committee hearings were Culture
Minister Vasily G. Zakharov; Gennady P. Bogomyakov, nominee for
minister of the oil and gas industry; Polad A. Polad-Zade for
minister of land reclamation and water management, a controversial
department in charge of dams and canals; Marat V. Gramov for head of
the sports committee; Lira I. Rozenova for the price committee, and
Vladimir G. Gribov for head of the central bank.
   Ryzhkov said candidates for a first deputy premiership and head
of a new Commission on Food and Purchases were withdrawn during
other committee work.
   He indicated the nomination of one first deputy premier, Lev A.
Voronin, still was active but did not say which of the candidates
for the other two deputy premierships, Yuri D. Maslyukov or Vladimir
I. Kalashnikov, was dropped.
   A Supreme Soviet committee rejected Kalashnikov as head of the
food commission, however, so he may have been the one.
   The premier said he had no nominee for the top position at the
State Committee for the Protection of Nature, now held by Fyodor T.
Morgun.
   In response to a question, Ryzhkov said four scientists had been
offered the job but turned it down. He said nothing about Morgun.
   In other action in the Supreme Soviet:
   _ The environmental protection budget will quadruple to about
$612 billion for the next 15 years, and factories will face
pollution fines starting in 1991. U.S. businesses, citizens and the
government spent $71.4 billion in 1987 for pollution abatement, the
U.S. Commerce Department recently reported.
   _ The Supreme Soviet will ``work out a political assessment'' of
the 1979 decision to send Soviet troops into Afghanistan and report
to the next session of the Congress. The Soviet forces, which backed
Kabul in its fight with U.S.-and Pakistan-supported Moslem
guerrillas, were withdrawn in February.
   _ The legislative agenda for this 40-day summer session includes
new laws on consumer protection, inventions, the court system, the
press, taxes, citizen associations, the criminal code and economic
reform, and first readings of new laws on trade unions, youth,
freedom of conscience and religious organizations.
   Some deputies called for consideration of land-owning _ now
reserved exclusively to the government _ and on the state's response
to emergencies. The last was apparently in reference to
congressional debate on the use of troops to clear a demonstration
in Soviet Georgia in April. At least 20 people died in the Georgian
unrest.
   Vladimir Lapygin, chairman of the Supreme Soviet committee on
defense and the KGB, told the newspaper Izvestia the heads of these
agencies will report to his committee. Lapygin also said lawmakers
should consider eliminating the military draft in favor of a
professional army.
</TEXT>
