<DOCNO> AP890627-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionConsent     06-27 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Consent,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion-Consent Law Argued Before State Supreme Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's privacy laws should be
extended to minors, a lawyer told the state Supreme Court Tuesday in
the case of a teen-ager forced to ask a judge to allow an abortion
without parental consent.
   ``The statute clearly fails to protect a minor's privacy right,''
attorney Jerri Blair told the justices. ``A minor who is pregnant
has a right to submit to any medical procedure except abortion under
Florida law.
   ``There is no question it should be applied to the minor's
abortion decision,'' Ms. Blair told reporters later.
   The Florida law requires unmarried minors to get permission from
their parents or a judge before having an abortion.
   The case argued Tuesday began when Ms. Blair's client, a
15-year-old known only as ``T.W.,'' did not want to tell her parents
about her pregnancy _ then in its 11th week _ and sought judicial
permission for an abortion.
   A Lake County judge denied her request last month, saying the
state law was vague and unworkable. An appeals court then ruled the
law unconstitutional, and a series of legal maneuvers landed the
case in the U.S. Supreme Court, which returned the case to state
justices without comment.
   The U.S. Supreme Court has left the law unenforceable until the
Florida high court reviews it.
   Suporters of the law contend it protects the unborn and the right
of parents to supervise their children.
   ``When you elevate the right of privacy over the right to life,
you have elevated an inferior right over a superior right,'' said
Ken Connor, a Tallahassee attorney for Florida Right to Life.
``Without the right to life, there is no right to privacy.''
   Attorney James Bopp Jr. of Terre Haute, Ind., who served as
guardian for the fetus, argued that minors are not mature enough to
make decisions about abortion.
   ``I don't believe the people of Florida intended to subvert
parental rights (or) to subvert the state's traditional interest in
protecting innocent human life, and withdraw the ability of the
state to protect vulnerable minors when they adopted the 1980
Florida right of privacy,'' Bopp said.
   A ruling by the seven justices could be weeks away as the court
begins its annual vacation period next month. The court's decision
could affect thousands of unmarried pregnant teens and possibly set
a broad precedent, attorneys said.
   Similar privacy issues dominate a case pending before the U.S.
Supreme Court and the original 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision giving
women the right to have abortions.
   Before Florida's parental consent law was declared
unconstitutional, 60 teen-agers received judicial permission for an
abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
