<DOCNO> AP890627-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-US     06-27 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-US,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty International Condemns U.S. Death Penalty Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said Tuesday that rulings by
the U.S. Supreme Court upholding the death penalty for youthful or
retarded offenders are a step backward for human rights.
   In two 5-4 votes, the Supreme Court said Monday the
Constitution's ban on cruel and unusual punishment does not prohibit
execution of people who committed crimes as young as 16, or adults
with the reasoning capacity of children.
   ``The imposition of death sentences on juvenile offenders was in
clear contravention of international human rights treaties and
standards including the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights and the American Convention on Human Rights, both
of which the U.S. government signed in 1977 but has not ratified,''
Amnesty International said.
   The London-based group, which won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1977,
said the death penalty was particularly inappropriate for
individuals who had not attained full physical or emotional maturity
at the time of their crimes.
   ``To impose the death penalty in such cases, whether as
retribution or as an intended deterrent, violates basic principles
of humanity,'' the group's statement said.
   Amnesty International noted that 72 countries that retain the
death penalty have abolished it for criminals under the age of 18,
including the Soviet Union, South Africa, Syria, Paraguay and Libya.
   Bangladesh, Pakistan, Iraq and Iran are among the countries that
have executed people who were under 18 at the time of their crimes,
Amnesty International said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
