<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     06-27 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Say They Killed Colonel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels Tuesday took
responsiblity for the assassination of an army colonel and said he
participated in rightist death squads.
   Col. Roberto Rivera, director of the National Firemen's Corps
since June 1, was slain Monday as he drove to work.
   He was previously director of the Public Security Academy and
assistant director of Treasury Police.
   ``Col. Rivera was a military man with a criminal and repressive
trajectory,'' said a rebel communique broadcast on the clandestine
Radio Venceremos. ``His activity was clearly linked to death
squads.''
   A nine-year civil war between the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, known as FMLN, and the U.S.-backed government has
left an estimated 70,000 people dead. Human rights groups say more
than 20,000 people were killed by military-linked rightist death
squads in the early 1980s.
   ``The FMLN reiterates that the `dirty war' actions of the
government against civilans will receive a firm response from the
people in arms,'' said the rebel communique.
   In Washington, the State Department on Tuesday renewed its appeal
to the rebels to negotiate with the government on ending the civil
war in a statement prompted by Monday's slaying.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler noted that Salvadoran
President Alfredo Cristiani has formed a national commission to talk
to the guerrilla movement.
   ``We repeat our call to the FMLN to end the violence in El
Salvador and to enter into negotiations without preconditions aimed
at ending the conflict,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
