<FIRST>r w AM-Women'sShrine     06-27 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Women's Shrine,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Shrine Asked Cigarette Company for Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive director of the National Women's
Hall of Fame said Tuesday that the board had no qualms about
accepting $35,000 from a cigarette company to keep the financially
ailing museum open.
   In fact, Sally Parr said the board of the Seneca Falls, N.Y.,
museum approached Philip Morris Cos. and was rateful for its help.
   But the decision to accept the money has drawn stinging criticism
from a leading feminist who said cigarettes are killing women.
   ``Women's organizations are going to have to stop taking money
from the merchants of death,'' Molly Yard, president of the National
Organization for Women, said Monday.
   Parr said at a news conference Tuesday that the $10,000 in cash
and $25,000 worth of public relations and fund-raising services from
Philip Morris gave the museum ``a starting point to move on.''
   Philip Morris spokeswoman Posie DiSesa said the company didn't
expect any promotion from the museum in exchange for the donation.
   The museum board launched an urgent fund-raising drive June 13,
saying the Hall of Fame would close if $100,000 wasn't raised by
June 30.
   The board announced Monday that the $35,000 donation from Philip
Morris and a $100,000 Gannett Foundation grant would keep the shrine
alive. The private, non-profit educational institute was $68,000 in
debt before the drive.
   The National Women's Hall of Fame, founded in 1968, is in an old
bank building in the upstate New York village that bills itself as
``The Birthplace of Women's Rights.''
   Women's rights pioneer Elizabeth Cady Stanton and 300 other women
met there in 1848 to issue a ``Declaration of Sentiments,'' which
demanded the right to vote, equal schooling and wages.
   Despite her displeasure with the Philip Morris donation, Yard
said it was important to keep the hall open.
   ``It's the only place in the country where there's any attempt to
keep records of leading American women,'' she said.
</TEXT>
