<SECOND>AM-Bush-Fourth,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges Americans to Thank God for Their Freedom on July Fourth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flag Burning, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush urged Americans Tuesday to thank
God for their freedom on the Fourth of July and celebrate ``the
resounding success'' of their 213-year-old experiment in democracy.
   ``To every American citizen, here and abroad, Happy Fourth of
July!'' Bush said in an Independence Day message.
   ``The Fourth of July is a day to pause and thank God that men
such as Thomas Jefferson and Ben Franklin had the strength, courage
and insight to forge a nation predicated upon the noble ideal, `that
all men are created equal, that they are endowed by their creator
with certain unalienable rights,''' Bush said.
   ``After 213 years, Americans can say that the experiment is a
resounding success,'' said Bush. ``The Fourth of July is a time to
rejoice in this success, which has inspired all who seek to break
the shackles of totalitarian rule and breathe in the life-giving air
of liberty.''
   As a boy growing up in Connecticut, ``the Fourth of July
represented the best of holidays. It held the promise of parades,
picnics and fireworks,'' Bush said.
   ``More important, however, it introduced a small boy to the
promise of America,'' said the president. ``Everywhere I turned, I
would see the red, white and blue of our flag.
   ``As a grew older, I realized that the flag has reminded
generations of Americans how fortunate we are to live in a free and
democratic republic,'' said Bush, who said Tuesday he will seek a
constitutional amendment to overturn a Supreme Court ruling that
struck down flag desecration laws. ``It is a banner respected around
the world.''
   Bush will leave Friday for his oceanfront home in Kennebunkport,
Maine, to spend the holiday with family and friends. He will return
to Washington on Wednesday July 5.
</TEXT>
