<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     06-27 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grosz Says He Wants To Quit As Party Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karoly Grosz, his power curbed in a new
four-man leadership dominated by reformers, was quoted Tuesday as
saying he plans to resign as Communist Party chief next year.
   Mai Nap, an independent afternoon daily, quoted Grosz as saying
in an interview he ``will no longer be general secretary'' after
parliamentary elections scheduled for 1990. He has held the post 13
months.
   ``We have to make room for the younger generation,'' the paper
quoted him as saying. ``Obviously, I'll continue to be engaged in
politics at some level, but I never again want to be a general
secretary.''
   Rezsoe Nyers, father of pioneering economic reforms in the late
1960s, was chosen as party chairman Saturday, and a four-man
Presidium was formed to run the party until the Communist Party
Congress scheduled for Oct. 7.
   The paper quoted Grosz as saying the Central Committee had
``agreed that we will need to hold (another) Congress after the
elections as well. It's obvious that there will be a new balance of
forces and a new leadership.''
   Grosz, considered a centrist, has lost standing recently with
contradictory statements.
   He angered other leading Communists, and many other Hungarians,
when he said on television May 30 there was no need to rehabilitate
Imre Nagy, who led the 1956 uprising crushed by Soviet tanks,
because Nagy's execution was ``not a party decision.''
   A day later, party issued a statement that described Nagy as a
forerunner of reform and amounted to de facto rehabilitation. Nagy
since has been reburied with honors.
   Grosz replaced Janos Kadar as party chief in May 1988, heading a
new leadership that seemed to strike a balance between reformers and
more orthodox Communists.
   As reformers gained the upper hand over conservatives wary of
relinquishing power, Grosz jockeyed unsuccessfully for a middle
ground.
   Communists and democratic opposition groups agreed to cooperate
in drafting legislation to govern the first multiparty elections in
more than 40 years, and work began June 13.
   The government has said elections will be held by June of next
year, but there have been increasing calls for the date to be
advanced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
