<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Palau     06-27 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palau,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Compact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday endorsed and sent to the
Senate legislation that would give final approval to a
self-government plan for the Western Pacific islands of Palau.
   The measure, passed on a voice vote, also provides final
authorization for spending of $238 million over the next five years,
including an immediate $36 million payment to cover Palau's debt for
a power plant.
   ``This is a highly responsible act for the United States,'' said
Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., chairman of the House Interior Committee.
   The measure ``brings an honorable end to a very difficult chapter
in the history of the United States in the Western Pacific,'' said
Ron de Lugo, the non-voting House delegate from the Virgin Islands.
   Palau is the last of four parts of the Trust Territory of the
Pacific Islands, created following World War II, to define its
political status. The plan, called the Compact of Free Association,
provides self-government in all areas except defense, which is
reserved for the United States.
   The United States also retains a 50-year right to establish a
military base on Palau should it need an alternative to its current
bases in the Philippines.
   Palau itself has failed in six referendums to approve the
compact, and the bill provides another $200,000 to hold a seventh
referendum.
   The island nation has been troubled by political corruption,
crippling debts and fiscal mismanagement, drug abuse and crumbling
public facilities. The legislation would create a anti-drug program
for Palau and establishes controls for the spending of U.S. aid
money.
   The House acted despite warnings from Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn.,
who argued that the United States doesn't have the money to spend.
``We are playing fast and loose with our budget agreement. We are
squeezing things in and declaring them emergencies,'' he said.
   In a separate action, the House also approved and sent to the
Senate a bill establishing regular diplomatic relations with two
other former Pacific trusteeships, the Marshall Islands and
Micronesia. The measure would elevate the status of the U.S. envoys
in those two island groups to ambassador.
</TEXT>
