<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages     06-27 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnappings May Have Been a Mistake, Hezbollah Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kidnapping of foreigners, 14 of whom
are believed still held in Lebanon, may have been ``a very big
mistake,'' said a spokesman for Shiite Moslems thought to be the
captors' umbrella group.
   Ibrahim Amin, the spokesman for Hezbollah, or Party of God said:
``It is possible that we might feel that some acts might have
involved a very big mistake.
   ``But we have to face our mistakes in the way that preserves and
respects our society,'' Amin said.
   Hezbollah has repeatedly denied involvement in the kidnappings,
and the black-turbaned Amin reiterated those denials at a news
conference. But Western and local intelligence sources have linked
the organization to extremist groups who claim responsibility in
most of the abductions.
   Hezbollah supported the anti-West policies of Iran's late
spiritual leader and founder of the Islamic republic, Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, who died of a heart attack on June 3. It was
unclear whether Hezbollah's attitudes would change with his death.
   Hezbollah has declared support for Iranian President Ali
Khamenei, who was appointed Khomeini's successor as supreme leader.
   Among those held are nine Americans. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
He was kidnapped in Moslem west Beirut on March 16, 1985.
