<FIRST>r a AM-MormonRestoration     06-27 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mormon Restoration,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mormons to Dedicate Restored Jail Where Prophet Shot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARTHAGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Mormons gathered Tuesday to
dedicate a $1 million shrine on the ``hallowed spot'' where church
founder Joseph Smith and his brother, Hyrum, were killed by a mob
145 years ago.
   Mormon Church President Ezra Taft Benson; Jayne Thompson, wife of
Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson, and about 3,000 others attended a
ceremony marking the completed restoration of the old Carthage jail
where Smith died _ a site considered sacred by the world's 6.5
million Mormons.
   ``Few could foresee the future stature of the man whose blood
stained the floor of this jail,'' said Gordon Hinckley, first
counselor to Benson, as he recounted the shooting of the Smiths on
June 27, 1844.
   ``We are grateful for the reconciliation that has come with the
passage of time,'' said Hinckley, who described the founder's death
as ``an epic story of martyrdom.''
   ``This is a hallowed spot,'' Hinckley said.
   The five-room, bullet-riddled jail stands as a reminder of the
religious persecution of the Mormons and the hatred that drove them
from the Mississippi River town of Nauvoo, 30 miles west, he said.
   The two-story stone jail, with its two cells and the bedroom
where the Smiths died, has been restored to its 1844 appearance.
   Bullet holes are still visible in the bedroom door and Hyrum
Smith's blood-stained cloths are on display, along with a statue of
the Smiths and six slate monuments inscribed with quotes from Joseph
Smith.
   Renovation of the jail, built in 1840, was completed to coincide
with the 150th anniversary of the Mormon's settlement in Nauvoo, a
town of about 1,100 located 200 miles north of St. Louis that
briefly was home to Smith's followers _ the core of the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Sains.
   Smith and his congregation arrived in Nauvoo in 1839, when the
town was named Commerce.
   They settled on 1,000 acres in the swamp ``flats'' below the
town's main business district. The land was drained and divided into
four-acre farm plots. Each member was given an acre for a house,
barn and a few animals.
   Within a few years, a city of 15,000 sprang from the swamp.
   Named Nauvoo by the Mormons _ from the Hebrew for ``beautiful
location'' _ it rivaled Chicago as the largest city in Ilinois. A
huge, limestone temple was built on a bluff overlooking the town.
   But the friction with outsiders that had forced Smith to leave
other towns followed the settlers into Illinois.
   Mormons clashed with local residents who rejected Smith's claims
that he had spoken with God, been visited by angels and was a
prophet.
   The conflict eventually led to the arrest of the Smiths and two
associates.
   They were awaiting trial in Carthage when the jail was stormed by
a mob estimated by some accounts at 125.
   ``The historic preservation of this site will foster an ongoing
growth of tolerance which is Illinois and America,'' Mrs. Thompson
said.
   After the deaths of the Smiths, Brigham Young assumed leadership
of the church and two years later led a mass exodus west from
Nauvoo, eventually settling in Salt Lake City.
</TEXT>
