<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     06-27 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Warns of Action Against Unauthorized Publications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military government said on
government radio and television Monday that it will act under
martial law to stop unauthorized organizations from printing and
distributing books and pamphlets.
   The announcement said there were ``48 unauthorized organizations
engaged in activities aimed at disturbing peace and tranquility in
the country and also printing and distributing pamphlets illegally.''
   The government added that ``51 similar unauthorized organizations
are also operating in the name of students organizations.''
   ``Legally registered political and other organizations can apply
for registration under the ... law .. and ask for exemption to print
and distribute books and pamphlets purely for election purposes,''
it said.
   It said 226 political parties were registered with the Election
Commission and 57 social organizations with the Ministry of Home and
Religious Affairs.
   The military government, which seized power last September, has
promised a general election next year,
   Karen rebel sources in Mae Sot, Thailand, said up to 900 Burmese
soldiers backed by mortar and artillery fire attacked Karen
guerrilla positions close to the Thai frontier before dawn Tuesday.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said heavy
fighting followed at the Karen base of Pa Loo, about eight miles
south of Mae Sot.
   Soldiers fired hundreds of mortar and artillery shells into Pa
Loo and a nearby camp at Kaw Moo Ra, they said. The Moei River
separates the camps from Thailand.
   More than 50 shells fell into Thailand near Pa Loo and Burmese
machine-gun fire hit three houses and a Buddhist temple in Mae Kone
Kane village, Thai border patrol police said, adding that Thai
security forces returned fire.
   No casualty reports were available.
   The Karens are among a dozen ethnic groups in Burma which for 40
years have fought for greater autonomy. The Karens, with about 8,000
armed fighters, are the largest group.
   Government forces began a major campaign against the Karens last
October.
</TEXT>
