<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-27 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms In Texas And Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms from the remnants of Tropical Storm
Allison spread heavy rain Tuesday over southeastern Texas and
western Louisiana, and thunderstorms were scattered along the Ohio
Valley.
   In the East, Baltimore posted a record-tying high of 98 degrees.
   The highest sustained wind speed associated with the tropical
depression was near 35 mph, with gusts to 45 mph in heavy squalls
along the extreme upper Texas coast. Tides 2 to 3 feet above normal
along the upper Texas coast and the western coast of Louisiana were
expected to slowly decrease during the night.
   Heavier rain amounts for the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
3.95 inches at Lake Charles, La., 2.65 inches at Shreveport, La.,
2.57 inches at Lufkin, Texas, and 1.27 inches at Fort Polk, La.
   A thunderstorm in southwestern Louisiana unleashed a tornado at
Hackberry that destroyed three to four houses and damaged 12 others,
the National Weather Service said. A thunderstorm at Lake Charles
produced high wind which damaged the roof of a hangar and blew the
roofs off two smaller buildings.
   The Shreveport, La., fire department reported that it rescued a
woman whose car slipped into a flooded irrigation ditch. Rescue
personnel said she was in good condition at a local hospital.
   Ahead of a cold front in the upper Midwest, showers and
thunderstorms were scattered from the middle Mississippi Valley to
the central Appalachians, the upper Ohio Valley and the lower Great
Lakes region.
   Thunderstorms packing high winds damaged houses, uprooted trees
and knocked down power lines in Wapakoneta, Ohio. Officials said no
injuries were reported.
   ``At first it started real hard rain. You couldn't see across the
street,'' said Wapakoneta resident Adis Roop. `Then here come the
trees. I ran for the house, I couldn't hardly get through the door.
The suction pulled me back out.''
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from the central
Gulf Coast to southern Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Bremerton, Wash., to 102 at Phoenix, Ariz. The nation's
low was not supplied by the weather service.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from eastern Oklahoma and eastern Texas to the Atlantic Coast
states. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from Montana to Minnesota and Iowa.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted from northern New England to the
Great Lakes, and from western Montana to the northern Pacific Coast
and along the California coast; in the lower 90s across the southern
half of the Atlantic Coast region, and across much of the area from
southern and central interior California to the great Plains region;
and above 100 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
