<DOCNO> AP890627-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Investor     06-27 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Investor,0401</SECOND>
<UNK>Brazilian Police File Charges Against Super-Investor</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillionaire investor linked to a
financial scandal that shook Brazil's stock markets has been charged
on two counts of financial wrongdoing, police said Tuesday.
   Police questioned Nahas Monday night about his role in the
scandal, but the charges filed were unrelated to the crisis, which
led to the closing of six brokerage houses, police spokesman Mauro
Ament said from Brasilia, the capital.
   Nahas is accused of trying to illegally take dollars out of the
country in 1987 and of violating the Financial System Law in 1983,
Ament said.
   Ament said that in December, 1987, police at Sao Paulo's
International Airport found $20,000 in Nahas' suitcase as he was
about to board a plane for London. By law, Brazilians then were only
allowed to take $1,000.
   In 1983, a construction firm owned by Nahas borrowed the
equivalent of $12 million from the Sogeral Bank, of which he was a
major shareholder. ``This was a violation of the Financial System
Law, which prohibits this kind of transaction,'' Ament said.
   The spokesman said that if convicted on the charges, Nahas faces
an 11-year jail term.
   Federal police also questioned Nahas on his alleged role in the
stock market scandal that broke June 9, but Ament said there was
still insufficeint evidence to bring charges against the investor.
   Nahas bounced $31 million in checks to pay for highly speculative
deals on the Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange, according to the
Brazilian Securities Commission.
   On June 12, the government closed all of Brazil's nine stock
markets to avoid panic among investors. Nahas was prohibited from
leaving the country. The market reopened the next day.
   The government has closed six brokerage houses involved in the
scandal, including one owned by Elmo Camoes, former president of the
Central Bank. Camoes resigned shortly before his brokerage was
closed.
   Nahas, a Lebanese immigrant whose business interests range from
mining and farming to real estate and insurance, is a common sight
in Brazilian society pages. In 1984 he hosted Saudi Arabian arms
merchant Adnan Khashoggi on a visit to Brazil.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission of the United States
also has linked Nahas with Texas billionaires Nelson Bunker Hunt and
William Herbert Hunt in their ill-fated try to corner the world's
silver bullion market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
