<FIRST>r w AM-HonorariaLimit     06-27 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honoraria Limit,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Council OKs Income Limit for City Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Council approved
legislation Tuesday to sharply limit outside income for city
officeholders, a move some say is designed to prevent the Rev. Jesse
Jackson from running for mayor.
   The bill, sponsored by council member John Ray and approved on an
11-2 vote, sets a $10,000 limit on income from speeches for the
mayor and council chairman and includes an amendment by council
Chairman David Clarke that limits the mayor or council chairman to
$10,000 income from book royalties.
   Both Ray and Clarke are running for mayor in the 1990 race.
Incumbent Marion Barry has not said whether he will seek re-election.
   Jackson, who earns most of his income from speeches, has not
ruled out running for the $82,500-per-year post.
   ``I am awfully suspicious when two announced candidates put
together legislation to keep someone from running,'' said council
member Frank Smith.
   ``We can ... say that this is a Jesse Jackson bill for sure,''
said council member Nadine Winter. ``We have railroaded a piece of
legislation in 19 days only because the political campaign is
heating up, and it seems to me we have a problem here.''
   Smith and council member Betty Ann Kane voted against the measure.
   Ray denied the bill was meant to keep Jackson off the ballot and
said he began working on it after constituents complained last year
when the council voted itself a pay raise.
   Council member H.R. Crawford said the honoraria limit would be an
unfamiliar concept for most city officials.
   ``From what I hear in the community, most people would pay us
$10,000 only to be quiet,'' Crawford said.
</TEXT>
