<FIRST>r i AM-ProtesterKilled     06-27 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Protester Killed,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Killed When National Guardsmen Fire on Peasant Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARQUEIROS, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National guardsmen opened fire on
villagers protesting a mining operation, fatally wounding a young
man, officials reported Tuesday.
   A National Republican Guard spokesmen said six shots were fired
after a guardsman was injured Monday by villagers throwing stones.
   Carlos Simoes, 20, was shot in the head and taken to a hospital
in Oporto, 45 miles away, where he died Tuesday.
   More than 200 residents of this northern village fought with
about 80 armed guardsmen during the protest.
   Portugal's National Republican Guard is a paramilitary police
force, similar to Spain's Civil Guard, that operates mainly in rural
areas.
   Villagers say a nearby mine, where porcelain clay is extracted,
pollutes the air and water and uses machinery that violates noise
restrictions.
   The guard spokesman, whose name was withheld in keeping with
regulation, said the Interior Ministry had ordered an investigation
of the use of firearms in the confrontation.
   At least 12 other villagers and a guardsman were treated at
hospitals for injuries siffered in the fighting. Protesters fled
into nearby cafes and houses.
   A villager reached by telephone from Lisbon on Tuesday said
Barqueiros was calm and ``we're in mourning.'' Witnesses said the
mine was operating.
   In a statement issued Monday, the Mibal mining company said it
would not be ``intimidated by ... threats in clear disrespect of the
law and democracy.''
   Residents of Barqueiros boycotted European Parliament elections
this month as part of their protest.
</TEXT>
