<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchResignation     06-27 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Resignation,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Church Council Quits, His ``Dream'' For It Rebuffed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the National Council of Churches said
Tuesday he's quitting because ``ecumenical dreams'' for the council
as a more unifying movement have been blocked.
   The Rev. Arie R. Brouwer said that in recent struggles over
council objectives, ``differences in dreams led to the sharpness of
the conflict,'' with him favoring fuller integration of the
council's operational units.
   ``I can do no more in this position to fulfill'' that goal, he
told a conference.
   Brouwer, 53, said he would step down Friday as the council's
general secretary, a post he has held for four and a half years, the
last two embroiled in turmoil over future council directions.
   The council, the country's largest ecumenical organization,
includes most major Protestant and Eastern Orthodox denominations
totaling more than 40 million members.
   Brouwer, a tall, quiet-spoken Midwesterner from Iowa and a
clergyman in the Reformed Church in America, emphasized he was not
leaving the council office ``in a spirit of anger or bitterness.''
   The conflict over goals boiled to a near breaking point at a May
meeting in Lexington, Ky., of the council's governing board, which
split evenly _ 57 votes to 57 _ over a move to oust Brouwer.
   He said his resignation ``is a direct result of events
precipitated'' at that meeting, which initiated steps to consolidate
11 council units into four, each run by church representatives
largely independent of other units.
   Brouwer said this essentially perpetuated the past loosely linked
units, mostly setting their own policies.
   He had clashed sharply with Church World Service, the council's
relief arm and largest operational unit, in trying to bring it into
joint administration, efforts that CWS strongly resisted.
   At the Lexington meeting, Brouwer sharply delineated the
conflict, denouncing a tide of ``rumors, innuendo and false
charges'' against him. Critics had called Brouwer harsh and
autocratic.
   He said the problem was that he dared speak the truth. ``The
powerful are not accustomed to such behavior and they are outraged.
They will not have it.''
   Brouwer said he spoke out strongly about the matter then because
``I wanted to set it openly before the entire community,'' knowing
that doing so involved ``personal vulnerability and professional
risk.''
   The tie vote over his continuing in his post showed that the
governing board could not resolve the issues, he said, and in
reflecting about the impasse, he concluded he should resign.
   ``Under those circumstances, I could not carry further the work
which is essential to my vocational fulfillment,'' he said in a
written statement.
   ``To outside observers, this must surely seem to be a time of
great brokenness for the council. It is, but it is also a time of
healing and binding. The experiences of the past few weeks have in
some ways brought us closer together.''
   Brouwer was chief executive of the Reformed Church in America
before he took the council post in 1985 at a time when a special
panel had presented plans for making the council a closer-knit
``communion of communions.''
   Acknowleging that he had been rebuffed in trying to implement
that larger dream, he added, ``That does not, however, mean that I
am giving up on those dreams or on the council.''
   A statement by other council officers said, ``We profoundly
regret the developments in our life together that now deprive our
community of Arie's leadership.''
   The Rev. Patricia McClurg, a Presbyterian and the council's
titular president, said there has been a ``great deal of hurt'' in
the conflict, and the council wanted to move forward toward greater
unity, but she added:
   ``This was not the right time. We didn't learn to do it quickly
enough. We've had some rough sledding. But we haven't given up.''
   The Rev. James Hamilton, a United Methodist and the council's
Washinton, D.C. public-policy representative, was named as the
council's acting general secretary until Brouwer's successor is
chosen.
</TEXT>
