<FIRST>u a AM-OwlCompromise     06-27 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owl Compromise,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Reject Plan, Want More Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists on Tuesday rejected a
compromise plan that would have preserved the best Northwest forest
land for the rare Northern spotted owl while freeing enough timber
to keep mills operating.
   The environmental groups, however, said they were willing to
continue negotiating toward a solution that would overcome a bitter
court battle, which has tied up billions of board feet of timber on
federal lands.
   ``We are talking about the extinction of a species and shouldn't
act precipitously,'' said Andy Kerr, conservation director for the
Oregon Natural Resources Council. ``Conservationists, like misers,
may be hell to live with, but we make great ancestors.''
   Timber industry officials had said they were willing to accept
the compromise offered Saturday by members of the Oregon
congressional delegation and Gov. Neil Goldschmidt.
   The proposal called for a short-term increase in the number of
trees that could be cut on federal land in Oregon and Washington
while protecting some of the older forests where the rare Northern
spotted owl nests.
   A statement issued by the environmental groups said they could
not accept the timber harvest figures in the compromise without more
information.
   ``The proposal was a bittersweet pill,'' Robert L. Spence,
chairman of the Northwest Forest Resources Council, said at a news
conference in Seattle. ``The simple truth is that less timber means
fewer jobs.''
   In Washington, D.C., Rep. Bob Smith, R-Ore., reacted angrily to
the rejection, while Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., expressed hopes for an
eventual resolution.
   ``All bets are off,'' said Smith, who has proposed legislation to
allow unrestricted logging for five years while the status of the
owl is studied more.
   ``No doors are closed,'' said AuCoin spokeswoman Rachael Gorlin.
``We're in touch with everyone.''
   The compromise was offered at the so-called spotted owl summit
meeting in Salem among representatives of the timber industry,
environmentalists, all seven members of Oregon's congressional
delegation and Gov. Neil Goldschmidt.
</TEXT>
