<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Khomeini     06-27 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Khomeini,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputies Want Khomeini's Son To Run For Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tehran Radio said Tuesday that 205 of the
270 deputies in Iran's Parliament have asked Ahmad Khomeini, son of
the late revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, to run
for Parliament.
   Political foes said it was intended to avert an open power
struggle between radicals led by Ahmad Khomeini and pragmatists led
by Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, the only announced
candidate in the July 28 presidential election.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the Tehran
Times daily as saying the deputies suggested that Ahmad Khomeini
become speaker if he wins an election in Rafsanjani's Tehran
constituency.
   Rafsanjani, who polled 1.3 million votes in last year's
parliamentary election, will have to give up his seat in the Majlis,
or parliament, to run for president. No date has been set for the
by-election.
   ``We call upon your excellency to be in the Majlis ... to become
a cause of strength, encouragement and guidance for this important
pillar of legislation in the arena of the country's decisions,'' the
radio quoted the deputies as saying in a letter to Ahmad Khomeini.
   The Iranian news media were monitored in Nicosia.
   The Iraq-based Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors,
opposition group said the deputies' offer was aimed at leaving
Rafsajani a clear run.
   Speculation has grown that the politically ambitious Ahmad
Khomeini, 43, would declare himself a candidate for president to run
against Rafsanjani.
   Many analysts said that would lead to an open fight for power
between the pragmatists and their radical rivals.
   The Mujahedeen said in a statement telexed from their Baghdad
headquarters to The Associated Press in Nicosia: ``Ahmad has told
his aides that if Rafsanjani becomes president, that would lead to
splits within the regime and its disintegration.''
   It said the deputies sent the letter to Ahmad on Sunday and that
Rafsanjani was a signatory.
   ``The letter ... reflects the deputies' profound fears that any
factional alignment in the presidential elections would lead to the
disintegration of the whole regime'' following Ayatollah Khomeini's
death June 3, the Mujahedeen said.
   Analysts believe that if Rafsanjani is elected president, he will
take over the day-to-day running of Iran. Once entrenched, his
pragmatic faction is expected to maneuver to loosen the government's
grip on the economy and to mend relations with the West.
   Such policies are anathema to the radicals. The Mujahedeen say
the radicals are engineering to promote Ahmad Khomeini in the
hierarchy to curb the power of their rival camp.
   The younger Khomeini, a low-ranking clergyman, has held no
official position, but he was a close aide to his father and
controlled access to him.
</TEXT>
