<HEAD>Philippine Communist Army Admits Massacre But Blames Other Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVAO CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist New People's Army
acknowledged on Tuesday that its rebel fighters killed 39 villagers
at a church over the weekend, but said anti-communist vigilantes
among the victims fired first.
   Officials reported at least eight people wounded in the encounter
Sunday at the United Church of Christ chapel in Rano, 640 miles
southeast of Manila, and said two of those killed, a Protestant lay
leader and his brother, were beheaded.
   The NPA has been fighting for 20 years to establish a communist
state in the Philippines.
   A church official in Manila said all 39 people killed were
members of the congregation.
   A survivor said two rebels also were killed, but military
officials said the guerrillas apparently carried away their dead.
   An NPA statement, distributed to reporters in Davao City,
expressed regret over the deaths of women and children. It said
rebels gave some wounded first aid.
   The statement said 24 guerrillas entered Rano ``to hold a
dialogue with the residents,'' many of whom were also members of an
anti-Marxist vigilante group.
   It said the rebels asked the vigilante commander to leave the
chapel ``and offered a peace dialogue.''
   ``But they answered back with hostility and attacked the team,''
the statement said. ``What occurred at Rano was more of self-defense
than attack. The NPA ... had no alternative but to fight back.''
   Lt. Col. Jose Maneja, deputy commander of Davao del Sur province,
said on Monday, that the bloodshed came after about 100 guerrillas
entered the village looking for the vigilantes' leader.
