<FIRST>u a AM-AIDS-SecretTests     06-27 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Secret Tests,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Conducting Trial Of Chinese AIDS Drug</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration announced
Tuesday it is investigating doctors in several U.S. cities who are
testing an AIDS drug from China without federal approval.
   Nine doctors in Los Angeles, San Francisco and New York City have
treated 42 patients with Compound Q, imported from China with the
help of couriers who in some cases bribed Chinese government
officials, doctors said Monday. Three patients showed adverse
reactions and one died Saturday.
   Compound Q is the name AIDS researchers have given to
trichosanthin, a protein from the root of a cucumberlike plant that
Chinese doctors have used to induce abortions and to treat cancer
since the third century.
   Dr. Paul Rothman, one of the doctors in the underground testing,
said that observations of 15 patients in Los Angeles indicated the
drug ``appears to be the most effective AIDS medication available or
on the horizon.''
   ``We would have liked to have done this study formally, and with
the approval of the FDA,'' he said. ``But one person dies from AIDS
every 30 minutes. We felt that as long as we proceeded on a rigorous
scientific basis, we would be on very strong ground.''
   The FDA, under its so-called compassionate use decision, allows
individuals to import ``personal use'' quantities of experimental
drugs. The supplies must be no more than enough for one individual
use for three months. Large-scale importation of unapproved products
for commercial use is prohibited. Violating FDA policy on
distributing unapproved drugs could result in seizure of the
material; cease and desist orders; or, in rare cases, mostly
involving for-profit schemes, criminal penalties.
   The agency said drug testing must be done under its scrutiny.
   ``We will be investigating this matter, to see just what has
occurred,'' said FDA spokesman Brad Stone in Washington.
   The FDA has approved only one drug, AZT, to treat AIDS, and side
effects keep many patients from taking it.
   The FDA in April approved testing on AIDS patients of GLQ223, a
highly purified form of trichosanthin developed at the University of
California at San Francisco and Genelabs of Redwood City, Calif.
   At the time, Genelabs warned that AIDS patients should not turn
to China to get the active ingredient because it might have toxic
side effects.
   Some AIDS activists charged that the university and Genelabs were
taking that position to protect an agreement giving their financial
backer, the Swiss pharmaceutical company Sandoz Ltd., exclusive
rights to market GLQ223.
   At least one doctor not involved in the underground testing said
the extreme side effects of Compound Q could have contributed to the
death Saturday of an AIDS patient at San Francisco's Mount Zion
Hospital.
   That was denied by Martin Delaney, co-director of Project Inform,
a San Francisco AIDS education group that organized the network of
doctors in the underground testing.
   ``But I want to stress that this is not herbal tea,'' said
Delaney. ``This is radical chemotherapy. Some of the patients have
had a very rough ride.''
   San Francisco immunologist, Dr. Alan Levin, who helped set up the
study of Compound Q, said the program is at least six months ahead
of mainline research on the drug's efficacy and contended he could
have dosage recommendations within three months.
   ``From our tests, we'll have better scientific data in 10 percent
of time and 1 percent of the cost it is taking regular science to do
the job,'' said Levin. He and his wife, Dr. Vera Byers, designed the
trial.
   ``Our scientific (procedures) are very good and rigorous,'' said
Levin. ``I resent people calling us underground, illegal or guerilla
groups. We're not amateurs. We're first-class doctors.''
   Levin said lawyers for doctors involved in the program had
informed FDA officials earlier this spring of the treatment trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0197 </DOCNO>
