<HEAD>Frank Trapani, Jazz Trumpeter, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Trapani, a longtime jazz trumpeter with
the Dukes of Dixieland, has died of a blood clot to the lungs. He
was 52.
   Trapani died Monday at a hospital. He will be given a traditional
jazz funeral on Thursday.
   ``Frank was one of the greatest trumpeters in town,'' said John
Shoup, manager of the Dukes of Dixieland. ``He was a true New
Orleans player. But in the same breath he could play all styles of
music.''
   Trapani played with the orchestras of Charlie Barnett, Les Elgard
and Billy May, as well as with artists such as Pearl Bailey, Tony
Bennett, Lou Rawls and Quincy Jones.
   He was lead trumpeter with the Dick Stabile Orchestra in New
Orleans for 12 years until 1974, when he joined the Dukes of
Dixieland.
   For the past 12 years he was the Dukes' front man, the musician
who introduced each number to the audience.
   Survivors include his wife, four children and several
grandchildren.
