<HEAD>Blasts Injures 10 Officers Probing Fireworks in LA's Koreatown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with resident booked for investigation of
possession of explosives, bomb squad detonated more fireworks, building
damage estimate, one officer remains hospitalized. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Koreatown apartment exploded in flames
Tuesday as police investigated a stash of fireworks, injuring 10
police officers. A resident was later arrested for allegedly
possessing explosives.
   After the blast, a bomb squad detonated more explosives at the
two-story Victorian building in city's Koreatown section, said
police Officer Margie Reid.
   ``There was a large cache of fireworks,'' Reid said. ``They were
there on a follow-up investigation because a guy showed up at the
hospital with the fingers blown off his hands.''
   Gary Wexler, 39, was later arrested and booked for investigation
of possession of explosives after treatment at Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center for severed fingers.
   Bomb squad experts Robert Gollhofer, 46, and Dan Johnson, 34,
were inside the apartment when the 6:14 a.m. explosion occurred and
suffered cuts, burns and chest injuries. Johnson was being kept in a
hospital overnight, Reid said.
   Six officers were treated at hospitals for temporary hearing loss
and two others were treated at the scene of the explosion, Reid said.
   The officers were in the building investigating a minor fireworks
explosion several hours earlier that had severed part of Wexler's
hand. Wexler said he held a firecracker too long.
   About 35 firefighters battled the blaze at the six-unit apartment
house, about five miles west of downtown, after the blast, said Fire
Department spokesman Jim Williamson. It took a half-hour to
extinguish the fire. Damage was estimated at $140,000.
