<FIRST>r a AM-USCRecords     06-27 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USC Records,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>USC Foundation Appeals Judge's Order to Open Records To Public</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of South Carolina foundation
filed an appeal with the state Supreme Court on Tuesday in an effort
to keep its records from being opened to the public.
   Circuit Judge Carol Connor on Monday ordered the Carolina
Research and Development Foundation to open its records as a result
of a 1987 lawsuit filed by The Associated Press and The Greenville
News.
   The news organizations requested access to the records under the
state's Freedom of Information Act, which requires, with some
exceptions, that public bodies open their records and meetings to
the public.
   The foundation was established as a non-profit corporation to
engage in land acquisition and development for the university.
   In their lawsuit, the news organizations said the foundation had
received and spent more than $28 million in public funds.
   Foundation attorneys argued that the foundation is a private
entity separate from the university and thus is unaffected by the
law's disclosure provisions.
   But Ms. Connor agreed with the AP and The News, ruling June 13
that the foundation was subject to the Freedom of Information Act.
On Monday, Ms. Connor acted on the written order that she had
instructed the news organizations' attorneys to prepare in the
earlier ruling.
   Attorneys for the foundation filed a motion in circuit court
Tuesday requesting a stay of the order so that the foundation's
records could not be opened while the appeal was being considered.
   The judge said the ruling did not necessarily apply to all
foundations related to state schools or to businesses that receive
public money.
</TEXT>
