<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Soviet 3rdLd-Writethru a0799 06-27 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0799,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Israeli Flight Brings Victims of Armenian Earthquake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with details of survivors arrival,
quotes, other. CORRECTS figures for survivors, quake homeless. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's national airline made its first
direct flight to the Soviet Union on Tuesday and brought 61
survivors of the Armenian earthquake to Israel for six weeks of
treatment.
   The 49 amputees and 12 victims suffering from multiple fractures,
known as the ``crush syndrome,'' came slowly down the ramp. Those
able to walk supported themselves with crutches as they limped off,
taking their first look at the Jewish state that gathered them in
for six weeks of medical treatment.
   The El Al Boeing 757 took off for Yerevan, the capital of the
Soviet Armenian republic, at 1:30 p.m. and returned to Ben Gurion
airport from its historic flight nine hours later.
   Israeli officials and Archbishop Kerkin Kazanjian, head of the
Armenian Church in Jerusalem, greeted the survivors. Israeli
immigrants from Armenia brought flowers.
   Health Minister Yaakov Tzur told reporters at the airport, ``This
definitely shows we are experiencing a new relationship with the
Soviet Union.''
   Moscow cut diplomatic relations with Israel after the 1967 Middle
East war in a show of solidarity with Arab nations. The Soviet Union
and Israel exchanged low-level consular delegations in 1987.
   The Armenian patients looked confused and smiled uneasily upon
their arrival. During the 2{-hour flight from Soviet Armenia, many
burst into tears recalling the ordeal of the Dec. 7 earthquake that
left an estimated 25,000 dead, many thousands injured and 500,000
homeless.
   ``I lost 18 classmates in the earthquake,'' said 17-year-old Egor
Khatchaturian of hard-hit Spitak.
   ``They told me a week ago that I was going to Israel. I feel very
well. I hope they will make a prosthesis for me,'' he said.
   Khatchaturian, who lost his left leg, could not recall what he
did after the quake and wept the moment the disaster was mentioned.
   The youth was traveling alone, his parents back in Armenia.
Clutching his crutches, he sat silently in an armchair, dressed in
blue sports jacket and blue hat.
   An Armenian team of two doctors and four nurses accompanied the
victims. They will be trained in Israel to provide the pateints with
follow-up treatment.
   In Yerevan, Armenian officials held a reception for the Israeli
group and laid out cheese, meat, vodka and Armenian cognac.
   On the main table, an Israeli flag stood beside the red-and-blue
Armenian flag. The restaurant band played Hava Nagila, the popular
Israeli tune, as officials of the American Jewish Joint Distribution
Committee performed a lively dance.
   ``I hope the time will come when planeloads like yours will land
in Yerevan without any disaster having prompted their visit,'' said
Narine Balayan, the Armenian minister of social affairs who acted as
host.
   The mood grew quieter as survivors emerged one by one from the
main building and were carried onto the plane. A bearded Armenian
approached and made the sign of cross on their foreheads.
   ``Go with God,'' somebody muttered.
   The New-York based JDC, a Jewish relief group, sponsored the
mission after collecting about $500,000 in donations. The money will
be used to build a rehabilitation clinic in Leninacan, Armenia, and
to bring victims for treatment in Israel.
   Transport Minister Moshe Katzav saw off the flight to Yerevan and
described it as a new stage in the thawing relations between the two
countries.
   Katzav said, ``It is primarily a humanitarian operation, but
Israel is interested and is looking forward to a resumption of
diplomatic relations with the Soviet Union.''
   The plane also carried to Armenia 10 tons of medicine and medical
equipment accidently shipped to Israel by a Dutch relief agency, a
Jerusalem municipal spokeswoman said.
   Israel sent military medics to the Soviet Union during the last
year to help victims of the Armenian earthquake and of a rail
disaster in the Ural Mountains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
