<DOCNO> AP890627-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv28   06-27 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 28 ,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, June 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Where Are Automotive Stocks Headed?</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Through marketing ingenuity, incentives, good
design, improved quality and sheer persistence, automakers have
managed to stretch their selling cycle long beyond its usual
lifespan.
   Now they are faced with another situation: With the delayed but
inevitable end of their growth cycle appearing on the horizon, can
they manage to maintain their stock prices until the next upturn?
   Automaking is a cyclical industry, meaning it has at least as
many ups and downs as the economy itself. The pattern is as distinct
as in real estate: a rising demand, overproduction, big inventories,
a downturn and a recovery.
   It's been a bit different this time. Amid intense competition,
the carmakers developed techniques to shift the production mix _
cars vs. trucks, for example _ offer discounts and below-market
interest rates, and fine-tune production.
   In so doing they demonstrated that the cycle can indeed be
stretched, if only to a point. Now, with indications it could snap _
July output may be at an annual rate of only 5 million cars, lowest
for any month since 1982 _ you might think the appeal of automaker
stocks would fall. But it might not.
   With industry earnings heading for a second-half decline,
automotive stocks still remain in many portfolios, one reason being
that analysts believe the automakers might be able to do for their
stocks what they did for their sales.
   How do you keep stock prices up?
   _By using the money you earned in the good times to buy back your
stocks, as General Motors and Ford are doing, thus tending to
maintain the supply-demand ratio.
   _By maintaining dividends at a rate higher than most blue chips.
General Motors current dividend yield is 6.6 percent, Ford's 6.2
percent and Chrysler's 4.8 percent.
   _By making operations more efficient, thus buffering earnings to
some degree against a sales downturn.
   Ford often is cited as the best example of improved operating
efficiency. Moreover, it chose to meet demand in the good days by
expanding overtime rather than expanding plants. It costs less to
reduce overtime than to close a plant.
   Still another factor, low price-earnings ratios, conceivably
could protect share prices. GM sells for six times earnings, Ford
four and Chrysler five. For the market as a whole, the P-E is in the
double digits.
   Reflecting some of these considerations, The Value Line
Investment Survey offers these views of the Big Three automakers on
the eve of a sales downturn:
   GENERAL MOTORS. ``We look for negative quarterly matchups for the
remainder of `89, and expect the full-year's earnings to decline by
about 12 percent ...
   These shares have impressive total return potential for the
three- to five-year term. In the meantime, (they) provide an
above-average yield based on a secure payout ....''
   FORD. ``We expect Ford shares to keep pace with the market in the
year ahead, protected from most downside risk by a secure dividend
that provides an attractive yield.''
   CHRYSLER. ``Patient investors should keep this stock in mind.
Although recent earnings comparisons suggest the stock is only
likely to be an average performer in the year ahead, we project
sharply improved earnings for the company by 1992-1994.
   If it turns out that way, the major automakers may have succeeded
not just in muting the ups and downs of the car market but of the
stock market too.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, June 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Lewis Adv29   06-27 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Lewis, Adv 29,0842</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs, June 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Goodness, Gracious It's Jerry Lee Lewis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Great Balls of Fire'' opens June 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1 of June 26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drugs, booze, divorces and deaths may
have softened the cockiness just a bit, but pioneer rocker Jerry Lee
Lewis still has plenty left as he tries for a recording comeback
spurred by a new movie on his tumultuous life.
   ``I'm as good as I ever was, if not better,'' Lewis said about
recent performances and his soundtrack for the movie ``Great Balls
of Fire,'' starring Dennis Quaid.
   The soundtrack demonstrates that Lewis still knows how to rock
'n' roll, with remakes of such classics as ``Whole Lotta Shakin'
Goin' On'' and ``Great Balls of Fire.''
   As for the movie itself, Lewis said he enjoyed Quaid's acting but
didn't give too many points to accuracy. ``This is a movie, and it
needs to be accepted as just a movie.''
   Initially, there was talk that Quaid, who has his own band, would
perform at least some of the songs in the movie. Lewis had to
audition to get the job.
   ``All the way on the plane he was saying, `This is ridiculous.
Jerry Lee auditioning for himself.' But he pulled it off great,''
said his former manager, Jerry Schilling.
   Schilling is also creative projects manager for the Graceland
Division of Elvis Presley Enterprises. He and Lewis parted this year
after Lewis was quoted in print as calling Presley a dummy who
wasted his talent.
   ``Jerry Lee says some things that can be very damaging. A lot of
times, he's striking out at himself,'' Schilling said.
   Lewis wants to record again _ if he can do it his way.
   With his pumpin' piano and wild stage antics, Lewis was at the
top of the rock world in the late 1950s.
   Presley, then the undisputed king of rock 'n' roll, had been
drafted into the Army, and Lewis was regarded as a possible
contender for Presley's crown. But his rocket to fame, launched by
records cut at the old Sun Studio in Memphis, was deflected by a
scandal over his marriage to 13-year-old cousin Myra Brown.
   ``It totally destroyed his career,'' said the former Mrs. Lewis,
now Myra Williams. ``He went from making $10,000 a night to $200 a
night. That's starvation wages when you're trying to travel on the
road and pay a band.''
   Lewis, then 22, was advised to keep the marriage quiet, but he
insisted on showing off his young bride on a concert tour to
England. Lewis knew the marriage would upset people, but he didn't
care. The reaction, however, was stronger than expected. ``It didn't
quite go like I thought it was going to go,'' he said.
   ``Jerry has been headstrong all his life,'' Williams said. ``You
just couldn't tell him anything. You couldn't stop him from doing
anything.''
   Now married to a real estate broker in Atlanta, Williams wrote
the book on which the movie is based.
   At 53, Lewis has been on the road all of his life, sometimes
playing 200 or more dates a year. And though he's had long dry
spells between records, and often found himself snarled by tangled
finances and business squabbles, his stage show has kept its fire.
   His recording career, which peaked in the 1950s, blossomed again
in the late '70s with such country hits as ``Middle-Age Crazy'' and
``I'm Gonna Find It Where I Can.'' He did well in the early `80s
with ``39 and Holding'' and ``Over the Rainbow,'' then took a break
from recording to concentrate on live shows.
   ``I just got so tired and bogged down with that country style,
slow-singing, beer-drinking type music. I just had to kind of get
out of it,'' he said. ``It's great music, don't get me wrong. But I
like to rock 'n' roll.''
   Lewis has made hundreds of thousands of dollars over his career,
but he likes his money in cash and has tastes that run to flashy
jewelry and fancy cars rather than ledger books. He filed for
bankruptcy last year and hasn't had a hit record in quite a while.
He told the bankruptcy court he will make about $200,000 from
``Great Balls of Fire.''
   Dogged by the Internal Revenue Service, he's had trouble getting
concert dates. The worst may be over, thanks to the movie and to
efforts begun in 1987 to clean up his image with promoters.
   Lewis recently completed a three-week stint in Las Vegas and
headlined two large concerts in California and Colorado. But those
jobs would have been closed to him two years ago.
   ``I tried to get him in Las Vegas for six months, and they
literally laughed at me,'' Schilling said. ``Evidently, there was
some bad past history with Jerry Lee in Vegas.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
