<FIRST>a i AM-Israel-ArabWorkers Adv04   06-27 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Arab Workers, Adv 04,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, July 4, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab Day Labor Is Controversial Issue in Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETAH TIKVA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to keep Palestinian day
laborers in a fenced-in compound while they wait to be hired in
Petah Tikva has fueled debate over the wisdom and morality of using
Arabs to work in Israel.
   Critics of restrictions on Arab laborers say the practice is
similar to what Nazis did to Jews in Germany, but proponents
maintain that after 18 months of a violent Palestinian uprising in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip, restrictions are necessary for safety
and security.
   Caught in the middle are the Arabs, who usually work as
construction laborers, street cleaners, garbage collectors and at
other menial jobs, and their employers, who pay them about half what
Israeli workers would have to be paid.
   In the West Bank settlement of Ariel, officials backed down from
a plan to make the Arabs wear tags labeling them ``alien workers''
after critics compared them to the yellow Stars of David that Jews
were forced to wear in Nazi Germany.
   When the town council in Petah Tikva, a city of 150,000 six miles
east of Tel Aviv, approved the holding area for Arab workers in May,
some Israeli newspapers said it amounted to a ``temporary prison.''
   The original plan called for a fenced-in holding pen where Arab
workers would be required to show their identity cards and wait to
be hired.
   But after the public outcry, the town decided to do away with
plans for the fence and a legal requirement that workers wait inside.
   Instead, a metal-frame shelter with a green plastic roof was
erected over three park benches; a portable toilet was put up
nearby. On one recent day, the shelter was empty and several Arab
workers waited at a corner about 100 yards away.
   ``People are afraid to go to the shelter,'' said one of the
workers, identifying himself as only as Faisal. ``They are afraid of
the police or of citizens here who might plant bombs or shoot guns
at us.''
   Avraham Oren, a Petah Tikva town council member who opposes the
shelter, said it would probably never be used because of the
controversy it has caused.
   ``This idea that it is possible to put people in pens is like
segregation of the races,'' he said.
   But council spokesman Shuki Yelin defended the shelter, saying it
was meant to ease fears by Jewish parents that their children might
be attacked by Arabs on the streets.
   ``We built it because ... many Jewish citizens protested and sent
petitions, saying they are suffering because of the presence of the
Arabs near their houses,'' Yelin said.
   ``It's not racist. We know we are criticized, but it's not a
jail. We don't force them to go. It's an open place.''
   Similarly expressed fears have been behind other moves to
restrict Arab workers.
   Mayor Zvi Zilker of the southern Israeli town of Ashdod
temporarily barred all Palestinian laborers recently after a soldier
was killed nearby and another disappeared and was believed
kidnapped. Police said they suspected Palestinians from the Gaza
Strip in both cases.
   After the attacks on soldiers, the Israeli government also began
requiring Gaza Arabs to obtain new work permits and restricting
those with records of crime or security offenses.
   But right-wing calls for barring all Arab workers from Israel
have brought an outcry from employers who depend on them.
   The issue has opened up a debate that touches not only Israel's
economy but also many Israelis' vision of their country as a bulwark
of Jewish morality that does not condone exploiting the Arabs.
   Professor Ehpraim Yuchtman-Yaar, a social psychologist at Tel
Aviv University, says Israelis are torn between dependence on Arab
workers and guilt over their treatment.
   ``People recognize the labor is vital for the Israeli economy,''
he said. ``They are doing low-status jobs that Israelis prefer not
to do. But morally, many Israelis feel the Arabs should be treated
equally to Jewish workers. ... Because they are not, it is
exploitation and should be denounced.''
   Moshe Semyonov, a Tel Aviv University sociologist, says the
segregation of Arabs is being fostered by a curious alliance between
right-wing Israelis and traditionalists who see the use of Arab
labor crushing their dream of an Israel built by Jews.
   ``People on both ends of the political spectrum are against
depending on Arabs _ one out of antagonism, the other for humanistic
or moral reasons,'' Semyonov said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues AMs, July 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
