<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Lewis Adv29-1stAdd   06-27 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Lewis, Adv 29 - 1st Add,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<TEXT>MEMPHIS: in Vegas.''    Bad history has always been with Lewis,
and he hasn't been bashful about letting people know that he acts how he
likes, when he likes.    ``Jerry Lee is a rebel. He's not some namby-pamby,''
said his sister, Linda Gail Stefanow. ``I think he's a lot more of a hero
than people realize. He wouldn't be Jerry Lee Lewis if he had lived his
life differently.''    Lewis, the first cousin and boyhood companion of
TV evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, quit school at 16 and briefly tried preaching
and selling sewing machines before focusing on rock 'n' roll.    He has
had six wives. His fourth wife, Jaren, drowned in a swimming pool in 1982
while suing for divorce; his fifth wife, Shawn, 23 years his junior, died
of an apparent drug overdose in 1983. Within a year, Lewis married his
sixth wife, Kerrie, 21, who filed for divorce in 1986, accusing him of
roughing her up and infidelity. Lewis countersued, but both petitions were
dropped. The Lewises live with their 2-year-old son, Jerry Lee III, near
Nesbit, Miss.    Lewis has bounced in and out of courtrooms throughout
his life, suing or being sued over busted concert dates, troubled romances
and other entanglements.    He also has a history of alcohol and drug
abuse, and in 1986, according to a former road manager, checked himself
out of a detox program because he didn't like making his own bed.    In
1976, Lewis was detained by police after ramming his Lincoln Continental
into the front gates of Presley's Memphis residence, Graceland, while armed
with a .38-caliber pistol. Admitting he had been drinking heavily, Lewis
told police he was called to Graceland because Presley was depressed and
wanted to talk.    Presley never commented publicly on the gate-ramming
escapade, but Shilling, who was a member of Presley's entourage for 11
years, said the two performers were never close friends.    ``You don't
call Jerry Lee if you're depressed,'' Schilling said.    The son of a
one-time bootlegger, Lewis was born in Ferriday, La., and taught himself
to play the piano as a child. His early plans were to become a piano-playing
preacher, and he gave a brief try at attending a fundamentalist bible college
in Texas following his first marriage, at age 16.    Lewis' third marriage,
to Myra, set off cries from parents across the country that it was irrefutable
evidence of the dangers of rock 'n' roll. But marrying young was nothing
new to Lewis' family. His sister Frankie Lee married at 12, and Gail, who
has been married seven times, first wed at 14.    ``I think we're oversexed,''
said Gail Stefanow, who toured as a backup singer with her brother for
15 years.    Lewis has been fighting the IRS for more than a decade. He
went to trial for tax evasion in 1984 and was acquitted, but the government
said he still owed more than $650,000.    In fighting the tax charges,
Lewis' lawyer presented his client as an uneducated country boy overwhelmed
by trying to keep up with the thousands of dollars he was making, much
of it paid in cash. The government said $31,000 was found stuffed in a
paper bag at the singer's Mississippi home, and a former girlfriend said
Lewis once gave her $80,000 in a shoe box to keep for him while he was
hospitalized.    Lewis nearly died from a ruptured stomach in 1981 and
has since had much of his stomach removed. He still gets out from time
to time for late-night drinks at his favorite bars, but is becoming more
of a homebody since the birth of his new son.    Lewis' first son, Jerry
Lee Jr., was killed in a traffic accident at age 19. Aother son, Steve
Allen, drowned in a swimming pool at age 3. He also has two daughters.
   Lewis acknowledged that many of the lumps and bumps in his life may
have been of his own doing, but he stopped short of offering any apology.
   ``I don't think I overshot my runway,'' he said. ``I'm still rockin',
brother ... and I did it my way.'' 
</TEXT>
