<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Yehoshua Adv07-09-1stLd-Writethru bcottonfuturesweretrading
06-27 1009</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Yehoshua, Adv 07-09 - 1st Ld-Writethru, b0822,1027</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 7-9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: The Importance of Myth for Israeli Writers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf to correct spelling of Israel.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early in 1988, a letter composed by four Israeli
writers appeared in The New York Times urging American Jews to speak
out against Israel's violent crackdown of Palestinian protesters in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   One of the writers was A.B. Yehoshua, whose novels include ``A
Late Divorce'' and the recently released ``Five Seasons''
(Doubleday, $19.95). Yehoshua, Amos Oz, Yehuda Amichai and other
Israeli writers uphold a tradition of active participation in their
country's politics. Zionism, or Jewish statehood, they note, was
created by a writer _ Theodor Herzl.
   ``The main figures of the first Zionist congress were writers,''
said Yehoshua, professor of literature at Haifa University. ``By
their imagination they understood what was going to happen to the
Jewish people.''
   Avraham Bulli Yehoshua was born in Jerusalem in 1936 at a time
when the city was part of British-controlled Palestine. When he was
12 years old, Israel was granted independence and won a fierce war
with Arabs for possession of the land.
   ``I remember always sitting under the shelters and being without
food. I remember the fighting, the shelling, the bullets. I was
worried about my father, who was working in the secret service,
listening to the Arabs' telephone calls,'' he said.
   He didn't originally want to be a writer, dreaming instead about
a legal career. But as a teen-ager, Yehoshua joined a youth group
and impressed his peers with humorous pieces about local events. He
continued to write while serving in the army.
   ``I was writing about things in the unit _ creating absurd
situations in a very fantastic kind of style, describing what was
inside the camp. This was the idea: absurd stories, fantastic
stories.''
   His first published work, a short story about a dying man, was
also an absurdist piece.
   ``He's still alive but the old woman decides to bury him alive,
to get rid of him,'' Yehoshua said about the work. ``The neighbors
are participating in this live burial, and I'm writing about how
this can be achieved.''
   Yehoshua soon became influenced by the works of William Faulkner,
admiring the great Southern writer's stream-of-consciousness prose
and blending of myth and reality.
   The use of myth is important for an Israeli writer. ``We don't
have a long history as an independent country so you have to relate
yourself to some myth,'' Yehoshua said. ``Israel has changed so
radically it's unbelieveable.''
   A self-described ``dove'' who favors talks between Israel and the
Palestine Liberation Organization and eventual Palestinian
self-determination, recalled a short story he had written in 1962:
   ``A student is sent to a forest because he didn't finish his
studies and his friends are advising him to finish his thesis. So
he's sent to a forest. There's an Arab in the distance planning to
set fire to the forest because it was built on his village. Finally,
the forest is set on fire.
   ``In 1962, it was an indication that the Palestinian problem was
being repressed. The Palestinian problem has been coming, expecially
in the last year. It's a sign that the Israelis have to realize the
limits of Zionism.''
   Politics are not mentioned directly in ``Five Seasons,'' which
chronicles the difficulties of a middle-aged government bureaucrat,
Molkho, in adjusting to the death of his wife, who succumbs to
cancer at the start of the novel.
   Molkho anxiously seeks companionship, flying to Berlin for a
weekend with the legal adviser from work, and spending time with the
wife of his old youth group counselor, who has encouraged the
meeting. But Molkho is unable to connect with either woman, as the
grief over his late wife makes him alternately abrupt and distant,
incapable of understanding their feelings.
   ``My point in this book is that this was the year Molkho thinks
he'll be free,'' Yehoshua said. ``Without believing in ghosts he
interiorizes his wife in such a way that she's still alive after her
death. And this is the way he has to struggle until then he's
liberated.''
   Where ``A Late Divorce'' showed Faulkner's unmistakable
influence, Yehoshua's writing in ``Five Seasons'' is in keeping with
his main character: restrained, introverted and obsessed with minor
details.
   ``It had to be much more subtle,'' the author said. ``When you
are writing stream-of-consciousness, everything has to get out. With
this, there's what you say and what you don't say. There's a gap
between the two. In a way, I was returning to the style of my short
stories.''
   In one passage, Yehoshua describes Molkho's thoughts while
attending a dinner party given by the legal adviser:
   ``The conversation rambled intimately. Though he had prepared a
few subjects to talk about, especially several of a legal nature, he
saw at once that he needn't make the effort, for everyone appeared
harmoniously acquainted and he, it seemed, was passed back and forth
among them in a discreet and unaffected fashion.
   ``Afraid of being suspected of some organic problem if he went to
the toilet too soon, he sat with his legs together to ease the
pressure on his bladder while one by one the men came up to him,
introducing themselves once again ...''
   Yehoshua is a strong critic of the diaspora, the dispersion of
Jews around the world, stating that the failure of Jewish people to
return to their homeland presents a greater threat than the Arabs to
Israel's national security. Yet in the final chapter of ``Five
Seasons,'' Molkho helps an unhappy Russian-born girl return to her
home country.
   ``It was a healthy thing for her to do,'' Yehoshua explained. ``I
don't tell you to stay. You have to feel natural. By understanding
the Russian's feelings, Molkho can better understand himself and
demonstrate his belonging to the country.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 7-9</NOTE>
</DOC>
