<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-27 0854</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0890</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. rejected a sweetened $12.2 billion
takeover offer offer from Paramount Communications Inc., calling the
$200-a-share bid inadequate and restating its intention to pursue
its own $14 billion offer for Warner Communications Inc.
   Time reiterated its objections to Paramount's earlier
$175-a-share, or $10.7 billion, bid, stating Monday that none of the
conditions in Paramount's offer had been met.
   The conditions include Paramount's obtaining of financing for the
deal and the rights to operate some 800 cable television systems
Time owns, as well as the termination of Time's merger agreement
with Warner.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that the federal
anti-racketeering law is not just aimed at mobsters, making it
easier to use the statute in lawsuits against businesses sued for
fraud.
   The court unanimously reinstated on Monday a lawsuit against
Northwestern Bell Telephone Co. by Minnesota consumers. The civil
suit accused the utility of violating the federal Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, or RICO.
   In another case, the high court agreed to set guidelines on when
employers may withdraw recognition of a labor union after hiring new
workers to break a strike.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angered by Britain's rejection of a single
European currency and central bank, France is threatening to renege
on an agreement that forms part of the drive for a united European
market by 1992.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher refused at the opening
session of a two-day summit Monday to embrace a plan for a tight
monetary union of the 12 nations of the European Economic Community.
   Her opposition prompted French President Francois Mitterrand to
threaten to renege on promises for more liberalized money markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declining interest rates that have pushed
conventional mortgage rates below single digits also have spurred
loan refinancings by many homeowners wanting to cut their house
payments and their ties to fickle adjustable rate mortgages.
   ``We're seeing a rash of these variable rate loans coming for
refinancing to a fixed rate, even some where their current (ARM)
rate is lower,'' Angelo Mozilo, president of Countrywide Funding
Corp. in Pasadena, Calif., said Monday. His company is of the
nation's largest mortgage lenders.
   In the past month, more and more lenders have dropped their
30-year conventional mortgage rates to below 10 percent for the
first time in about 16 months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospective homebuyers failed to take advantage
of falling mortgage rates in May when sales of existing homes fell
5.6 percent to their lowest level in 16 months, according to a real
estate trade group.
   The National Association of Realtors said Monday that sales of
single-family homes fell last month to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 3.21 million nits, down from 3.4 million units in both March
and April.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said fixed-rate mortgage
interest dropped from 10.97 percent the first week of May to 10.48
percent at the end of the month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. will move its 6,000-worker
merchandising group from downtown Chicago to suburban Hoffman
Estates, capping a bidding war between Illinois and the Sunbelt for
the division.
   Illinois won the contest Monday with the aid of a $61 million
package of incentives, which was backed by local tax incentives
reportedly totaling up to $178 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rash of oil spills in U.S. coastal waters is
fouling chances for major oil companies to escape congressional
drilling bans the industry says will make the nation more dependent
on foreign energy sources.
   At stake for the industry is a long-sought opportunity to hunt
for oil and natural gas in areas considered among the most promising
in the country: Alaska's Bristol Bay, and offshore Southern
California, southern Florida and New England.
   ``They'll stop Bristol Bay'' exploration, Dillard Spriggs,
president of the New York consulting company Petroleum Analysis
Ltd., said Monday. ``It's going to be hard to explore very much in
Alaska'' until the industry improves its public image.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Batman'' made more money in three days than
most movies generate in their lifetimes, with a $42.7 million
opening that broke a week-old record and drove the industry to a
record $90 million-plus weekend.
   Despite attracting less-than-overwhelming reviews, ``Batman,''
starring Michael Keaton in the title role and Jack Nicholson as the
Joker, set new marks for the best opening day with $15.3 million
Friday, according to figures released Monday. It also recorded the
biggest Saturday at $14.6 million and Sunday at $12.7 million in
movie history.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned downward Monday as traders cashed in gains
that carried the market to new post-crash highs last week. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials, up 49.70 points Friday, dropped
back 20.49 to 2,511.38.
   Bond prices climbed.
   The dollar ended higher against most major currencies following
last week's selloff.
   Gold prices declined. Coffee futures prices sagged to an 11-month
low, while orange juice futures soared; corn and soybean futures
dropped while wheat advanced; livestock and meat futures rallied;
oil futures rose; and precious metals slumped.
</TEXT>
