<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingSST Bjt   06-27 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing SST, Bjt,0846</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Boeing Exploring New SST, But Foresees Many Problems</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new generation of supersonic jetliners
might be built, but only if manufacturers can conquer the immense
environmental, technical and economic problems of a plane that would
fly at twice the speed of sound while costing twice as much as a
747, a Boeing Co. official says.
   ``This is Boeing dreaming,'' said Michael Henderson, manager of
High-Speed Commercial Transport studies for Boeing. ``But it's our
job in new airplane development to protect the future of the company.
   About 70 Boeing employees has been looking at whether a new
supersonic transport could be flying within the next 20 years. The
early outlook, Henderson said Monday, is that it could be done, but
not easily.
   Henderson said that McDonnell Douglas Corp. _ the only other U.S.
maker of commercial jets _ the Europeans and the Japanese also have
looked at new-generation SSTs, and appear to have reached similar
conclusions.
   ``We and Boeing have been working on parallel paths,'' said
McDonnell Douglas spokesman Keith Takahashi in Long Beach, Calif.
   Boeing and McDonnell Douglas each received $4.5 million from the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration for a two-year study
on the feasibility of a new SST. Both companies decided to continue
the research after the study ended last fall.
   Boeing declined to say how much it has spent so far.
   Boeing pinned a lot of hopes and a lot of money in the late 1960s
on building an SST. When the government cancelled the program over
environmental concerns, it contributed to the Boeing slump that
plunged Seattle, its headquarters city, into hard times in the early
1970s.
   Because of this, Boeing executives have said they are wary of
committing the hundreds of millions of dollars it would take to
build a new SST.
   Richard Albrecht, executive vice president of Boeing's Commercial
Airplanes division, has said that while the Concorde SST has been
successful as a premium trans-Atlantic service, he doubts anyone
would build _ nor would airlines buy _ a plane that must command a
much higher ticket price to serve a niche market.
   The Anglo-French Concorde began flying passengers in 1976. Only
about a dozen of the sleek jets now fly, operated by Air France and
British Airways, and are severely limited in routes because of noisy
engines and ear-rattling sonic boom resulting from it flying about
twice the speed of sound.
   Boeing is studying a plane capable of flying 1.8 to 2.5 times the
speed of sound, or roughly 1,330 to 1,850 mph. That would permit it
to fly from Los Angeles to Tokyo in 4 hours 20 minutes, compared
with the 10 hours, 20 minutes a non-stop subsonic flight takes today.
   Boeing doubts a faster plane would be practical, because it would
require new fuels such as liquid natural gas or liquid hydrogen, and
special airport facilities, Henderson said. Further, a plane that
could fly 2,500 mph or better would have scant time at cruising
speed on a 5,000-mile trans-Pacific flight.
   Boeing's four-engine HSCT, a long, languid curve in profile, is
envisioned to be about 293 feet long, 60 feet longer than a 747-400
jumbo jet, with a wingspan of just 142 feet, or 70 feet less than
the 747-400. It would haul 200 to 300 passengers about 5,000
nautical miles non-stop.
   The Concorde is about 204 feet long with an 84-foot wingspan and
carries 100 to 128 passengers 3,360 nautical miles non-stop.
   By using engine noise suppressors, Boeing planners think their
HSCT could meet the government's strict new standards for airport
noise. Sonic boom is another matter.
   ``We saw no way and still see no way we could reduce sonic boom
to acceptable levels over land,'' Henderson said.
   Another environmental worry is possible damage to the ozone
layer. By limiting the plane to under Mach 3, or three times the
speed of sound, it could still fly below the ozone layer, in the
troposphere, where engine emissions should be dispersed, Henderson
said.
   The HSCT would require some yet-to-be developed technology,
especially in lightweight composite materials. Just as critical is
making the plane economical to fly, he said.
   Boeing estimates air traffic in 2015 will be about 1.9 million
passenger miles per day, roughly twice what it is now. About a third
of all passengers would be on routes that could be served by an
HSCT, Henderson said.
   The problem, he said, is that to compete, an HSCT has to offer a
ticket price roughly the same as the newer and cheaper-to-operate
long-range widebody jets. That could be tough, he said, for a plane
that probably would cost twice as much as a 747-400, which sells for
about $125 million.
   In Boeing's market research, ``even an optimistic look says that
if you were to increase the ticket prices by as much as 20 percent,
we'd lose over half the market,'' he said.
</TEXT>
