<FIRST>r f PM-Time Bjt   06-27 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, Bjt,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Rejects Sweetened Paramount Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. has rejected Paramount Communications
Inc.'s $12.2 billion takeover bid, noting that the sweetened offer
is subject to the same unresolved conditions as Paramount's earlier
$10.7 billion proposal.
   Time's board, which turned down the revised $200-a-share bid
Monday, also called the offer financially inadequate, and the media
giant restated its intention to pursue a $14 billion tender offer of
its own for Warner Communications Inc.
   ``The Paramount offer remains as highly conditional and
conjectural as it was when Paramount started it nearly three weeks
ago,'' Time said in a statement Monday.
   Paramount has conditioned its buyout on being able to obtain
financing for the deal _ which it did not accomplish while its
earlier $175-a-share bid was on the table _ and on obtaining the
rights to operate about 800 cable television systems Time owns. The
bid is also contingent upon the termination of Time's merger
agreement with Warner.
   Time, which has focused on these conditions in its campaign
against Paramount, claims they will prevent the Paramount bid from
being completed and has urged its shareholders not to be tempted by
the size of the offer.
   ``It's not just the question of price,'' Time Vice Chairman Jerry
Levin said in a telephone interview Monday.
   Paramount was undaunted by the latest rejection. ``We will
continue to pursue our acquisition of Time in a calm, studied and
deliberate manner,'' it said in a statement.
   Time announced its rejection of the Paramount bid after the close
of trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Time stock seesawed in nervous trading as investors awaited the
board's response, rising as high as $172.25 a share before closing
at $164 a share, down $1.87{ from Friday's close.
   Securities analysts had expected Time to reject any sweetened bid.
   However, observers said they did not expect Paramount to raise
its offer again and Levin indicated the company expected the
takeover struggle to be resolved in Delaware Chancery Court, where
Paramount has sued to block Time's planned $70-a-share buyout of
Warner.
   A key issue before the court in Delaware _ where all three
companies are incorporated _ is whether Time put itself up for sale,
thereby opening itself up to the bid from Paramount, when it
announced its merger agreement with Warner in March.
   Time and Warner originally agreed to merge in a stock-for-stock
transaction but revised their merger agreement to provide for Time's
tender offer after Paramount announced its first bid on June 6.
   Paramount contends that Time's tender offer for Warner was begun
solely as a defense against the Paramount bid.
   ``I just believe that when the court looks at these issues, that
there's a fairly persuasive case that we have a transaction that has
not been done defensively...'' Levin said. ``It's something we've
studied for so long.''
   When they announced their plans to merge, Time and Warner said
they had been negotiating over two years.
   Time stated that its board based its unanimous rejection of the
Paramount bid partly on the opinions of its financial advisers,
Wasserstein, Perella &amp; Co. and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., that the
offer was inadequate.
   ``Paramount's original offer of $175 was absurdly low,'' Time
Chairman J. Richard Munro stated. ``Paramount's revised offer has
not changed the conclusion of our management and board that the
acquisition of Warner by Time is in the best interests of Time and
its stockholders.''
   Meanwhile, speculation continued on Wall Street that Paramount
itself might be the target of a hostile bid. Investors bid Paramount
stock up $2.37{ a share to $60.37{ Monday.
   Warner stock was up 25 cents a share to $58.87{.
   Also Monday, two large Time shareholders, Robert M. Bass Limited
Partners and a partnership of the Cablevision Systems Corp. and
Jerry Perenchio, filed suit in Delaware Chancery Court seeking to
block Time's annual meeting, scheduled for Friday.
   Bass and the Cablevision-Perenchio group have been mentioned as
possible bidders for some of Time's assets, The New York Times
reported in Tuesday's editions.
</TEXT>
