<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-27 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in quiet, early European
trading today, and foreign currency dealers said the market was
waiting for cues from economic news to be released this week.
   Gold prices fell.
   ``The dollar is completely flat today,'' said one trader in
Milan, Italy.
   He said investors were uncertain about where to go and were
waiting for Thursday's release of U.S. leading economic indicators
and for the outcome of the West German central bank's policy meeting
the same day.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.05 yen to a closing 141.23 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 141.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.9558 West German marks, up from 1.9552; 1.6840
Swiss francs, unchanged; 6.6343 French francs, down from 6.6380;
2.2045 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2003; 1,415.55 Italian lire, up
from 1,414.00; and 1.1943 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19405.
   The dollar fell slightly against the British pound in London. It
cost $1.5495 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5450 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $374.30 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $375.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $373.55.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $373.85, down from $374.25 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.15 to close at a bid of
$375.11.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.29 a troy ounce,
down from Monday's $5.33.
</TEXT>
