<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-27 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index plunged.
   The dollar closed at 141.23 yen, up 1.05 yen from Monday's close
of 140.18 yen. It opened at 141.15 yen and fluctuated between 140.90
yen and 141.30 yen.
   The dollar had fallen 4.77 yen in three trading days before
today's rebound.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a trader at Daiwa Bank, said the rebound
mainly reflected position adjustments.
   ``Nothing happened today,'' he added. ``There were no buying
incentives, there were no releases of major economic indicators this
week, there was no central bank intervention _ nothing.''
   Kinugasa said, ``The yen's sharp rebound last week has come to a
halt, and the majority of investors are now avoiding major moves
until they find a new trend in the market.''
   The dollar had risen to a nearly two-year high closing of 151.30
on June 15 before heading back down.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost
156.61 points, or 0.47 percent, closing at 33,469.21. The market's
main barometer had gained 95.11 points Monday.
   Masahiro Umemori, an analyst with Nomura Securities, said the
index fell mainly because of the yen's decline against the dollar
and the governing Liberal Democratic Party's loss in a parliamentary
by-election on Sunday.
   ``Japanese investors were reluctant to buy issues because of
uncertainties over the direction of the foreign exchange and
pessimism over performance in the upper house election,'' he said.
Elections for half the seats in the upper house are scheduled for
July 23.
   Other dealers said speculative investors sold spot issues for
arbitrage deals between the spot and the futures markets, prompting
the Nikkei's fall in the afternoon session.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 500
million shares, up from Monday's 430 million.
</TEXT>
