<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-27 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0313</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose in early trading today,
bouncing back from Monday's round of selling.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 12.71 to 2,524.09
in the first 30 minutes of trading.
   Gainers outnumbers losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 576 up, 343 down and
517 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.58 million shares at 10 a.m.
on Wall Street.
   The early gains indicated the impact of Monday's more than
20-point decline in the Dow industrials may have waned. But there
was little economic news or other factors that appeared to be
driving the market early today.
   The stock market advanced last week to new highs following the
1987 crash amid gathering signs of a slowing economy. The Dow Jones
industrials average gained 66 points on Thursday and Friday alone.
   A slowdown today also was attributed to waning support from
``window dressing'' by money managers at investing institutions, who
were readying their portfolios for midyear reports to clients.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
182.94, up 0.74 at 10 a.m.
   Among gainers, Eastman Kodak was up 1] to 49{, United Airlines
jumped 3 to 142\, British Telecommunications gained ~ to 42} and
Chevron was up | at 53{ in early trading.
   Time, which Monday rejected a $200-a-share buyout offer from
Paramount Communications, was up 1 at 164. Paramount was unchanged
at 60].
   On Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 20.49 to
2,511.38.
   Declining issues outpaced advances by nearly 4 to 3 on the NYSE,
with 629 up, 825 down and 494 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 143.60 million shares, against 198.72
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
