<FIRST>u f PM-EuropeanSummit 2ndLd-Writethru   06-27 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-European Summit, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Leaders Compromise on Plan to Unite Their Economies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Thatcher, Mitterrand, Kohl comments;
no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European Economic Community leaders today
agreed on a compromise plan for gradually unifying their economies
after Britain succeeded in blocking attempts to create a single
currency and a central bank.
   ``We have conceded nothing at all,'' British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher said at the end of a two-day summit.
   However, France and West Germany, which were aligned against
Britain in the dispute over broad plans to unify the economies, also
declared themselves pleased with the compromise pact.
   Closer monetary union is part of the EEC's drive toward December
1992, when the member nations will drop trade barriers to form a
single market.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said the agreement at the end
of a two-day EEC summit was a ``superb result.
   ``The foundation has been laid for a development that brings the
EEC further together and brings political union one step nearer,''
Kohl told reporters.
   The 12 EEC leaders have been divided over how far and how fast to
go toward closer economic and monetary union as part of the
establishment of a single Europe-wide market in 1992.
   In a final communique, the leaders endorsed only part of a
sweeping plan for monetary union drawn up by Jacques Delors, head of
the EEC's executive body, the European Commission.
   The communique avoided setting any deadline on the more
controversial aspects of the plan: creating a single currency and a
central bank. But it did provide for the calling of the
intergovernmental conference on those proposals, something Mrs.
Thatcher had sought to avoid.
   French President Francois Mitterrand said he would call an
intergovernmental conference after next year. The conference can be
called by a simple majority, but once there any member nation could
then veto the changes.
   Britain also agreed in principle to link the pound to the
exchange rate mechanism that aligns the value of the EEC's major
currencies.
   But Mrs. Thatcher hedged the move, which she has long resisted,
with strict conditions. These included that Britain's 8.3 percent
inflation must drop to near the 4.5 percent average in the EEC and
that arrangements for the single market must be complete.
   Besides Britain, some smaller EEC nations, including The
Netherlands, Luxembourg and Portugal, have also expressed
reservations about the Delors plan.
   Mitterrand and Mrs. Thatcher clashed repeatedly during the summit
behind closed doors, officials reported, and jibed publicly at each
other afterward.
   Each claimed that it was the other who was the other who had been
most isolated at the conference.
   ``It was not me who was isolated,'' said Mrs. Thatcher. ``It was
President Mitterrand.''
   Mitterrand agreed with a French radio interviewer that Mrs.
Thatcher was the ``brake'' on Europe.
   She retorted at a news conference, ``Its a bit rich, isn't it _
someone who has not got freedom of capital movement ... calling me a
brake on Europe. He has scarcely got into the car.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, adopting a more conciliatory manner than usual at
this summit, agreed Monday to support in principle the linking of
the British pound to a system that aligns the major EEC currencies.
   Mrs. Thatcher rejects full monetary integration as surrendering
to the EEC national policy-making powers on budgetary and other
financial matters.
   Mitterrand conference said he was ``very satisfied'' with the
summit.
   Asked if he was angry about Mrs. Thatcher's resistance to the
Delors plan, which he strongly favored, he said, ``One should not
confuse a certain firmness with anger.'' He added smiling, ``I am
used to her ... she's very nice.''
  
</TEXT>
