<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MayDivestiture     06-27 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-May Divestiture,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>May Department Stores Considers Sale of Discounters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. today said it is
exploring the possibility of selling its Caldor and Venture
subsidiaries, the company's discount segment.
   David C. Farrell, May chairman and chief executive officer, said
the company has asked the investment banking firm Morgan Stanley &amp;
Co. Inc. to look into the possible sales.
   ``The divestiture of Caldor and Venture will allow May to focus
on the operations and expansion of our higher-return and
faster-growing businesses, department stores and specialty shoe
stores,'' Farrell said.
   Farrell said that with the additions last year of Foley's and
Filene's, two department store chains, May's 14 department store
divisions produced sales of $7.5 billion and operating earnings of
$802 million. Volume Shoe's sales were $1.1 billion with operating
earnings of $138 million.
   Caldor's sales for 1988 came to $1.6 billion with earnings of $50
million and Venture's sales amounted to $1.3 billion with earnings
of $81 million.
   May said it anticipates using a significant portion of any
proceeds from the divestiture to buy back its stock, depending on
market conditions and other factors. The company said it would use
the balance of any proceeds for general corporate purposes,
including expansion of its department store and specialty shoe
businesses.
   May is one of the largest retailers in the United States. It
currently operates 283 department stores in 29 states and the
District of Columbia, 120 Caldor stores in eight states in the
Northeast, 73 Venture stores in the Midwest and 2,628 Volume Shoe
stores in 43 states and the District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
