<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Post Early Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade although
there was little fresh news of interest to the markets.
   The modest advance in corn and soybean prices suggested those
markets had already discounted the beneficial effects of overnight
rains in the Midwest and that some traders viewed Monday's steep
losses as excessive.
   Wheat prices continued a rally begun Monday on talk of a
significant Soviet purchase of U.S. wheat.
   The Agriculture Department issued its weekly crop update after
the close of trading Monday, rating the U.S. corn and soybean crops
in mostly fair to good condition as of Sunday.
   The USDA said most spring wheat was in good shape and winter
wheat harvesting was about 25 percent complete, compared to 49
percent on the same date last year.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 3} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.05{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 2 cents higher with July at $2.59 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
1{ cents higher with July at $1.49} a bushel; soybeans were
unchanged to 3 cents higher with July at $7.31 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were moderately lower and most pork futures were
down sharply in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .47 cent lower with August at 70.30
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower with
August at 81.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .23 cent to .77 cent
lower with July at 49.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1
cent lower to .60 cent higher with July at 34.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Monday.
</TEXT>
