<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-AsiaTrade     06-27 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Asia Trade,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Proposes Asian Trade Alliance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has
proposed establishing an Asian trade alliance involving the United
States and the emerging economic powers of the Pacific Rim.
   Although he didn't provide a detailed blueprint, Baker told a
black-tie dinner of the Asia Society, a non-profit group, late
Monday his plan would focus on coordinating the region's trade and
economic policies.
   He said the new alliance should also focus on other issues
ranging from cultural affairs to the environment.
   Baker said he plans to seek input on the plan during a trip to
Asia that starts July 3.
   Baker will stop in Tokyo to help plan multinational economic aid
for the Philippines. In Brunei, he will attend the annual meeting of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, an economic organization
of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and
Thailand.
   Intra-Asian trade last year totaled nearly $200 billion,
reflecting the rapid pace of Pacific Rim economic integration, Baker
said.
   ``Yet unlike Europe,'' he said, ``there are inadequate regional
mechanisms to deal with the effects of interdependence.''
   Japan's new foreign minister, Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, who met with
President Bush earlier Monday, spoke at the Asia Society dinner
before Baker. He stressed the need for America ``to maintain a
strong political, economic and military presence and commitment to
the region.''
   If a Pacific Rim group could be established it would ensure the
United States a stronger role in the region and provide a forum for
working out nagging trade problems.
   On China, Baker defended Bush's cautious response to the brutal
crackdown of pro-democracy demonstrators, saying it would be a
mistake to dismantle the relationship the United States built up
over two decades with the Communist government in Beijing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
