<HEAD>UAL Stock Soars On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s stock soared more than $7 a share this
morning on speculation that the parent of United Airlines may become
a takeover target.
   The buying surge apparently was prompted by a report in USA Today
that an investment group headed by Texas billionaire Robert Bass had
acquired 2.5 percent to 3 percent of UAL's stock.
   Susan Hawkins, a spokeswoman for Bass, declined comment on the
report. UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins said the company would not comment
on the stock activity.
   At noon EDT on the New York Stock Exchange, UAL's stock was
trading at $146.50 a share, up $7.25 from Monday's close. The jump
followed gains of $1.75 on Monday and $15.50 last week.
   Analysts said takeover specialists are eyeing airline companies
following an investor group's successful $3.6 billion bid last week
for NWA Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines.
