<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended sharply higher on the London
Stock Exchange Tuesday as recent fears of a rise in British interest
rates were soothed by a surprising narrowing of the British trade
deficit in May.
   Adding further momentum to the market's rise were strong gains in
early Wall Street trading.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 26.8
points, or 1.2 percent, higher at 2,206.4, just 1.1 points below its
peak. It was the first time the key index closed above 2,200 points
in more than five weeks.
   At its lowest, the index was down 5.8 points at late morning, as
players anxiously waited for the release of the May trade report.
   Volume accelerated to a moderate 498.2 million shares from 369.9
million shares on Monday.
   Share prices took their cue from the British pound, which rallied
on the strength of the trade report and on news that Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher had reached an agreement on plans for monetary
union with other European leaders meeting in Madrid, Spain.
   ``Anything at the moment that is good news for sterling is good
news for interest rates, which is good news for the (equity)
market,'' one dealer said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 20.4 points at 1,829.7.
The Financial Times 500-share index rose 11.27 points to 1,249.56.
</TEXT>
