<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CoalStrike 2ndLd-Writethru f0117 06-27 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0117,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Miners to End Wildcat Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES urgent series. CORRECTS Joel to Joe in 4th graf pvs
bg'ng, UMW national ...; minor editing throughout; No pickup; Also moved
on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN GILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ordered nearly
43,000 coal miners in nine states to end a wildcat strike and go
back to work.
   U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp issued the indefinite
restraining order against the United Mine Workers at the request of
the National Labor Relations Board.
   The nearly 43,000 miners walked out in support of 1,900 UMW
members who have been on strike against Pittston Coal Group since
April 5.
   UMW Vice President Joe Corcoran in Washington did not immediately
return a telephone call.
   Miners have ignored previous restraining orders and remained off
the job.
   Knapp said union officials must report to the NLRB within 10 days
on what steps they have taken to meet the court order.
   The judge could have restricted the back-to-work order to West
Virginia and parts of Virginia, Kentucky and Ohio, but instead made
it nationwide, ordering that it apply to all coal companies with
whom the UMW has contracts.
   About 1,600 UMW miners in Virginia and West Virginia went on
strike against Pittston on April 5 after working 14 months without a
contract. They were joined by 300 Pittston miners in Kentucky
earlier this month.
   That strike spurred wildcat sympathy walkouts beginning June 12
in Appalachia and the Midwest. At one point, 46,000 miners in
Missouri, West Virginia, Alabama, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Tennessee and Virginia were off the job. Missouri's
miners went back to work on Monday.
   Most of the nation's union miners began their two-week vacations
this week, and the coal fields have been relatively quiet since the
weekend.
   On Monday, a second attempt by Gov. Gaston Caperton to mediate in
the 11-week-old Pittston walkout fell short when Pittston Chairman
Paul Douglas declined to say whether he would meet with UMW
President Richard Trumka.
   Caperton had invited Douglas and Trumka last week to meet at the
governor's mansion.
   But Caperton attached several conditions unacceptable to Douglas,
including asking that Pittston not use other coal companies to fill
its orders and that other companies suspend any lawsuits against the
UMW over the strikes.
   The governor's latest offer contained no conditions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-ScamCapitals Adv02   06-27 1164</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scam Capitals, Adv 02,1196</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sun, Surf and Scams in Southern California and South Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are more than balmy breezes
blowing from the south.
   Hundreds of sweet-talking scam operators are working the
telephones to con victims out of a few hundred dollars or, in some
cases, their life savings.
   Investigators estimate 90 percent of all the major ``boiler
room'' telemarketing schemes in the nation are based in either South
Florida or Southern California, with affluent Orange County, Calif.,
dethroning Fort Lauderdale several years ago as the country's scam
capital.
   The pitches are limited only by the imagination _ from oil wells
to medical breakthroughs; worm ranches to low-cost precious metals _
and rope in nearly $1 billion annually, according to the Federal
Trade Commission.
   Officials say the best salesmen can mold a lump of truth into a
monument of credibility and disguise a sham as a once-in-a-lifetime
deal.
   ``These boiler room guys like life in the fast lane: the yachts,
the fancy cars, the sunshine,'' said Kent Neal, head of the Broward
County Economic Crime Unit based in Fort Lauderdale. ``South Florida
and Southern California offer the kind of lifestyle they want.''
   Scam artists also like southern climes for their transient
populations and ready pools of pitchmen.
   ``Some of the ads they run specifically target struggling actors
or musicians,'' said David Katz, coordinator of the Southern
California Fraud Task Force based in Los Angeles. ``In an way, it's
like an acting job. They try to give the pitch as sincerely and
convincingly as possible. Too many times it works.''
   Tougher state laws and more aggressive enforcement have driven
many boiler room operators from the Fort Lauderdale area, but Neal
estimates about 80 large telemarketing fraud operations still carry
on from Miami to Palm Beach. Katz said at least 150 boiler rooms
have staked out Southern California, with most centered around
Newport Beach.
   The boiler room's ability to survive is partially due to lack of
coordination betwen federal and state law enforcement agencies and
the con artists' nomadic instincts, say investigators.
   ``When the law gets too close, they pack up shop and begin
again,'' said Deputy State Attorney Albert Sheldon, a boiler room
specialist based in San Diego.
   The first telephone scams began in South Florida in the 1920s,
when salesmen would pitch mosquito-infested swampland as prime
property. The boiler rooms _ so called for their typically spartan
surroundings _ did not flourish again until the 1970s. This time,
sure-bet oil and gas fields and inexpensive gems and gold dominated
the pitches, said Neal.
   One of Neal's favorite souvenirs from the early '80s heyday of
South Florida boiler rooms is a piece of wood carved and painted to
resemble a gold bar. It was found with others in the vaults of
International Gold Bullion Exchange, one of the boldest and most
notorious fraud scams on record.
   From unusually swank offices in a Fort Lauderdale skyscraper
topped with the IGBE logo, principals William and James Alderdice
reportedly made $75 million on fraudulent sales of gold, silver and
platinum to 13,000 investors, many reassured by IGBE ads in the Wall
Street Journal. Some IGBE salesmen earned $8,000 a week and the
Alderdices were known to toss $100 bills from their stretch
limousine and watch folks scramble for the cash.
   Neal's successful prosecution of IGBE in 1985 was the first major
boiler room case in South Florida and is credited with beginning the
crackdown that drove many to California. William Alderdice was
hacked to death by his chauffeur before the trial began and his
brother received a 10-year federal and a six-year state sentence.
   ``We are an equal opportunity agency. We prosecute anyone. We
have doctors, lawyers and Indian chiefs,'' Neal said, pointing to a
photo of Bernard Kabrahrah, a former Comanche tribal leader who
became involved in a $40 million scam to sell rights to
non-producing natural gas wells in Oklahoma.
   And the victims _ known as mooches or mullets in boiler-room
parlance _ are just as varied.
   ``It's no longer just the retirees getting burned. Yuppies with
money to spend are becoming the new targets,'' said Neal.
   Some emerging scams include bogus job search agencies, travel
club rip-offs and touting low-priced ``penny'' stocks, according to
the Alliance Against Fraud in Telemarketing, a watchdog group. Neal
has also noticed organized crime taking an interest in boiler rooms.
   In April, the Securities and Exchange Commission charged the
nation's largest penny stock dealer, Stuart-James Co. Inc. of
Denver, with defrauding clients at its Boca Raton office by making
exaggerated claims about companies. ``A good boiler room salesman is
like a chameleon,'' said Neal. ``If you are religious, suddenly they
are born-again. If you have kids, they are suddenly the concerned
parent. They tell you what you want to hear.''
   In Southern California, scams involving vitamins and prize
contests are hot, say investigators.
   The boiler rooms hook customers with a postcard saying they have
won a valuable prize _ sometimes cash, a car or jewelry. The catch
is that the customers must also purchase a supply of vitamins or
some other item. Often the vitamins or prize are never delivered or
they are grossly inferior to the product described by the ``yaks,''
or boiler room salesmen.
   Yet local agencies are often slow to crack down, said Katz.
   ``The cops here are dealing with drug traffic, gang violence and
all sorts of other things,'' said Katz, whose office has prosecuted
300 people since 1986.
   Some areas, such as Clark County, Nev., have discouraged boiler
rooms by requiring costly bonds for each company and every employee
of a telemarking firm.
   California began registration of telemarketing firms in January
1987, and operators face a maximum penalty of one year in prison and
a $10,000 fine for failing to comply.
   Florida adopted tough boiler-room laws in October 1986, including
making schemes involving more than $50,000 in losses a first-degree
felony punishable by up to 30 years in prison. In 1987, Gary Fox was
convicted of swindling $11 million from 4,000 investors in his
United Precious Metals firm and was sentenced to 585 years in
prison, believed to be the longest white-collar crime sentence.
   Neal has one letter he can't forget. It came in early 1987 from
Samuel Kaminsky of Hazleton, Pa., who lost $70,000 in mostly
borrowed money in the United Precious Metals scam.
   ``I feel foolish and unable to make decisions. I always feel as
though I will make another devastating mistake,'' wrote Kaminsky.
   ``These letters tear me up,'' said Neal. ``When a guy robs you on
the street at least he is up front and only takes what is in your
pocket. With telemarketing scams, they don't just take what's in
your pocket, but everything else you own. You can make more money,
but it's the emotional impact you may never recover from.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday July 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
