<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0440</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher today, rebounding from
a round of selling Monday as interest rates declined in the bond
market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 21.62 to 2,533.00
at 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by almost 2 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 934 up, 506 down and
516 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 143.09 million shares with one
hour to go.
   Traders said the gains indicated the impact of Monday's more than
20-point decline in the Dow industrials had waned. Many traders
cashed in profits Monday after the market rallied last week, pushing
the Dow industrials up more than 45 points.
   Declining interest rates in the bond market helped propel stocks
higher, analysts said.
   Today's gains also were attributed to institutions attempting to
complete their second-quarter trading ahead of the July 4 weekend to
prepare midyear portfolio reports for clients.
   ``I think the market is finding a trading range here,'' said
Eugene Peroni, director of technical research for Janney Montgomery
Scott Inc. ``There seems to be good buying interest today.''
   The stock market advanced last week to new post-crash highs amid
gathering signs of a slowing economy, which were seen as indicators
that inflation would not accelerate. That would be positive news for
corporate earnings.
   UAL was up 7~ to 147[ on unconfirmed reports that Texas investor
Robert Bass was part of a group that had acquired a stake in the
company, parent of United Airlines. AMR, parent of American
Airlines, was up 1{ to 66\ and Delta Air Lines was up { to 72\.
   Time was unchaged at 164. The media giant rejected a $200 a share
takeover bid from Paramount Communications Inc. after the market
closed Monday. Paramount was down \ at 60[, while Warner
Communications, which Time is offering to buy for $70 a share, was
up ] at 59\.
   Oil stocks showed strength. Chevron gained 2] to 55\, Atlantic
Richfield rose 1} to 95[, Amoco was up 1{ to 46\ and Mobil gained 1~
to 51].
   IBM was the most actively traded NYSE stock, up 2{ to 114{, and
Digital Equipment was up 3{ to 95[.
   Among decliners, Teledyne fell 2} to 372} and Sears &amp; Roebuck
lost | to 43| in active trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
1.28 to 183.48. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 2.20 at 366.21.
