<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-27 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Leads Rise In Crop Futures, Soviet Buying Cited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wheat market led grain and soybean futures
prices to a sharply higher close Tuesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade, reflecting ideas that the Soviet Union is seeking to buy more
U.S. wheat.
   The rally drove wheat futures to their highest level since
mid-May and erased most of Monday's steep losses in the corn,
soybean and oat markets.
   Unlike the other grains, wheat futures had risen Monday on signs
that the Soviets had bought up to 500,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat
at market prices, an indication that they had an immediate need for
the grain.
   Tuesday's rally was fueled by speculation that the Soviets would
be back for more wheat and by reports of rain-induced harvest delays
in the central and southern states where soft red winter wheat _ the
variety reportedly sought by the Soviets _ is grown.
   ``There are also a lot of quality concerns in the soft red wheat,
which makes large-scale buying particularly bullish,'' said
Katharina Zimmer, a grain-market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York.
   At the close of trading, wheat was { cent to 10\ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in July at $4.12 a bushel; corn was
3{ cents to 4} cents higher with July at $2.62{ a bushel; oats were
4} cents to 5{ cents higher with July at $1.53{ a bushel; soybeans
were 4 cents to 13{ cents higher with July at $7.40 a bushel.
</TEXT>
