<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Beauvais Adv02   06-27 0916</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Beauvais, Adv 02,0947</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Six-Year-Old Airline Typifies Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGER SANDAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty years ago, Ed Beauvais left an
accounting job at a steel company for one in the airline industry
that offered $15 more a month. Today, he operates the nation's
10th-largest airline.
   America West is a prototype of successful companies in the 1980s
_ slick, opportunistic, oriented to employees' needs. A child of
deregulation, the 6-year-old airline made $10 million last quarter
while some other carriers waded in red ink. It projects a $30
million profit this year.
   While metal fatigue made headlines last year in the wake of fatal
accidents, America West fielded a fleet of 74 aircraft, mostly
Boeing 737s and 757s, averaging only 5.6 years old.
   ``We have a very good market niche ... and we've always been
adequately financed and our people are extremely productive,''
Beauvais says. ``You have to have all these elements in place or you
cannot deal with the significantly competitive atmosphere that we
have.''
   America West recently failed in its most ambitious undertaking _
an attempt to buy Eastern Airlines' Northeast shuttle out from under
developer Donald Trump _ despite offering $50 million more than
Trump.
   But Beauvais, the 52-year-old chairman and chief executive whose
swashbuckling image is stamped on his airline, didn't get where he
is by putting his eggs in one basket.
   America West has applied for federal approval to start flights to
Sydney, Australia, and Tokyo and is constantly on the lookout for
opportunities to expand into other markets.
   America West succeeds primarily because of strong leadership,
said James Carey, a senior vice president with Airline Economics
Inc., which publishes Airline Quarterly in Washington.
   ``They have proven to be able to make adjustments to their
operating strategies as the marketplace requires,'' Carey said.
   ``I do like the fundamentals of the company,'' said Paul Karos, a
financial airline analyst for First Boston Corp. in New York. ``They
clearly are well into a turnaround.''
   For its first five years, America West averaged about 65 percent
annual growth in carrying capacity but lost money in all but one
year, Karos said. In 1988, he said, the company began to slow its
growth in seat-miles to focus on profitability.
   It posted a profit in the second quarter of 1988 and has been
profitable each quarter since then.
   ``They changed their operating strategy,'' Carey said. ``They
actually changed from their emphasis on long-haul operations and
re-emphasized the feeder services through Phoenix and have improved
their profitability because of that revenue growth.''
   Carey said trans-Pacific air service is growing at a higher rate
than travel to Europe and is almost triple domestic growth.
   Beauvais said America West was serious about buying the shuttle
but ran out of time to come up with the financing. The airline is
going ahead with expansion of service to the East Coast through
Washington's National Airport and New York's LaGuardia via landing
slots acquired in May.
   America West needs approval from the U.S. Department of
Transportation and the Japanese government before it can start
service to Japan and Australia.
   Deregulation provided opportunity but also unprecedented
competition, and most of the new entrants failed.
   ``There's not many survivors,'' Beauvais said. He is one of them.
The Colorado native entered the industry in 1960 as an accountant
for Frontier Airlines and moved through jobs in Las Vegas, Phoenix,
San Francisco and Washington.
   In 1981, while in Phoenix for a second time, he linked up with
current company president Mike Conway, who had quit as a vice
president of Continental Airlines.
   By 1983, Beauvais, Conway and five others had raised $20 million
through public stock offerings and bank financing and were ready to
fly.
   The company started service Aug. 1 of that year with 280
employees and three Boeing 737s, serving four points between Los
Angeles and Kansas City, Mo.; today, America West has 8,800
employees and serves 47 cities.
   Beauvais said he chose the Phoenix area because no carrier
dominated the region.
   ``Other airlines failed to see the opportunity,'' he said. ``The
timing was right to build a hub-and-spoke system.''
   Two constants of the airline's history have been its original
marketing slogan _ ``Less Fare, More Care'' _ and management's
willingness to bend over backward to keep its employees from union
afflilation.
   America West offered ``more care'' through assigned seating,
complimentary beverages and free copies of the Wall Street Journal
and USA Today. After some complaints about late flights, the carrier
recovered and ranks first in on-time operations for the period since
the Department of Transportation began keeping figures in 1987.
   America West employees are stockholders who participate in a
profit-sharing program. Employees move around, working as a flight
attendant one day and taking reservations or doing ramp duties the
next.
   ``It's helped America West be extremely productive and given
individuals very good professional atmosphere,'' Beauvais said.
   The practices apparently convinced employees to reject two unions
in elections this year and keep their airline the nation's largest
without any unionized employees. Continental Airlines is largely
non-unionized but has a weak flight attendants' union.
   Beauvais' second-floor office is directly beneath the flight
paths into and out of Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport,
allowing the chief executive officer the opportunity to watch his
planes land and take off.
   ``I don't regret a moment of it,'' he said. ``I'd never work in
any other industry.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, July 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
