<DOCNO> AP890627-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1556EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MayDivestiture     06-27 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-May Divestiture,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>May Department Stores Considers Sale of Discounters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. Tuesday said it is
exploring the possibility of selling its Caldor and Venture discount
chains.
   Divesting the two general merchandise discounters would enable
the retailer to more easily pursue its intention to concentrate on
its department store and shoe businesses.
   ``The divestiture of Caldor and Venture will allow May to focus
on the operations and expansion of our higher-return and
faster-growing businesses ...'' said David C. Farrell, May chairman
and chief executive officer.
   May, one of the largest retailers in the country and owner of
Lord &amp; Taylor, Hecht's, Sibley's, plus other department stores and
specialty shoe chains, said it anticipates using a significant
portion of the proceeds from a possible sale to buy back its stock.
   The remainder of any proceeds would be spent on general corporate
purposes, including investment in the department store operations
and shoe businesses, the company said in a news release.
   May management have been working to restore Caldor to higher
levels of profitability and recently have expressed optimism about
Caldor's prospects.
   Caldor, which operates in the Northeast, was taken over by May in
1986 as part of the acquisition of Associated Dry Goods. Caldor's
operating earnings came to $50 million in 1988 on sales of $1.6
billion.
   May launched Venture in 1970. It operates in the Midwest and last
year had operating income of $81 million on sales of $1.3 billion.
   Both Venture and May sell a range of items including hard line
goods, such as appliances, and soft line goods, such as clothing.
   Thomas A. Hays, May's president, described Caldor and Venture as
two ``well-positioned businesses with excellent management and
committed associates.''
   As a condition of any sale, May will insist on provisions
regarding jobs, compensation and benefits for Caldor's and Venture's
employees.
   Retail industry analysts had been expecting that May eventually
would shed Caldor and Venture.
   ``I think it was something we were all expecting them to do,''
said Jeffrey Edelman, of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``But it is a
little earlier than expected.''
   Edelman said he thought May would have waited to look for buyers
until Caldor and Venture had shown steady financial progress over a
longer period of time.
   Given May's plan to use much of the money it would get from
selling the two units to buy its shares, the move seems aimed
chiefly at enhancing the value of the retailer's stock.
   Some shareholders had become disgruntled when May diluted its
earnings through the acquisitions of the Associated Dry Goods
properties in 1986 and then the Foley's and Filene's department
store chains in 1988.
   ``I think it's an attractive move for them to make as far as
shareholders are concerned,'' said Edelman.
   Farrell said May has asked the investment banking firm Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. Inc. to look into the move.
   With the addition of Foley's and Filene's last year, May's 14
department store divisions produced sales of $7.5 billion and
operating earnings of $802 million. Volume Shoe's sales were $1.1
billion with operating earnings of $138 million.
   May, which is based in St. Louis, currently operates 283
department stores in 29 states and the District of Columbia, 120
Caldor stores in eight states in the Northeast, 73 Venture stores in
the Midwest and 2,628 Volume Shoe stores in 43 states and the
District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-KodakWorries Adv02   06-27 1004</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kodak Worries, Adv 02,1039</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kodak Can't Find Formula For Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sustaining success has been difficult for
Eastman Kodak Co. this decade and that's one reason the company's
name keeps coming up on Wall Street as a possible takeover target.
   The company has managed to turn around a sagging bottom line
twice since 1980, only to see the same problems _ increased
competition, a rising U.S. dollar and higher costs _ return to chew
up profits.
   ``It seems like they wipe their brow and say, `Whew, we're glad
that's over,' and they turn around and have to do it all over
again,'' said Mark Obenzinger, a stock analyst for Wood, Gundy &amp; Co.
in New York.
   Call it the three-year twitch.
   Kodak laid off thousands of workers in 1983 saying unfavorable
exchange rates and soft markets overseas had hurt its business. The
company's profits went up 63 percent the next year.
   In 1986, the company had to lay off more than 10,000 workers,
radically restructure the company and start a cost-cutting program
in an effort to remain competitive.
   Profits more than tripled the next year and set a record in 1988.
   Now in 1989, after profits declined 23 percent in the first
quarter of the year, the company has announced plans to cut costs by
consolidating its photofinishing and consumer photography units,
which could mean hundreds of layoffs.
   ``It does seem to go in cycles and we're at the point where the
company is under pressure again,'' said Eugene Glazer, a stock
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Meanwhile, Kodak is having trouble controlling expenses at
Sterling Drug Co., which it bought for $5.1 billion last year. And
the company is battling in court to prevent a large damage award to
Polaroid Corp. in the two companies' patent infringement lawsuit
over instant photography.
   As if all these problems-that-won't-go-away aren't enough, Kodak
was named last month as the No. 1 emitter of the industrial
pollutant methylene chloride by a Washington-based environmental
group.
   Analysts point to several reasons for Kodak's roller-coaster ride
through the '80s.
   First and foremost is the value of the U.S. dollar.
   When the dollar is strong compared to other countries'
currencies, Kodak gets hurt in two ways: its profits overseas are
smaller when translated back into dollars, and foreign rivals gain a
price advantage in sales to the U.S. market.
   This double whammy hurt Kodak throughout the first half of the
decade and helped competitors like Fuji Photo Film Co. and
Agfa-Gevaert Inc. loosen Kodak's strangle hold on photographic film
sales around the world.
   In the 1970s, Kodak sold between 90 and 95 percent of all
photographic film in the world. Today, that has fallen to between 80
and 85 percent, according to industry estimates.
   The dollar has been gaining strength for the past year and,
unless it weakens soon, Kodak is going to have to continue cutting
costs to offset the losses it will bring.
   ``I'm not sounding alarm right now on the dollar, but I'm getting
ready to,'' Kodak's Chairman Colby Chandler said. ``If it hasn't
started down by year-end, I'm going to be concerned.''
   Chandler said it's difficult to determine how much of Kodak's
woes can be traced to outside factors like the dollar or to
management decisions made by Kodak executives.
   ``America basically has sort of a chip on its shoulder these
days. We're always trying to find who's to blame for something,''
Chandler said. ``Instead of taking responsibility, we have learned
to blame everyone else but ourselves for what goes wrong.''
   He said he doesn't want Kodak to join that chorus.
   In an effort to become more in control, Chandler said the company
is planning to sell a number of its businesses that have either been
developed within the company or been acquired.
   ``Each one will not make a significant impact on the company or
the public eye, they're not that big. But the idea is very powerful
inside the company,'' Chandler said.
   Kodak remains a benevolent corporate father figure to the
Rochester area, where it remains the largest employer, said Peter
Enderlin, an analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   ``Their idea of dramatic cost-cutting and dramatic restructuring
really isn't that dramatic,'' Enderlin said. ``They still have a
mentality that is somewhat paternalistic.''
   Questions about Kodak being too nice only pump up the takeover
talk on Wall Street.
   Rumors have swirled in the past few weeks speculating that
corporate raider Carl Icahn has begun looking at the company and
that Kodak might be considering a merger with General Electric Co.
   With takeovers sweeping corporate America, stock analysts aren't
surprised that Kodak's name has popped up on the merger and
acquisitions menu, but most agree a takeover of the company is
unlikely.
   ``These rumors get started because the company has
characteristics that attract corporate raiders, but the odds are
against a takeover attempt,'' said Glazer.
   Kodak is a well-known name, it's in a good industry and it's
being managed for long-term growth, three things that appeal to
corporate raiders who want companies that can be changed around to
yield more money right away.
   ``I guess there are some people who believe that some outside
group can wave a magic wand and change Kodak from an ugly duckling
into a beautiful swan,'' said Enderlin of Smith Barney. ``It's not
that easy.''
   Kodak's businesses are complex. The company also has a number of
hurdles that give it some protection from potential hostile
takeovers.
   The company is incorporated in New Jersey, which has tough
anti-takeover laws. If a raider acquired a majority of Kodak stock,
management could issue enough new stock to friendly buyers to
outvote the raider.
   The company also has about $13 billion in long- and short-term
debt, which would increase the cost of a leveraged buyout.
``Nothing's impossible, but a takeover attempt would be hard to
believe,'' said Obenzinger.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
