<FIRST>r f AM-InvestorFined     06-27 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Investor Fined,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investor Fined For Penny Stock Filing With SEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of the British unit of Japan's
Nissan Motor Co. was fined $10,000 Tuesday for filing a false
statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission about his
ownership of penny stock.
   The defendant, Frank Shannon, 56, of Hove, England, pleaded
guilty April 18 to a criminal information before U.S. District Judge
Kevin Duffy of Manhattan. Duffy could have sentenced Shannon to five
years in prison and fined him $250,000.
   Prosecutors said Shannon had understated his ownership of stock
in T.S. Industries Inc. According to court papers, Shannon filed a
statement with the SEC on May 16, 1988, that said he had control
over more than 1.5 million T.S. shares. Shannon was charged with not
reporting nearly 1 million additional shares of T.S. stock that he
controlled.
   According to prosecutors, Shannon was an investor in T.S. stock
through Haas Securities Corp., a brokerage house that collapsed nine
days after the Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash.
   Prosecutors maintain that Haas' alleged scheme to artifically
raise the prices of penny stocks _ inexpensive securities traded
over the counter _ could not be maintained after the market dropped
and share prices tumbled.
   Eugene Laff, former Haas chairman, was charged in March with 15
counts of conspiring to manipulate the prices of stocks to increase
their value.
</TEXT>
