<FIRST>u f AM-UAL     06-27 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Stock Soars On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s stock jumped higher Tuesday, fueled by
a report that a group led by Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass had
acquired up to 3 percent of the company, which owns United Airlines.
   Bass spokeswoman Susan Hawkins declined comment on the report in
USA Today, and UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins said the company would not
comment on the stock activity.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, UAL rose $6.75 to $146 a
share. The jump followed gains of $1.75 on Monday and $15.50 for all
of last week.
   Analysts said speculators have taken an intense interest in
airline companies following an international investor group's deal
last week to buy NWA Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines, in a
deal valued at $3.64 billion.
   The airline industry's strongest performers _ including American,
Delta, United and USAir _ may have much higher value than their
stock prices indicate, said analyst Louis Marckesano of Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   ``I think the Northwest bidding and the subsequent publicity has
kind of highlighted the potential value of the four or five strong
majors, the ones who are strong and prosperous and have been that
way for years,'' Marckesano said.
   ``The mentality seems to be that if NWA can be taken over, why
can't anybody else?'' said Robert Decker, an analyst with Duff &amp;
Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
   United is the nation's second-largest airline after American in
terms of paid passenger miles.
   United owns 80 percent of its 408-jet fleet, the highest
percentage among the major carriers and one of the factors that
could enhance its appeal to suitors, analysts said.
   A buyer could conceivably sell the owned aircraft and use the
money to pay off debt from the acquisition and lease other aircraft.
   United also has a large route network in the Pacific, the world's
fastest-growing air-travel region.
   UAL is the successor to Allegis Corp., which formerly owned the
airline, the Hertz car rental company and the Westin International
and Hilton International hotel chains.
   Allegis embarked on a major restructuring in 1987, after the
investor group Coniston Partners acquired a 13 percent stake and
threatened to mount a takeover of the board of directors to force a
breakup of the company.
   Coniston contended that the stock market would value Allegis more
highly if it dumped its non-airline businesses.
   Allegis sold its non-airline companies and renamed itself UAL,
which was its title before it acquired those businesses and renamed
itself Allegis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
