<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-27 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Tuesday against all
major currencies except the Japanese yen in thin, choppy trading.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
troy ounce of gold at $375.25 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up $1.25 from late
Monday.
   Currency dealers said sentiment toward the dollar remains bullish
but that many traders were reluctant to buy the currency prior to
the Independence Day holiday and in the absence of any market-moving
news.
   ``There's a real sense in the market that this lull is a welcome
respite after what we've experienced in the last couple of weeks,''
said J. Thomas Stanley, a vice president at Chemical New York
Capital Markets Group.
   The dollar has risen sharply in recent weeks, then fell back last
week amid concern that central banks will intervene to thwart its
rise and over worries of higher interest rates overseas.
   The dollar came under pressure abroad Tuesday on a report that
the West German Bundesbank might consider an interest-rate hike at a
meeting Thursday of its central-bank council.
   The battered British pound, meanwhile, gained ground against the
dollar, helped by a surprising narrowing in the British trade
deficit in May and news that Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher agreed
with other European leaders on plans toward monetary union.
   At least two rounds of intervention by the Bank of England also
encouraged the pound's recovery.
   In London, the pound cost $1.5640, more expensive than $1.5450
late Monday. Sterling bought $1.5660 later in New York, up from
$1.5450.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.05 yen to a closing 141.23 yen. It was quoted
lower at 141.07 yen in London, and at 141.75 yen in New York, up
from 141.10 yen late Monday.
   Traders said the yen was hurt by reports in Tokyo that Japanese
Prime Minister Sousuke Uno was prepared to resign due to allegations
that he hired a geisha as a mistress.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.9560 West German marks, down from 1.9590; 1.6850 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6882; 1.1937 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1940;
6.6395 French francs, down from 6.6480; and 1,414.87 Italian lire,
down from 1,416.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday, included:
1.9550 West German marks, down from 1.9552; 1.6845 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6840; 6.6335 French francs, down from 6.6380; 2.2010 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.2003; 1,408.50 Italian lire, down from 1,414.00;
and 1.1939 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1940.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $376.60 a troy ounce, up $1.50 from Monday's late
bid.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $376.75 a troy ounce,
up from late Monday's $375.25. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold rose to
$375.75 an ounce from $374.25 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.15 to close at $375.11 an
ounce.
   Silver prices were unchanged. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.306 a troy ounce, the same as
late Monday. Silver closed in London at $5.33 an ounce, also
unchanged from Monday.
</TEXT>
