<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-27 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Surge With Hopes For Soviet Buying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices bounded to a six-week high Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade in anticipation of further buying of U.S.
wheat by the Soviet Union, which apparently is strapped for supplies.
   On other markets, livestock and meat futures were mostly lower
while oil and precious-metals futures were mixed.
   Wheat settled { cent to 10} cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $4.12{ a bushel; corn was 3} cents to 5 cents
higher with July at $2.62} a bushel; oats were 4} cents to 5{ cents
higher with July at $1.53{ a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 13
cents higher with July at $7.38{ a bushel.
   The rally pushed wheat futures to their highest level since May
15 and erased most of Monday's steep losses in the corn, soybean and
oat markets.
   Unlike the other grain markets, wheat futures had risen Monday on
rumors the Soviets had bought up to 500,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat at market prices, an indication they had an immediate need for
the grain.
   Most of the Soviet Union's recent purchases of U.S. grain have
been through the Agriculture Department's Export Enhancement
Program, which effectively subsidizes grain sales and requires
buyers to submit bids in a process that is not always speedy.
   After the close of trading Tuesday, the USDA said private
exporters had reported sales of 400,000 metric tons of soft red
winter wheat to the Soviet Union for delivery during the current
marketing year, which began Oct. 1.
   Tuesday's rally was fueled by speculation that the Soviets would
be back for more wheat and by reports of rain-induced harvest delays
in the central and southern states where soft red winter wheat is
grown.
   ``There are also a lot of quality concerns about the soft red
wheat, which makes large-scale buying particularly bullish,'' said
Katharina Zimmer, a grain-market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, reversing Monday's trend.
   The hog market led the way down, reflecting lower spot hog prices
and perceptions that the market was nearing a top.
   Cattle futures were pressured by slack demand and ample supplies.
   Live cattle settled .35 cent lower to .07 cent higher with August
at 70.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .27 cent
lower with August at 81.25 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to .87
cent lower with July at 49.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .80 cent lower to .50 cent higher with July at 34.75 cents a
pound.
   Heating-oil and crude-oil futures rose for the fifth straight day
on the New York Mercantile Exchange but the gasoline market's rally
ended with a modest decline.
   Analysts said the market's uncertain performance indicated that a
downturn _ a so-called technical correction _ was likely.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 6 cents to 23 cents higher
with August at $20.48 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .88 cent
higher with July at 50.53 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .01
cent to .25 cent lower with July at 63.68 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures rose slightly while silver futures were nearly
unchanged on New York's Commodity Exchange, in quiet trading that
reflected the dollar's mixed performance against other major
currencies.
   Gold settled $1.50 higher across the board with August at $379.80
a troy ounce; silver was unchanged to 1 cent lower with July at
$5.31 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
