<FIRST>r f AM-Greenspan     06-27 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenspan,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Back on the Job After Suffering Heat Exhaustion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
returned to his office Tuesday after spending the night at a
hospital for treatment of heat exhaustion, a spokesman said.
   Greenspan, 63, was rushed to George Washington University
Hospital Monday night after becoming ill at a dinner at the home of
Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, spokesman Joseph R. Coyne said.
Greenspan had played tennis earlier in the day when temperatures
were in the 90s.
   Coyne denied what he said were market rumors that Greenspan had
suffered a heart problem.
   The Fed chairman was released from the hospital shortly before 10
a.m. EDT and returned to work in the afternoon.
   Greenspan began a four-year term as Fed chairman in August 1987
and has led the central bank's campaign against inflation by
tightening credit and boosting interest rates. The Fed recently
began to ease its grip on credit amid signs that economic growth was
slowing.
   Greenspan served as chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers
under President Ford from 1974 to 1977 and was chairman of the
National Commission on Social Security Reform from 1981 to 1983.
   He also served as a member of President Reagan's Economic Policy
Advisory Board.
   Greenspan was born March 6, 1926, in New York City and received a
B.S. degree in economics, an M.A. degree in economics and a doctor's
degree in economics, all from New York University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
