<DOCNO> AP890627-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Drexel-NYSE     06-27 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-NYSE,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Says Drexel Sanctions Decision Will Come After Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the New York Stock Exchange is
indicating the Big Board will take disciplinary measures against
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. for the firm's involvement in Wall
Street corruption.
   However, an NYSE spokesman said Tuesday the exchange would wait
for Drexel to settle the sweeping criminal securities fraud case
brought against it by the federal government before deciding what
sanctions if any to impose on the investment firm.
   Drexel agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay $650
million in penalties to settle its criminal case, which involved
alleged securities law violations stemming from the insider trading
scandals linked to now-jailed speculator Ivan Boesky.
   NYSE Chairman John J. Phelan Jr. said in an interview with the
Wall Street Journal that the settlement represents ``the biggest
failure of the (supervisory) system in the history of the financial
markets.''
   Phelan did not specify what sanctions were being considered, but
the exchange could fine, censure or suspend the firm and employees.
Issues before the exchange include whether top Drexel officials
failed to supervise employees properly.
   ``The last thing we want to do is come out looking like a wimp,''
Phelan said.
   Phelan made comments last week that raised doubts about whether
the NYSE would follow up on the federal sanctions being levied
against Drexel by the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
Justice Department.
   ``I'm not sure what purpose we would serve by adding any more to
that since the commission could have done everything including bar
(Drexel) as a broker-dealer,'' he told a group of reporters.
   Exchange officials maintain Phelan was not indicating the
exchange would not take action against Drexel.
   ``We have not yet determined what action if any the New York
Stock Exchange will take in the Drexel case,'' spokesman Rich
Torrenzano said. ``That determination will be made in the coming
weeks and months once federal regulators have completed all of their
deliberations and settlements.''
   A federal judge last week approved a civil settlement between the
SEC and the firm that places Drexel under strict supervision for
three years. Approval of the separate criminal settlement is pending
before another judge.
   Once that happens, Phelan said, ``we will go full blast.''
   ``The exchange has been talking to the SEC and has been examining
the SEC's proposed settlement,'' Torrenzano said.
   In 1985, the NYSE fined E.F. Hutton &amp; Co. $400,000 and censured
its president and chief financial officer for failing to supervise
the firm properly after Hutton pleaded guilty to federal mail and
wire fraud charges in a wide-ranging check-kiting scheme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-27 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Higher; Gasoline Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil and wholesale heating oil futures
continued to climb Tuesday, carried aloft largely by technical
buying.
   Gasoline futures prices pulled back.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate rose 23 cents to $20.48 per 42-gallon barrel. The
contract closed with a gain of 54 cents on Monday.
   Contracts for later delivery of WTI, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude, posted similar increases.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the July
contract for No.2 heating oil gained 0.88 cent to settle at 50.53
cents a gallon, adding to Monday's gain of 0.16 cent. Other contract
months of heating oil also finished higher.
   The contact for July delivery of unleaded gasoline edged down by
0.01 cent to 63.68 a gallon after Monday's surge of 0.77 cent.
Contracts for August, September and October gasoline delivery also
declined.
   Mary L. Haskins, a vice president at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said the rally in the crude futures pits was sustained with the help
of technical buying.
   Buying bred more buying as traders pushed the price of crude
futures past thresholds considered significant.
   ``The technicals have pointed upward now for a week and a half
and until we get some dramatic bearish news the market will keep
moving higher,'' said Haskins. ``The market looks like it wants to
head to $21 or $21.20 (a barrel) in the near term.''
   The market also has been getting a lift this week from news that
some OPEC members intend to curb crude production.
   Published reports have said Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates,
two chronic overproducers, will reduce their output levels closer to
the amount desired by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
   Kuwait previously had rejected its OPEC-imposed production
ceiling and set its own quota.
   Both Kuwait and the UAE reportedly now plan to scale back
production levels but keep them above the amount mandated by the oil
cartel at a meeting in Vienna, Austria, earlier this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
