<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Time Bjt   06-27 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time, Bjt,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time-Paramount Struggle Could Affect Future of Friendly Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that Time Inc. has rejected a sweetened $12.2
billion takeover bid from Paramount Communications Inc., the focus
of their struggle is shifting to Delaware, not only the fate of Time
but also the future of friendly mergers may be decided in court.
   Time is fighting to preserve a planned merger with Warner
Communications Inc. _ and it is that merger on which the takeover
fight may turn.
   Paramount, after announcing its original $175-a-share, or $10.7
billion, bid on June 6, filed suit in Chancery Court in Delaware to
stop the transaction that would create Time-Warner Inc., the world's
largest communications concern. All three companies are incorporated
in Delaware.
   Time and Warner first proposed their friendly stock-for-stock
merger transaction in March. After Paramount began its pursuit of
Time, the merger agreement was amended and Time began a $14 billion
tender offer for its would-be partner.
   Paramount contends Time opened up a Pandora's box _ effectively
putting itself up for sale _ by announcing it would merge with
Warner.
   Under Delaware law, if a company has put itself up for sale, its
board is required to seek the maximum value for shareholders. If the
court rules that Time in fact put itself up for sale, the company's
board could be hard-pressed to reject Paramount's $200-a-share bid,
which is $74 higher than the price at which Time stock traded before
Paramount announced its bid.
   Time rejected Paramount's latest offer Monday, calling it
financially inadequate and subject to too many conditions. Time
contends that its merger plans with Warner did not put the company
up for sale, meaning its board does not have to consider higher bids.
   A court hearing on the issue is scheduled for July 11.
   The case has generating much interest among companies and
corporate lawyers because of the possibility it could set a
precedent affecting mergers between other companies.
   Many U.S. companies _ including about half of the Fortune 500 _
are incorporated in Delaware to take advantage of state tax laws
aimed at attracting business. As a result, business law decisions by
the Delaware courts _ which have established a strong reputation in
dealing with corporate issues _ widely are seen as important
precedents.
   Harry DeAngelo, a professor at the University of Michigan, said a
ruling in Paramount's favor could place a chill on friendly mergers
such as the original Time-Warner deal in favor of cash buyouts.
   ``You would want to make sure, if you didn't want to be acquired,
you were clearly the buyer'' in a deal, he said.
   But DeAngelo said a ruling favoring Paramount would not
necessarily mean an end to mergers such as the Time-Warner deal, and
predicted that corporate lawyers would find a way to structure
mergers in accordance with such a ruling.
   ``You'll see a period of uncertainty and people will tread
carefully as they get used to the new rules,'' he said.
   Donald Margotta, a professor at Northeastern University in
Boston, said that even if the court rules in Paramount's favor, a
merger transaction structured differently from the Time-Warner
proposal might not be affected.
   However, Margotta said, a ruling against Time is ``going to make
it much more difficult'' to accomplish a friendly stock-swap merger.
   Many observers decline to predict how the court might rule, but
some believe the fight will come down to a question of money and
Paramount's $200-a-share bid.
   ``The legal issue is nothing more than a subterfuge for some
basic economic conflicts,'' said Alfred Rappaport, a professor at
Northwestern University's Kellogg Graduate School of Management.
   Time stock has fluctuated since Paramount announced its bid, as
traders try to forecast how the court might rule and how the
struggle will end. On Tuesday, Time stock slipped 75 cents to
$163.25 a share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Warner was up 25 cents to $59.12{ a share, and Paramount was down
87{ cents to $60.37{ a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
