<FIRST>u f AM-MerrillLynch     06-27 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Merrill Lynch,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merrill Lynch Moving Some Jobs to Jersey City; New York City Miffed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. has decided to move about
2,600 jobs to Jersey City, N.J., and New York City officials said
they have decided to remove the firm as senior underwriter for
future municipal bond offerings.
   ``They are now a New Jersey company,'' said George Arzt,
spokesman for Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   However, the giant financial services firm, which currently
employs about 13,000 people in New York City, said its headquarters
would remain in Manhattan.
   ``Even after this move, the firm will continue to be the largest
employer among securities firms in New York,'' said Fred Yager, a
Merrill Lynch spokesman.
   Merrill Lynch's planned 43-story office tower is to be built on
the site of a former Colgate-Palmolive factory in Jersey City. The
site, still owned by Colgate, is being developed by the Linpro Co.
of Berwyn, Pa.
   ``We were very disappointed to learn today of Merrill Lynch's
decision to relocate 2,600 of their employees from Manhattan to New
Jersey,'' Koch and city Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin said at a
late afternoon news conference at City Hall. ``Accordingly, we have
agreed to remove Merrill Lynch as the senior managing underwriter
for any future New York City bond offerings.''
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas H. Kean issued a statement in Trenton,
N.J., applauding the firm's decision to move to the Hudson County
waterfront.
   ``By combining all the standard incentives available at the
state, county and local levels, we are able to construct a winning
financial package,'' he said.
   New Jersey is hoping Merrill Lynch's relocation will energize its
efforts to redevelop the waterfront area.
   Rick Cohen, director of the Department of Housing and Economic
Development in Jersey City, called Merrill Lynch's announcement ``a
major shot in the arm to the waterfront development.''
   ``It's been a little slow and this is really going to perk up the
waterfront and stimulate other tenant leases,'' he said.
   Details of the financial package offered to Merrill Lynch by New
Jersey were not available.
   Terms of the Linpro-Merrill Lynch agreement were not disclosed,
but the move is expected to reduce Merrill Lynch's annual occupancy
costs for the operations by 50 percent.
   ``We don't disclose those costs, but I can tell you the reduction
is 50 percent,'' said Yager.
   The jobs being relocated to Jersey City involve back-office
administrative functions in support of Merrill Lynch's consumer
investment and capital markets businesses.
   Separately, Merrill Lynch said it will relocate approximately 500
data center employees to Manhattan and Staten Island from Boston and
from Somerset and New Brunswick, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
